{"title_page": "Bentley University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Bentley University\n| image = Bentley University seal.svg\n| image_size = 150\n| established = 1917\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| motto = ''Paratus'' (Latin)\n| mottoeng = Prepared\n| endowment = $241.9 million (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2016 Market Value of Endowment Assets and Percentage Change* in Endowment Market Value from FY2015 to FY2016|website=NACUBO.org|access-date=12 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| president = [[Alison Davis-Blake]]\n| city = [[Waltham, Massachusetts|Waltham]]\n| state = [[Massachusetts]]\n| country = United States\n{{coord|42.387633|-71.22061|display=title,inline}}\n| faculty = 484\n| students = 5,602\n| undergrad = 4,203 (2017\u20132018)\n| postgrad = 1,405\n| doctoral = 40\n| campus = [[Suburb]]an<br />163 acres\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division II]]\n| nickname = [[Bentley Falcons|Falcons]]\n| former_names = Bentley School of Accounting and Finance<br/>(1917\u20131971)<br/>Bentley College<br/>(1971\u20132008)\n| colors = Blue, White<ref>{{cite manual|url=http://www.bentley.edu/offices/marketing-communications/bentley-brand/brand-assets#Color%20Palette |title=The Bentley Brand Book|publisher=Bentley University |accessdate=2015-11-20}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#0075BE}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| mascot = [[Flex the Falcon]]\n| website = {{URL|www.bentley.edu}}\n| logo = Bentley University logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250\n}}\n\n'''Bentley University''' is a [[private university]] focused on business and located in [[Waltham, Massachusetts]]. Founded in 1917 as a school of accounting and finance in Boston's [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]] neighborhood, Bentley moved to Waltham in 1968.  Bentley awards bachelor of science degrees in 14 business fields and bachelor of arts degrees in 11 arts and sciences disciplines, offering 36 minors spanning both arts and science and business disciplines. The graduate school emphasizes the impact of technology on business practice, and offers PhD programs in Business and Accountancy, the Bentley MBA with 16 areas of concentration, an integrated MS+MBA, seven Master of Science degrees, several graduate certificate programs and custom executive education programs.\n\nBentley's athletic teams compete in [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] (except for men's hockey, which competes in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]]) and are known collectively as the [[Bentley Falcons]]. They compete in the [[Northeast-10 Conference]].\n\n== History ==\nBentley University was founded in 1917 as the Bentley School of Accounting and Finance by [[Harry C. Bentley]], who served as the school's president until 1953. In 1961, the college was accredited to confer four-year Bachelor of Science degrees under President Morison, who moved the college from its [[Boylston Street]] address in Boston to its current-day location in Waltham, Massachusetts. Gregory H. Adamian, a major driving force in the college's development, became the fourth president in 1970. Under his guidance, the college became accredited to confer four-year Bachelor of Arts degrees in 1971 and graduate degrees in 1973. During this time, the school also changed its name to Bentley College. In 2002, Bentley College opened up a campus in the Middle Eastern country of [[Bahrain]] in partnership with the Bahrain Institute of Banking and Finance. The college was accredited to confer its first doctoral degrees in the fields of business and accountancy in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2163 |title=We're sorry, but we can not find the page you're looking for. &#124; Bentley University Newsroom |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207010231/http://bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2163 |archivedate=February 7, 2008 }}</ref> A main fixture of the campus, The Bentley Library, underwent a sweeping renovation in 2006 during which time the school's logo was changed to showcase the clock tower that sits atop the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2258 |title=We're sorry, but we can not find the page you're looking for. &#124; Bentley University Newsroom |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207010613/http://bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2258 |archivedate=February 7, 2008 }}</ref> One year later, [[Gloria Cordes Larson]], a former state and federal government official and Boston-based lawyer, became the first female president of Bentley College. In 2008, the school changed its name to Bentley University after being authorized by the state board of higher education to do so.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2008/10/bentley_college.html|title= Bentley morphs from college into university |publisher=Boston.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-30}}</ref> [[Alison Davis-Blake]], the former dean of the Carlson School of Management at the University of Minnesota and of the Ross School of Business at the University of Michigan, became Bentley's eighth president in July 2018.\n\n==Campus==\nIn 1968, Bentley moved from downtown Boston to Waltham, Massachusetts to accommodate an increasing number of students. The first buildings on the Waltham campus were built between 1965 and 1968. Today, the campus stretches across {{convert|163|acre|km2}} of land, and is accessible by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]] [[554 (MBTA bus)|554 bus]].\n\nBentley University's campus is divided into three parts: Upper Campus, Lower Campus, and North Campus.\n\n===Upper Campus===\n\nUpper Campus contains most of the school's academic buildings and all of its classrooms. It is located on the North side of Beaver Street. Upper campus also contains all three freshman dorms, a few upperclassman dorms, and the University's bookstore.\n\n===Lower Campus===\n\nLower Campus contains more upperclassman housing, the Dana Athletic Center, and the Multi-Purpose Arena. It is connected to upper campus via a bridge over Beaver Street. It is located on the South side of Beaver Street.\n\n[[Image:Bentley College Library.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Bentley Library]]\n\n===North Campus===\n\nNorth Campus is located a half-mile north of the main entrance to Upper Campus on Forest Street. Transportation to and from North Campus is provided via shuttle bus. North Campus contains only residence hall buildings named: A, B, C and D. Residence halls A and B were opened in 2005 while C and D were opened in 2007, making North Campus the most recent addition to Bentley's housing facilities. Each building has 3 floors and includes an elevator and 2 stairwells. Originally, North Campus was intended to be graduate student housing, but due to the sharp growth of enrollment it is occupied mostly by undergraduates.\n\n==Rankings==\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Regional University North Rankings \u2013 Best Colleges \u2013 Education \u2013 US News and World Report |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/bentley-university-2124|magazine=U.S. News and World Report|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> \n* Top 10 Master's Universities in the North 2018 - Ranked 2nd\n* Top 50 Undergraduate Business Programs 2017\n\n''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Undergraduate Business Schools 2013|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-03-20/best-undergraduate-business-schools-2013|publisher=Businessweek.com|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n*Best Undergraduate Business Schools 2016 - Ranked 10th\n\n[[The Princeton Review|''Princeton Review'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings?rankings=best-career-services|title=Best Colleges for Career Services {{!}} The Princeton Review|website=www.princetonreview.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref>\n\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2019 - Ranked 1st\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2018 - Ranked 1st\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2017 - Ranked 2nd\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2016 - Ranked 1st\n\n==Graduate programs==\n\n===McCallum Graduate School of Business===\nBentley's McCallum Graduate School of Business offers two master's degrees, the [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) and the [[Master of Science]].  It also has PhD programs.\n\n===Bentley User Experience Degree (San Francisco)===\nThe Masters of Human Factors in Information Design program is offered on the West Coast.\n\nStudents take four of the required courses in California, five courses online, and the 10th course at Bentley's \"User Experience Center\".\n\nThe program was designed to accommodate the busy schedules of tech professionals and to draw students from a wide geographic area. Each course is delivered in an executive format: three class meetings on Friday, Saturday and Sunday, followed by four weeks of faculty-monitored virtual teamwork, and closing with a Friday/Saturday meeting in the classroom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admissions.bentley.edu/graduate/masters-in-human-factors|title=Masters in Human Factors - Bentley University Graduate School of Business|website=admissions.bentley.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Academic organizations ===\nBentley is home to a number of academic organizations. Its Fed Challenge team won the National Fed Challenge in 2010,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/other20101130a.htm|title=Federal Reserve Board - Federal Reserve announces college Fed Challenge winners|website=www.federalreserve.gov|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> and won second place in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/other20121127a.htm|title=Federal Reserve Board - Federal Reserve announces college Fed Challenge winners|website=www.federalreserve.gov|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> The university is also home to the Bentley Investment Group, a student-run organization charged with managing a portion of the university's endowment fund.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/article/bentley-entrusts-part-of-endowment-with-students-cm17940|title=Bentley University Entrusts Students With Part Of Endowment|date=2010-03-02|work=NASDAQ.com|access-date=2018-12-19|language=en-us}}</ref> Other notable academic organizations include the Bentley Marketing Association, TAMID, and the Bentley Real Estate Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bentleyspeak.com/how-to-get-involved}}</ref>\n\n===Club sports===\nIn addition to the intercollegiate and intramural programs, the university offers a number of club sports for students to take part in.  These clubs are operated within the Student Activities department, and are financially supported by the student's activity fees. Club Sports include: cheerleading, dance team, men's rugby, women's rugby, men's ultimate frisbee (2014 [[USA Ultimate]] Div-III Champions), women's ultimate frisbee, men's volleyball, men's hockey, women's hockey, and sailing.\n\n===Campus media===\n* ''The Vanguard'': student-produced weekly on-campus newspaper<ref name=vanguard>{{cite web |title=The Vanguard: Official Student Newspaper of Bentley University |url=http://bentleyvanguard.com/ |work=The Vanguard |accessdate=31 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121051007/http://bentleyvanguard.com/ |archivedate=2012-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n* ''Bentley TV'': student-produced TV station broadcasting on channel 45 on campus.<ref>[http://www.bentleytelevision.com/about-bstv/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091020190630/http://www.bentleytelevision.com/about-bstv/|date=October 20, 2009}}</ref>\n* ''Piecework'': student-produced annual literary magazine\n* ''Bentley Observer'': staff-produced quarterly magazine for alumni<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bentley.edu/alumni/publications/index.cfm |title=Publications : Bentley |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208002114/http://www.bentley.edu/alumni/publications/index.cfm |archivedate=2011-02-08 }}</ref>\n* ''WBTY - Radio Bentley'': on-campus radio station, operating at 105.3 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]\n* ''Falcon Records (Massachusetts)'': an independent record label focused on promoted local artists in Boston and providing free and entertaining music to consumers\n*''Fusio'': an academic research journal published by the university's honors program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bentley.edu/academics/honors-program/fusio|title=Fusio: The Bentley Undergraduate Research Journal {{!}} Bentley University|website=www.bentley.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n===Fraternities and sororities===\nThere are currently seven recognized men's fraternities at Bentley University: [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]], Alpha Gamma Pi, [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]], [[Kappa Sigma]], [[Sigma Chi]], Sigma Gamma Delta, and [[Sigma Pi]]. Six chapters are inter/national and are governed by the [[North American Interfraternity Conference]]. Two of the men's organizations are local groups which means that Bentley University is the only institution that houses these chapters.\n\nThere currently are four recognized women's sororities at Bentley University: [[Alpha Phi]], [[Gamma Phi Beta]], [[Kappa Delta]],  and [[Phi Sigma Sigma]]. These chapters are governed by the [[National Panhellenic Conference]] or the National Association of Latina/Latino Fraternal Organizations, Inc.\n\nIn the 2017-2018 academic year, Greek organizations raised over $60,000 through philanthropic events held on campus.\n\nThere are also two business fraternities on campus, [[Alpha Kappa Psi]] and [[Delta Sigma Pi]]. They are co-ed, and hold numerous professional events throughout the year.\n\nThere is a chapter of [[Alpha Psi Omega]] National Theater Honors Society, which performs a fall musical and a spring play every year.\n\nThere is one co-ed service fraternity, [[Alpha Phi Omega]], chartered 2018, which provides its members opportunities to volunteer through a variety of community service events and fundraisers.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{see also|Bentley Falcons|Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey}}\n[[File:Bentley Falcons logo.svg|thumb|100px|Bentley Falcons logo.]]\n[[File:Dana Gym 015-web.jpg|thumb|left|Bentley University Basketball Gymnasium located in the Dana Athletic Center]]\nBentley's mascot is [[Flex the Falcon]]. The university has 23 men's and women's varsity teams. All of the teams compete in the [[Northeast-10 Conference]] at the [[NCAA Division II]] level, with the exception of the men's hockey program, which was one of the original six founding teams of [[Atlantic Hockey]] at the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] level.\n\nBentley is also home to one of the best rugby programs in the Northeast winning two national Division III titles as well as winning the 2008 Beast of the East tournament.\n\nIn 2001, the Bentley Field Hockey team won the NCAA Division II national championship.\n\nIn 2012, the Bentley Men's Cross Country team finished 26th in the nation at Division II XC Nationals. In 2015, the Bentley Men's Cross Country team qualified for the NCAA Division II Cross Country Championships and finished 30th in the nation.\n\nAfter beating [[Saint Michael's College]] by a score of 85-65 on February 23, 2008, the Bentley University Men's Basketball team set the record for the longest regular season winning streak in Division II history.  Additionally, Bentley has men's, women's, and co-ed intramural programs for the fall, winter, and spring semesters.\n\nThe Bentley Women's Basketball team completed the 2013-2014 season with a 35-0 record, winning the NCAA Division II National Championship.\n\nThe Bentley Men's Ultimate Frisbee team won [[USA Ultimate]]'s Division III College Championship in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usaultimate.org/news/bentley-wins-mens-division-at-the-2014-d-iii-college-championships/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140804/http://www.usaultimate.org/news/bentley-wins-mens-division-at-the-2014-d-iii-college-championships/ |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref>\n\nBentley is the #2 ranked school among all NCAA Division II colleges and universities in U.S., according to [[Next College Student Athlete]]'s 2018 NCSA Power Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-2-colleges |title= NCAA Division 2 Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> The NCSA Power Rankings recognize the best colleges and universities in the U.S. for student-athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges |title= NCSA Power Rankings 2018, Top Athletic and academic universities |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> NCSA ranked Bentley Football #1 for DII schools and #63 overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-football-colleges |title= Top Football Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> Among all DII schools, Bentley also ranked #1 in Men's and Women's Lacrosse; #2 in Men's and Women's Basketball, Men's and Women's Soccer, Men's and Women's Swimming, Men's and Women's Tennis, Men's Golf, Women's Field Hockey, Women's Volleyball, Softball, and Baseball; and #3 in Men's and Women's Track and Field. Bentley University Men's Ice Hockey ranked #20 among NCAA DI schools<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-1-ice-hockey-colleges |title= Division 1 Men's Ice Hockey Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n.\n\n==Bentley Arena==\nThe [[Bentley Arena]] is a multi-purpose ice hockey arena on the campus of Bentley University in Waltham, Massachusetts. It is home to the Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey program, replacing the previous facility, the John A. Ryan Arena. The first hockey game was on February 16, 2018 with Bentley taking on Army West Point. The seating capacity for hockey games is 2,207.<ref>[[Bentley Arena]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe 76,000 square foot facility was designed by Architectural Resources Cambridge and built by Suffolk Construction. Ground broke on the Arena in the summer of 2016, and was completed in February 2018.\n\nIn May 2018, the Arena was awarded an LEED Platinum rating, the highest possible rating for sustainability, according to the U.S. Green Building Council.\n\nSince opening, the arena has hosted various events, such as Bentley's annual Spring Day concert, the Back to Bentley concert, and the Spring Comedy Show.\n\nMusical artists such as [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], [[Vince Staples]], and [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] have performed at the arena, as have comedians such as [[Nick Offerman]] and [[Wayne Brady]].\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n* [[George J. Bates]], former member of the United States House of Representatives from the state of Massachusetts\n* [[Mackenzy Bernadeau]], '08, professional [[American football|football]] player who was last with the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] organization; drafted 250th overall in [[2008 NFL Draft]] by the [[Carolina Panthers]].\n* [[Gailanne Cariddi]], former member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives\n* [[C.C. Chapman]], '96, American author and marketing consultant\n* [[Marcelo Claure]], '93, President and CEO of [[Sprint Corporation]] and founder of [[Brightstar Corporation|Brightstar Corp.]]<ref>{{cite web |title= Hispanic Business, June 2007. \"Hispanic Business, Shining Through\" Derek Reveron |url= http://www.hispanicbusiness.com/2007/5/31/shining_through.htm |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140222042353/http://www.hispanicbusiness.com/2007/5/31/shining_through.htm |archivedate= February 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[Patricia Courtney]], infielder in [[All-American Girls Professional Baseball League]]\n* [[Arthur T. Demoulas]], CEO of Demoulas Supermarkets (Market Basket)\n* [[William C. Freda]] '74, Vice Chairman and Senior Partner (Retired), [[Deloitte]] LLP, New York, NY\n* [[Brian Hammel]], '75, former Bentley basketball player and coach who was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the third round of the [[1975 NBA Draft]]\n* [[Gail Huff]], '84, Broadcast journalist for [[WJLA-TV]] and the wife of [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]], former U.S. Senator from Massachusetts\n* [[Michael Jingozian]], '91, founder and CEO, AngelVision, TV producer, and former presidential candidate for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n* [[Robert B. Kennedy]], American politician\n* [[Edward J. King]], '53, professional football player with Buffalo Bills and Baltimore Colts 1948-1950; Governor of Massachusetts 1979-1983\n* [[David Krikorian]], former candidate for Ohio's 2nd congressional district\n* [[William Landergan]], member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives from 1935\u20131937 \n* [[Todd J. Leach]], MBA '85, Chancellor of the [[University System of New Hampshire]]\n* [[Jay Leno]], former host of [[The Tonight Show]]; attended for one semester.\n* [[Christopher P. Lynch]], MBA '91, American Venture Capitalist and entrepreneur\n* [[Mike Malin (television personality)|Mike Malin]], recurring contestant on U.S. reality television series [[Big Brother (franchise)|Big Brother]], most notably winning [[Big Brother 7 (U.S.)]]\n* [[Mike Mangini]], '85, drummer of [[Dream Theater]]; former drum teacher at [[Berklee College of Music]]\n* [[David Pakman]], [[MBA]], host of [[The David Pakman Show]]\n* [[Frederick G. Payne]], '25, former [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Maine]] and the [[List of Governors of Maine|60th]] [[Governor of Maine]]<ref>{{cite dictionary\n|url= http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=p000150|title= PAYNE, Frederick George, (1904 - 1978)|dictionary= Biographical Directory of the United States Congress\n|accessdate= September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Perri]], head coach of men's basketball at [[Southern New Hampshire University]], previously [[LIU Brooklyn]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snhupenmen.com/sports/mbkb/2017-18/releases/20180605i2av5f|title=Jack Perri Selected as Head Men's Basketball Coach|date=5 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Edward J. Powers]], former president and general manager of the [[Boston Garden]]\n* [[Ryan Soderquist]], '00, current head coach of [[Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey]] team and all-time points and goals leader\n* [[Charles Taylor (Liberia)|Charles Taylor]], '77, 22nd President of [[Liberia]]; convicted war criminal\n* [[Jason Westrol]], '10, former Bentley basketball player who last played for the [[Limburg United]] of the [[Belgian Basketball League]]\n\n===Faculty and staff===\n*[[Gregory H. Adamian]], Bentley's fourth president\n*[[Harry C. Bentley]], founder and first president of Bentley\n*[[Gloria Cordes Larson]], Bentley's seventh president\n* [[Alison Davis-Blake]], Bentley's eighth and current president\n* [[Mohammad Javad Abdolmohammadi]], John E. Rhodes Professor of Accounting at Bentley since 1988\n*[[Amir Aczel]], lecturer in [[mathematics]] and the [[history of mathematics]] and science, as well as an author of popular books on mathematics and science\n*[[Selin Sayek B\u00f6ke]], Turkish politician who worked in Bentley's Economics department as an assistant professor\n* [[Steve Marchena]], guitar instructor-in-residence at Bentley\n* [[Scott Sumner]], noted economist and professor\n* [[Ryan Soderquist]], current head coach of the [[Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey]] team\n* [[Barbara Stevens (basketball)|Barbara Stevens]], longtime women's basketball coach and [[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]] member<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/04/sports/kevin-garnett-kobe-bryant-headline-2020-basketball-hall-fame-class-bentleys-barbara-stevens-inducted/|title=Kevin Garnett, Kobe Bryant headline 2020 Basketball Hall of Fame class; Bentley\u2019s Barbara Stevens elected with six others - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Hammel]], former Bentley men's basketball coach and [[Milwaukee Bucks]] draft pick in 1975\n* [[Peter Simonini]], former Bentley men's soccer coach\n* [[Bobby Shuttleworth]], former Bentley men's soccer assistant coach and [[New England Revolution]] player\n* [[Jack Perri]], head coach of men's basketball at [[Southern New Hampshire University]], previously [[LIU Brooklyn]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snhupenmen.com/sports/mbkb/2017-18/releases/20180605i2av5f|title=Jack Perri Selected as Head Men's Basketball Coach|date=5 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Hal Kopp]], Bentley football coach from 1972\u20131975\n* [[Jack Regan (American football)|Jack Regan]], Bentley football coach from 1976-1978\n* [[Peter Yetten]], Bentley football coach from 1979\u20132008\n* [[Robert Connors]], former offensive coordinator for the Bentley football team\n* [[Thom Boerman]], Bentley football coach from 2009\u20132013\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bentley.edu/}}\n* [http://www.bentleyfalcons.com/ Bentley Athletics website]\n\n{{Northeast-10 Conference navbox}}\n{{Atlantic Hockey}}\n{{Colleges and universities in metropolitan Boston}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bentley University| ]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Waltham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Bentley University\n| image = Bentley University seal.svg\n| image_size = 150\n| established = 1917\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| motto = ''Paratus'' (Latin)\n| mottoeng = Prepared\n| endowment = $241.9 million (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2016 Market Value of Endowment Assets and Percentage Change* in Endowment Market Value from FY2015 to FY2016|website=NACUBO.org|access-date=12 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| president = [[Alison Davis-Blake]]\n| city = [[Waltham, Massachusetts|Waltham]]\n| state = [[Massachusetts]]\n| country = United States\n{{coord|42.387633|-71.22061|display=title,inline}}\n| faculty = 484\n| students = 5,602\n| undergrad = 4,203 (2017\u20132018)\n| postgrad = 1,405\n| doctoral = 40\n| campus = [[Suburb]]an<br />163 acres\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division II]]\n| nickname = [[Bentley Falcons|Falcons]]\n| former_names = Bentley School of Accounting and Finance<br/>(1917\u20131971)<br/>Bentley College<br/>(1971\u20132008)\n| colors = Blue, White<ref>{{cite manual|url=http://www.bentley.edu/offices/marketing-communications/bentley-brand/brand-assets#Color%20Palette |title=The Bentley Brand Book|publisher=Bentley University |accessdate=2015-11-20}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#0075BE}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| mascot = [[Flex the Falcon]]\n| website = {{URL|www.bentley.edu}}\n| logo = Bentley University logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250\n}}\n\n'''Bentley University''' is a [[private university]] focused on business and located in [[Waltham, Massachusetts]]. Founded in 1917 as a school of accounting and finance in Boston's [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]] neighborhood, Bentley moved to Waltham in 1968.  Bentley awards bachelor of science degrees in 14 business fields and bachelor of arts degrees in 11 arts and sciences disciplines, offering 36 minors spanning both arts and science and business disciplines. The graduate school emphasizes the impact of technology on business practice, and offers PhD programs in Business and Accountancy, the Bentley MBA with 16 areas of concentration, an integrated MS+MBA, seven Master of Science degrees, several graduate certificate programs and custom executive education programs.\n\nBentley's athletic teams compete in [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] (except for men's hockey, which competes in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]]) and are known collectively as the [[Bentley Falcons]]. They compete in the [[Northeast-10 Conference]].\n\n== History ==\nBentley University was founded in 1917 as the Bentley School of Accounting and Finance by [[Harry C. Bentley]], who served as the school's president until 1953. In 1961, the college was accredited to confer four-year Bachelor of Science degrees under President Morison, who moved the college from its [[Boylston Street]] address in Boston to its current-day location in Waltham, Massachusetts. Gregory H. Adamian, a major driving force in the college's development, became the fourth president in 1970. Under his guidance, the college became accredited to confer four-year Bachelor of Arts degrees in 1971 and graduate degrees in 1973. During this time, the school also changed its name to Bentley College. In 2002, Bentley College opened up a campus in the Middle Eastern country of [[Bahrain]] in partnership with the Bahrain Institute of Banking and Finance. The college was accredited to confer its first doctoral degrees in the fields of business and accountancy in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2163 |title=We're sorry, but we can not find the page you're looking for. &#124; Bentley University Newsroom |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207010231/http://bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2163 |archivedate=February 7, 2008 }}</ref> A main fixture of the campus, The Bentley Library, underwent a sweeping renovation in 2006 during which time the school's logo was changed to showcase the clock tower that sits atop the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2258 |title=We're sorry, but we can not find the page you're looking for. &#124; Bentley University Newsroom |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207010613/http://bentley.edu/news-events/pr_view.cfm?id=2258 |archivedate=February 7, 2008 }}</ref> One year later, [[Gloria Cordes Larson]], a former state and federal government official and Boston-based lawyer, became the first female president of Bentley College. In 2008, the school changed its name to Bentley University after being authorized by the state board of higher education to do so.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2008/10/bentley_college.html|title= Bentley morphs from college into university |publisher=Boston.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-30}}</ref> [[Alison Davis-Blake]], the former dean of the Carlson School of Management at the University of Minnesota and of the Ross School of Business at the University of Michigan, became Bentley's eighth president in July 2018.\n\n==Campus==\nIn 1968, Bentley moved from downtown Boston to Waltham, Massachusetts to accommodate an increasing number of students. The first buildings on the Waltham campus were built between 1965 and 1968. Today, the campus stretches across {{convert|163|acre|km2}} of land, and is accessible by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]] [[554 (MBTA bus)|554 bus]].\n\nBentley University's campus is divided into three parts: Upper Campus, Lower Campus, and North Campus.\n\n===Upper Campus===\n\nUpper Campus contains most of the school's academic buildings and all of its classrooms. It is located on the North side of Beaver Street. Upper campus also contains all three freshman dorms, a few upperclassman dorms, and the University's bookstore.\n\n===Lower Campus===\n\nLower Campus contains more upperclassman housing, the Dana Athletic Center, and the Multi-Purpose Arena. It is connected to upper campus via a bridge over Beaver Street. It is located on the South side of Beaver Street.\n\n[[Image:Bentley College Library.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Bentley Library]]\n\n===North Campus===\n\nNorth Campus is located a half-mile north of the main entrance to Upper Campus on Forest Street. Transportation to and from North Campus is provided via shuttle bus. North Campus contains only residence hall buildings named: A, B, C and D. Residence halls A and B were opened in 2005 while C and D were opened in 2007, making North Campus the most recent addition to Bentley's housing facilities. Each building has 3 floors and includes an elevator and 2 stairwells. Originally, North Campus was intended to be graduate student housing, but due to the sharp growth of enrollment it is occupied mostly by undergraduates.\n\n==Rankings==\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Regional University North Rankings \u2013 Best Colleges \u2013 Education \u2013 US News and World Report |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/bentley-university-2124|magazine=U.S. News and World Report|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> \n* Top 10 Master's Universities in the North 2018 - Ranked 2nd\n* Top 50 Undergraduate Business Programs 2017\n\n''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Undergraduate Business Schools 2013|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-03-20/best-undergraduate-business-schools-2013|publisher=Businessweek.com|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n*Best Undergraduate Business Schools 2016 - Ranked 10th\n\n[[The Princeton Review|''Princeton Review'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings?rankings=best-career-services|title=Best Colleges for Career Services {{!}} The Princeton Review|website=www.princetonreview.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref>\n\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2019 - Ranked 1st\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2018 - Ranked 1st\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2017 - Ranked 2nd\n* Best Colleges for Career Services 2016 - Ranked 1st\n\n==Graduate programs==\n\n===McCallum Graduate School of Business===\nBentley's McCallum Graduate School of Business offers two master's degrees, the [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) and the [[Master of Science]].  It also has PhD programs.\n\n===Bentley User Experience Degree (San Francisco)===\nThe Masters of Human Factors in Information Design program is offered on the West Coast.\n\nStudents take four of the required courses in California, five courses online, and the 10th course at Bentley's \"User Experience Center\".\n\nThe program was designed to accommodate the busy schedules of tech professionals and to draw students from a wide geographic area. Each course is delivered in an executive format: three class meetings on Friday, Saturday and Sunday, followed by four weeks of faculty-monitored virtual teamwork, and closing with a Friday/Saturday meeting in the classroom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admissions.bentley.edu/graduate/masters-in-human-factors|title=Masters in Human Factors - Bentley University Graduate School of Business|website=admissions.bentley.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Academic organizations ===\nBentley is home to a number of academic organizations. Its Fed Challenge team won the National Fed Challenge in 2010,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/other20101130a.htm|title=Federal Reserve Board - Federal Reserve announces college Fed Challenge winners|website=www.federalreserve.gov|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> and won second place in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/other20121127a.htm|title=Federal Reserve Board - Federal Reserve announces college Fed Challenge winners|website=www.federalreserve.gov|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> The university is also home to the Bentley Investment Group, a student-run organization charged with managing a portion of the university's endowment fund.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/article/bentley-entrusts-part-of-endowment-with-students-cm17940|title=Bentley University Entrusts Students With Part Of Endowment|date=2010-03-02|work=NASDAQ.com|access-date=2018-12-19|language=en-us}}</ref> Other notable academic organizations include the Bentley Marketing Association, TAMID, and the Bentley Real Estate Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bentleyspeak.com/how-to-get-involved}}</ref>\n\n===Club sports===\nIn addition to the intercollegiate and intramural programs, the university offers a number of club sports for students to take part in.  These clubs are operated within the Student Activities department, and are financially supported by the student's activity fees. Club Sports include: cheerleading, dance team, men's rugby, women's rugby, men's ultimate frisbee (2014 [[USA Ultimate]] Div-III Champions), women's ultimate frisbee, men's volleyball, men's hockey, women's hockey, and sailing.\n\n===Campus media===\n* ''The Vanguard'': student-produced weekly on-campus newspaper<ref name=vanguard>{{cite web |title=The Vanguard: Official Student Newspaper of Bentley University |url=http://bentleyvanguard.com/ |work=The Vanguard |accessdate=31 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121051007/http://bentleyvanguard.com/ |archivedate=2012-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n* ''Bentley TV'': student-produced TV station broadcasting on channel 45 on campus.<ref>[http://www.bentleytelevision.com/about-bstv/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091020190630/http://www.bentleytelevision.com/about-bstv/|date=October 20, 2009}}</ref>\n* ''Piecework'': student-produced annual literary magazine\n* ''Bentley Observer'': staff-produced quarterly magazine for alumni<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bentley.edu/alumni/publications/index.cfm |title=Publications : Bentley |publisher=Bentley.edu |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208002114/http://www.bentley.edu/alumni/publications/index.cfm |archivedate=2011-02-08 }}</ref>\n* ''WBTY - Radio Bentley'': on-campus radio station, operating at 105.3 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]\n* ''Falcon Records (Massachusetts)'': an independent record label focused on promoted local artists in Boston and providing free and entertaining music to consumers\n*''Fusio'': an academic research journal published by the university's honors program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bentley.edu/academics/honors-program/fusio|title=Fusio: The Bentley Undergraduate Research Journal {{!}} Bentley University|website=www.bentley.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n===Fraternities and sororities===\nThere are currently seven recognized men's fraternities at Bentley University: [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]], Alpha Gamma Pi, [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]], [[Kappa Sigma]], [[Sigma Chi]], Sigma Gamma Delta, and [[Sigma Pi]]. Six chapters are inter/national and are governed by the [[North American Interfraternity Conference]]. Two of the men's organizations are local groups which means that Bentley University is the only institution that houses these chapters.\n\nThere currently are four recognized women's sororities at Bentley University: [[Alpha Phi]], [[Gamma Phi Beta]], [[Kappa Delta]],  and [[Phi Sigma Sigma]]. These chapters are governed by the [[National Panhellenic Conference]] or the National Association of Latina/Latino Fraternal Organizations, Inc.\n\nIn the 2017-2018 academic year, Greek organizations raised over $60,000 through philanthropic events held on campus.\n\nThere are also two business fraternities on campus, [[Alpha Kappa Psi]] and [[Delta Sigma Pi]]. They are co-ed, and hold numerous professional events throughout the year.\n\nThere is a chapter of [[Alpha Psi Omega]] National Theater Honors Society, which performs a fall musical and a spring play every year.\n\nThere is one co-ed service fraternity, [[Alpha Phi Omega]], chartered 2018, which provides its members opportunities to volunteer through a variety of community service events and fundraisers.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{see also|Bentley Falcons|Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey}}\n[[File:Bentley Falcons logo.svg|thumb|100px|Bentley Falcons logo.]]\n[[File:Dana Gym 015-web.jpg|thumb|left|Bentley University Basketball Gymnasium located in the Dana Athletic Center]]\nBentley's mascot is [[Flex the Falcon]]. The university has 23 men's and women's varsity teams. All of the teams compete in the [[Northeast-10 Conference]] at the [[NCAA Division II]] level, with the exception of the men's hockey program, which was one of the original six founding teams of [[Atlantic Hockey]] at the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] level.\n\nBentley is also home to one of the best rugby programs in the Northeast winning two national Division III titles as well as winning the 2008 Beast of the East tournament.\n\nIn 2001, the Bentley Field Hockey team won the NCAA Division II national championship.\n\nIn 2012, the Bentley Men's Cross Country team finished 26th in the nation at Division II XC Nationals. In 2015, the Bentley Men's Cross Country team qualified for the NCAA Division II Cross Country Championships and finished 30th in the nation.\n\nAfter beating [[Saint Michael's College]] by a score of 85-65 on February 23, 2008, the Bentley University Men's Basketball team set the record for the longest regular season winning streak in Division II history.  Additionally, Bentley has men's, women's, and co-ed intramural programs for the fall, winter, and spring semesters.\n\nThe Bentley Women's Basketball team completed the 2013-2014 season with a 35-0 record, winning the NCAA Division II National Championship.\n\nThe Bentley Men's Ultimate Frisbee team won [[USA Ultimate]]'s Division III College Championship in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usaultimate.org/news/bentley-wins-mens-division-at-the-2014-d-iii-college-championships/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140804/http://www.usaultimate.org/news/bentley-wins-mens-division-at-the-2014-d-iii-college-championships/ |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref>\n\nBentley is the #2 ranked school among all NCAA Division II colleges and universities in U.S., according to [[Next College Student Athlete]]'s 2018 NCSA Power Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-2-colleges |title= NCAA Division 2 Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> The NCSA Power Rankings recognize the best colleges and universities in the U.S. for student-athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges |title= NCSA Power Rankings 2018, Top Athletic and academic universities |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> NCSA ranked Bentley Football #1 for DII schools and #63 overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-football-colleges |title= Top Football Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> Among all DII schools, Bentley also ranked #1 in Men's and Women's Lacrosse; #2 in Men's and Women's Basketball, Men's and Women's Soccer, Men's and Women's Swimming, Men's and Women's Tennis, Men's Golf, Women's Field Hockey, Women's Volleyball, Softball, and Baseball; and #3 in Men's and Women's Track and Field. Bentley University Men's Ice Hockey ranked #20 among NCAA DI schools<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-1-ice-hockey-colleges |title= Division 1 Men's Ice Hockey Colleges, NCSA Power Rankings 2018 |publisher=NCSA College Power Ranking Report |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n.\n\n==Bentley Arena==\nThe [[Bentley Arena]] is a multi-purpose ice hockey arena on the campus of Bentley University in Waltham, Massachusetts. It is home to the Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey program, replacing the previous facility, the John A. Ryan Arena. The first hockey game was on February 16, 2018 with Bentley taking on Army West Point. The seating capacity for hockey games is 2,207.<ref>[[Bentley Arena]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe 76,000 square foot facility was designed by Architectural Resources Cambridge and built by Suffolk Construction. Ground broke on the Arena in the summer of 2016, and was completed in February 2018.\n\nIn May 2018, the Arena was awarded an LEED Platinum rating, the highest possible rating for sustainability, according to the U.S. Green Building Council.\n\nSince opening, the arena has hosted various events, such as Bentley's annual Spring Day concert, the Back to Bentley concert, and the Spring Comedy Show.\n\nMusical artists such as [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], [[Vince Staples]], and [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] have performed at the arena, as have comedians such as [[Nick Offerman]] and [[Wayne Brady]].\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n* [[George J. Bates]], former member of the United States House of Representatives from the state of Massachusetts\n* [[Mackenzy Bernadeau]], '08, professional [[American football|football]] player who was last with the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] organization; drafted 250th overall in [[2008 NFL Draft]] by the [[Carolina Panthers]].\n* [[Gailanne Cariddi]], former member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives\n* [[C.C. Chapman]], '96, American author and marketing consultant\n* [[Marcelo Claure]], '93, President and CEO of [[Sprint Corporation]] and founder of [[Brightstar Corporation|Brightstar Corp.]]<ref>{{cite web |title= Hispanic Business, June 2007. \"Hispanic Business, Shining Through\" Derek Reveron |url= http://www.hispanicbusiness.com/2007/5/31/shining_through.htm |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140222042353/http://www.hispanicbusiness.com/2007/5/31/shining_through.htm |archivedate= February 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[Patricia Courtney]], infielder in [[All-American Girls Professional Baseball League]]\n* [[Arthur T. Demoulas]], CEO of Demoulas Supermarkets (Market Basket)\n* [[William C. Freda]] '74, Vice Chairman and Senior Partner (Retired), [[Deloitte]] LLP, New York, NY\n* [[Brian Hammel]], '75, former Bentley basketball player and coach who was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the third round of the [[1975 NBA Draft]]\n* [[Gail Huff]], '84, Broadcast journalist for [[WJLA-TV]] and the wife of [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]], former U.S. Senator from Massachusetts\n* [[Michael Jingozian]], '91, founder and CEO, AngelVision, TV producer, and former presidential candidate for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n* [[Robert B. Kennedy]], American politician\n* [[Edward J. King]], '53, professional football player with Buffalo Bills and Baltimore Colts 1948-1950; Governor of Massachusetts 1979-1983\n* [[David Krikorian]], former candidate for Ohio's 2nd congressional district\n* [[William Landergan]], member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives from 1935\u20131937 \n* [[Todd J. Leach]], MBA '85, Chancellor of the [[University System of New Hampshire]]\n* [[Jay Leno]], former host of [[The Tonight Show]]; attended for one semester.\n* [[Christopher P. Lynch]], MBA '91, American Venture Capitalist and entrepreneur\n* [[Mike Malin (television personality)|Mike Malin]], recurring contestant on U.S. reality television series [[Big Brother (franchise)|Big Brother]], most notably winning [[Big Brother 7 (U.S.)]]\n* [[Mike Mangini]], '85, drummer of [[Dream Theater]]; former drum teacher at [[Berklee College of Music]]\n* [[David Pakman]], [[MBA]], host of [[The David Pakman Show]]\n* [[Frederick G. Payne]], '25, former [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Maine]] and the [[List of Governors of Maine|60th]] [[Governor of Maine]]<ref>{{cite dictionary\n|url= http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=p000150|title= PAYNE, Frederick George, (1904 - 1978)|dictionary= Biographical Directory of the United States Congress\n|accessdate= September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Perri]], head coach of men's basketball at [[Southern New Hampshire University]], previously [[LIU Brooklyn]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snhupenmen.com/sports/mbkb/2017-18/releases/20180605i2av5f|title=Jack Perri Selected as Head Men's Basketball Coach|date=5 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Edward J. Powers]], former president and general manager of the [[Boston Garden]]\n* [[Ryan Soderquist]], '00, current head coach of [[Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey]] team and all-time points and goals leader\n* [[Charles Taylor (Liberia)|Charles Taylor]], '77, 22nd President of [[Liberia]]; convicted war criminal\n* [[Jason Westrol]], '10, former Bentley basketball player who last played for the [[Limburg United]] of the [[Belgian Basketball League]]\n\n===Faculty and staff===\n*[[Gregory H. Adamian]], Bentley's fourth president\n*[[Harry C. Bentley]], founder and first president of Bentley\n*[[Gloria Cordes Larson]], Bentley's seventh president\n* [[Alison Davis-Blake]], Bentley's eighth and current president\n* [[Mohammad Javad Abdolmohammadi]], John E. Rhodes Professor of Accounting at Bentley since 1988\n*[[Amir Aczel]], lecturer in [[mathematics]] and the [[history of mathematics]] and science, as well as an author of popular books on mathematics and science\n*[[Selin Sayek B\u00f6ke]], Turkish politician who worked in Bentley's Economics department as an assistant professor\n* [[Steve Marchena]], guitar instructor-in-residence at Bentley\n* [[Scott Sumner]], noted economist and professor\n* [[Ryan Soderquist]], current head coach of the [[Bentley Falcons men's ice hockey]] team\n* [[Barbara Stevens (basketball)|Barbara Stevens]], longtime women's basketball coach and [[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]] finalist\n* [[Brian Hammel]], former Bentley men's basketball coach and [[Milwaukee Bucks]] draft pick in 1975\n* [[Peter Simonini]], former Bentley men's soccer coach\n* [[Bobby Shuttleworth]], former Bentley men's soccer assistant coach and [[New England Revolution]] player\n* [[Jack Perri]], head coach of men's basketball at [[Southern New Hampshire University]], previously [[LIU Brooklyn]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snhupenmen.com/sports/mbkb/2017-18/releases/20180605i2av5f|title=Jack Perri Selected as Head Men's Basketball Coach|date=5 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Hal Kopp]], Bentley football coach from 1972\u20131975\n* [[Jack Regan (American football)|Jack Regan]], Bentley football coach from 1976-1978\n* [[Peter Yetten]], Bentley football coach from 1979\u20132008\n* [[Robert Connors]], former offensive coordinator for the Bentley football team\n* [[Thom Boerman]], Bentley football coach from 2009\u20132013\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bentley.edu/}}\n* [http://www.bentleyfalcons.com/ Bentley Athletics website]\n\n{{Northeast-10 Conference navbox}}\n{{Atlantic Hockey}}\n{{Colleges and universities in metropolitan Boston}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bentley University| ]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Waltham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Amtoastintolerant", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated Barbara Stevens' status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bentley_University"}
{"title_page": "Lufussa", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name     = Lufussa\n| image    = Planta el\u00e9ctrica Pavana II.jpg\n| image_caption  = The Pavana II power plant, second of the three Lufussa power plants.\n| logo     = \n| type     = \n| foundation       = 1994\n| location         = [[Honduras]]\n| key_people       = Luis Kafie {{small|(Founder)}}\n| area_served      = [[Honduras]]\n| industry         = [[Electric Utility|Electric Utilities]]\n| products         = [[Electric power generation|Electricity generation]], [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] and [[Electricity distribution|distribution]]\n| homepage         = [http://lufussa.com/en/homepage/ lufussa.com] (English homepage)\n}}\n'''Luz y Fuerza de San Lorenzo Sociedad An\u00f3nima''' (English: '''San Lorenzo Light and Power Company'''; commonly known as '''Lufussa''') is a [[Honduras|Honduran]] energy company created in 1994, shortly after the country allowed the development of privately-owned [[power plant]]s. Founded by brothers [[Schucry Kafie]], Luis Kafie, and Eduardo Kafie,<ref name=\"Picacho\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2017/03/21/lufussa-dona-vivero-zona-picacho/|title=Lufussa dona vivero en zona de \u201cEl Picacho\u201d|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> it is one of a small number of substantial energy providers in the country, with an installed capacity of 390 MW from three main power plants.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/en/our-company/|title=Lufussa: About Us|access-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=92429|title=Qui\u00e9nes apoyan al gobierno ileg\u00edtimo de Roberto Micheletti|first=Decio|last=Machado|publisher=[[Rebelion.org|Rebeli\u00f3n]]|date=September 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Planta el\u00e9ctrica Pavana II en Honduras.jpg|thumb|Interior view of Lufussa owned Pavana II power plant.]]\nIn 1993, during the government of [[Rafael Leonardo Callejas]], Honduras made it possible for private enterprises to provide thermal energy to the country. In 1994, Lufussa was established as a power company, and [[Carlos Roberto Reina]] approved a 10-year contract and Lufussa.<ref name=\"PSIH\">Public-Private Infrastructure Advisory Facility, ''Private Solutions for Infrastructure in Honduras'' (2003), p. 106-107.</ref> In 1997, Lufussa was one of three firms out of thirteen prequalified competitors to bid on a 60-megawatt government contract, ultimately splitting the contract with another Honduran energy company, EMCE.<ref name=\"PSIH\"/> New contracts awarded via public tender were signed under the administrations of [[Carlos Roberto Flores|Carlos Flores]] and [[Ricardo Maduro]]. In March 2014, Lufussa negotiated an agreement with the Honduran government to provide 30 megawatts of energy to the country over the next two years, with production from the power plants involved being exclusive to Honduras.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/03/06/gobierno-logra-acuerdo-de-30-megas-con-lufussa/|title=Gobierno logra acuerdo de 30 megas con Lufussa|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=March 6, 2014|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041646/http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/03/06/gobierno-logra-acuerdo-de-30-megas-con-lufussa/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, an International Conclave organized by the Colegio de Ingenieros Mecanicos, El\u00e9tricos y Qu\u00edmicos de Honduras visited regional Lufussa power plants to examine thermoelectric power technology in Honduras.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/ingenieros-latinoamericanos-visitan-plantas-de-lufussa-y-enerbasa/|title=Ingenieros latinoamericanos visitan plantas de Lufussa y Enerbasa|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=October 14, 2015|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922195244/http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/ingenieros-latinoamericanos-visitan-plantas-de-lufussa-y-enerbasa/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> {{As of|June 2017}}, Lufussa claims an installed capacity of 390 MW, in three plants - Pavana I (39.5 MW, completed 1995), II (82 MW, completed 1999), and III (267.4 MW, completed August 2004).<ref name=\"about\"/> Pavana III represents the largest private investment in the country.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n==Charitable activities==\n===Environmental protection===\n[[File:Luis and Christopher Kafie among environmental government members in Punta Condenga, turtle liberation.jpg|thumb|Lufussa founder Luis Kafie and Christopher Kafie among environmental government members in Punta Condenga, turtle liberation.]]\nLufussa supports a variety of charitable activities in Honduras. In terms of [[environmental protection]], Lufussa is involved in the Honduran national [[reforestation]] program,<ref name=\"MW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/lufussa-delivered-200000-trees-to-the-honduran-government-2016-10-04-131604949|title=Lufussa Delivered 200000 Trees to the Honduran Government|publisher=[[MarketWatch]]|date=October 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Processo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.hn/mas-noticias/item/131910-plantaran-un-millon-de-arboles-donados-por-lufussa.html|title=Lufussa entreg\u00f3 200,000 \u00e1rboles al Gobierno de Honduras|publisher=Proceso Digital|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Arboles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/09/13/lufussa-ha-cumplido-meta-producir-200000-arboles-este-ano/|title=Lufussa ha cumplido su meta de producir 200,000 \u00e1rboles este a\u00f1o|date=September 12, 2016|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810071549/http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/09/13/lufussa-ha-cumplido-meta-producir-200000-arboles-este-ano/|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[sea turtle]] conservation in the [[Gulf of Fonseca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiohrn.hn/l/noticias/serna-liberar%C3%A1-40-mil-tortugas-golfinas-en-la-zona-sur|title=Serna liberar\u00e1 40 mil tortugas golfinas en la zona sur|date=14 November 2014|publisher=Radio HRN|access-date=5 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040339/http://www.radiohrn.hn/l/noticias/serna-liberar%C3%A1-40-mil-tortugas-golfinas-en-la-zona-sur|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Turtles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/lufussa-apoya-proyecto-de-conservacion-de-la-tortuga-golfina/|title=Lufussa apoya proyecto de conservaci\u00f3n de la tortuga golfina|date=October 14, 2015|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040322/http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/lufussa-apoya-proyecto-de-conservacion-de-la-tortuga-golfina/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Padilla\">{{cite web|url=http://fundahrse.org/boletines/14-por-quinto-ano-lufussa-continua-con-el-proyecto-de-conservacion-y-proteccion-de-la-tortuga-golfina-2/|title=14 Por quinto a\u00f1o Lufussa contin\u00faa con el proyecto de conservaci\u00f3n y protecci\u00f3n de la tortuga golfina|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Hondure\u00f1a de Responsabilidad Social Empresarial|website=fundahrse.org|access-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Lufussa delivered 200,000 trees to the Honduran government as part of the reforestation program.<ref name=\"MW\"/><ref name=\"Processo\"/><ref name=\"Arboles\"/> In June 2017, Lufussa entered into an agreement with the Mayor of [[El Picacho (Panama)|El Picacho]] to deliver a new municipal nursery to the city, with the necessary resources to produce an additional 112,000 trees per year for reforestation in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2017/06/01/casi-listo-vivero-construye-lufussa-la-amdc-picacho/|title=Casi listo vivero que construye Lufussa para la AMDC en El Picacho|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> With respect to sea turtle preservation, Lufussa has supported this effort since 2011, and in 2016 the company delivered 675 meals to volunteers securing sea turtle eggs at camps in Punta Rat\u00f3n, Boca de Rio Viejo, Cede\u00f1o and Carretales.<ref name=\"Padilla\"/>\n\n===Community development===\nIn support of the Honduran community, Lufussa supports construction efforts in cooperation with the non-governmental organization Honduras Outreach Inc. (HOI),<ref name=\"Hondudiario\">{{cite web|url=http://hondudiario.com/2017/07/27/lufussa-y-honduras-outreach-llevan-ayuda-social-a-comunidades-de-la-zona-sur/|title=Lufussa y Honduras Outreach llevan ayuda social a comunidades de la zona sur|publisher=Hondudiario|date=July 27, 2017}}</ref> and a medical brigade to serve low-income people in northern Honduras, also including the Choluteca region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/09/03/brigada-medica-estadounidense-para-atender-a-personas-de-escasos-recursos-economicos-en-la-zona-norte-de-honduras/|title=Brigada m\u00e9dica estadounidense para atender a personas de escasos recursos econ\u00f3micos en la zona norte de Honduras|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=September 3, 2014|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032507/http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/09/03/brigada-medica-estadounidense-para-atender-a-personas-de-escasos-recursos-economicos-en-la-zona-norte-de-honduras/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Brigade\">{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/es/lufussa-lleva-brigadas-medicas-varias-comunidades-choluteca/|title=Lufussa lleva brigadas m\u00e9dicas a varias comunidades de Choluteca|date=29 June 2016|publisher=Lufussa}}</ref> In 2016, Lufussa's volunteer force and HOI brigaders built 2 latrines and 3 bathrooms, installed concrete floors in 7 houses, and installed 2 eco-stoves in the communities of Guanacastillo, El Tambor and Aguacaliente, in the south of the country.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> They also provided more than 50 complete sets of bedding to the Regional Hospital del Sur.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> Since 2011, Lufussa has also carried out \"Healthy Homes\" Program in the communities of El Tambor, Guanacastillo, Pavana Center and Aguacaliente, remodeling 167 homes by changing earth floors to finely finished cement, thereby reducing incidences of disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://criterio.hn/2016/04/12/lufussa-inicia-segunda-etapa-programa-pisos-saludables-la-zona-sur-del-pais/|title=Lufussa inicia segunda etapa de su Programa \u201cPisos Saludables\u201d en la zona sur del pa\u00eds|date=April 12, 2016|publisher=Criterio.hn|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032835/http://criterio.hn/2016/04/12/lufussa-inicia-segunda-etapa-programa-pisos-saludables-la-zona-sur-del-pais/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The medical brigade, with the participation of 29 American doctors acting in coordination with Lufussa volunteers, has treated hundreds of people in Pavana Centro and Guanacastillo.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> Since December 2014, Lufussa has organized an annual city [[marathon]] in [[Choluteca, Choluteca|Choluteca]], Honduras, with the objective of raising funds for charitable causes in the area. In 2014, 150 thousand lempiras were raised for the Hospital del Sur, and in 2015 a donation of 175 thousand lempiras was made to the \"Enrique Elizalde\" School for the Blind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/12/01/exito-marathon-color-2016-lufussa/|title=Un \u00e9xito marath\u00f3n Color 2016 de Lufussa|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043510/http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/12/01/exito-marathon-color-2016-lufussa/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/es/exito-maraton-color-2016-lufussa/|title=Todo un \u00e9xito Marat\u00f3n Color 2016 de Lufussa|publisher=Lufussa|date=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Energy companies of Honduras]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name     = Lufussa\n| image    = Planta el\u00e9ctrica Pavana II.jpg\n| image_caption  = The Pavana II power plant, second of the three Lufussa power plants.\n| logo     = \n| type     = \n| foundation       = 1994\n| location         = [[Honduras]]\n| key_people       = Luis Kafie {{small|(Founder)}}\n| area_served      = [[Honduras]]\n| industry         = [[Electric Utility|Electric Utilities]]\n| products         = [[Electric power generation|Electricity generation]], [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] and [[Electricity distribution|distribution]]\n| homepage         = [http://lufussa.com/en/homepage/ lufussa.com] (English homepage)\n}}\n'''Luz y Fuerza de San Lorenzo Sociedad An\u00f3nima''' (English: '''San Lorenzo Light and Power Company'''; commonly known as '''Lufussa''') is a [[Honduras|Honduran]] energy company created in 1994, shortly after the country allowed the development of privately-owned [[power plant]]s. Founded by brothers [[Schucry Kafie]], Luis Kafie, and Eduardo Kafie,<ref name=\"Picacho\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2017/03/21/lufussa-dona-vivero-zona-picacho/|title=Lufussa dona vivero en zona de \u201cEl Picacho\u201d|publisher=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> it is one of a small number of substantial energy providers in the country, with an installed capacity of 390 MW from three main power plants.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/en/our-company/|title=Lufussa: About Us|access-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=92429|title=Qui\u00e9nes apoyan al gobierno ileg\u00edtimo de Roberto Micheletti|first=Decio|last=Machado|publisher=[[Rebelion.org|Rebeli\u00f3n]]|date=September 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Planta el\u00e9ctrica Pavana II en Honduras.jpg|thumb|Interior view of Lufussa owned Pavana II power plant.]]\nIn 1993, during the government of [[Rafael Leonardo Callejas]], Honduras made it possible for private enterprises to provide thermal energy to the country. In 1994, Lufussa was established as a power company, and [[Carlos Roberto Reina]] approved a 10-year contract and Lufussa.<ref name=\"PSIH\">Public-Private Infrastructure Advisory Facility, ''Private Solutions for Infrastructure in Honduras'' (2003), p. 106-107.</ref> In 1997, Lufussa was one of three firms out of thirteen prequalified competitors to bid on a 60-megawatt government contract, ultimately splitting the contract with another Honduran energy company, EMCE.<ref name=\"PSIH\"/> New contracts awarded via public tender were signed under the administrations of [[Carlos Roberto Flores|Carlos Flores]] and [[Ricardo Maduro]]. In March 2014, Lufussa negotiated an agreement with the Honduran government to provide 30 megawatts of energy to the country over the next two years, with production from the power plants involved being exclusive to Honduras.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/03/06/gobierno-logra-acuerdo-de-30-megas-con-lufussa/|title=Gobierno logra acuerdo de 30 megas con Lufussa|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|date=March 6, 2014|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041646/http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/03/06/gobierno-logra-acuerdo-de-30-megas-con-lufussa/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, an International Conclave organized by the Colegio de Ingenieros Mecanicos, El\u00e9tricos y Qu\u00edmicos de Honduras visited regional Lufussa power plants to examine thermoelectric power technology in Honduras.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/ingenieros-latinoamericanos-visitan-plantas-de-lufussa-y-enerbasa/|title=Ingenieros latinoamericanos visitan plantas de Lufussa y Enerbasa|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|date=October 14, 2015|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922195244/http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/ingenieros-latinoamericanos-visitan-plantas-de-lufussa-y-enerbasa/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> {{As of|June 2017}}, Lufussa claims an installed capacity of 390 MW, in three plants - Pavana I (39.5 MW, completed 1995), II (82 MW, completed 1999), and III (267.4 MW, completed August 2004).<ref name=\"about\"/> Pavana III represents the largest private investment in the country.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n==Charitable activities==\n===Environmental protection===\n[[File:Luis and Christopher Kafie among environmental government members in Punta Condenga, turtle liberation.jpg|thumb|Lufussa founder Luis Kafie and Christopher Kafie among environmental government members in Punta Condenga, turtle liberation.]]\nLufussa supports a variety of charitable activities in Honduras. In terms of [[environmental protection]], Lufussa is involved in the Honduran national [[reforestation]] program,<ref name=\"MW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/lufussa-delivered-200000-trees-to-the-honduran-government-2016-10-04-131604949|title=Lufussa Delivered 200000 Trees to the Honduran Government|publisher=[[MarketWatch]]|date=October 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Processo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.hn/mas-noticias/item/131910-plantaran-un-millon-de-arboles-donados-por-lufussa.html|title=Lufussa entreg\u00f3 200,000 \u00e1rboles al Gobierno de Honduras|publisher=Proceso Digital|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Arboles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/09/13/lufussa-ha-cumplido-meta-producir-200000-arboles-este-ano/|title=Lufussa ha cumplido su meta de producir 200,000 \u00e1rboles este a\u00f1o|date=September 12, 2016|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810071549/http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/09/13/lufussa-ha-cumplido-meta-producir-200000-arboles-este-ano/|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[sea turtle]] conservation in the [[Gulf of Fonseca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiohrn.hn/l/noticias/serna-liberar%C3%A1-40-mil-tortugas-golfinas-en-la-zona-sur|title=Serna liberar\u00e1 40 mil tortugas golfinas en la zona sur|date=14 November 2014|publisher=Radio HRN|access-date=5 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040339/http://www.radiohrn.hn/l/noticias/serna-liberar%C3%A1-40-mil-tortugas-golfinas-en-la-zona-sur|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Turtles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/lufussa-apoya-proyecto-de-conservacion-de-la-tortuga-golfina/|title=Lufussa apoya proyecto de conservaci\u00f3n de la tortuga golfina|date=October 14, 2015|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040322/http://www.latribuna.hn/2015/10/14/lufussa-apoya-proyecto-de-conservacion-de-la-tortuga-golfina/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Padilla\">{{cite web|url=http://fundahrse.org/boletines/14-por-quinto-ano-lufussa-continua-con-el-proyecto-de-conservacion-y-proteccion-de-la-tortuga-golfina-2/|title=14 Por quinto a\u00f1o Lufussa contin\u00faa con el proyecto de conservaci\u00f3n y protecci\u00f3n de la tortuga golfina|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Hondure\u00f1a de Responsabilidad Social Empresarial|website=fundahrse.org|access-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Lufussa delivered 200,000 trees to the Honduran government as part of the reforestation program.<ref name=\"MW\"/><ref name=\"Processo\"/><ref name=\"Arboles\"/> In June 2017, Lufussa entered into an agreement with the Mayor of [[El Picacho (Panama)|El Picacho]] to deliver a new municipal nursery to the city, with the necessary resources to produce an additional 112,000 trees per year for reforestation in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2017/06/01/casi-listo-vivero-construye-lufussa-la-amdc-picacho/|title=Casi listo vivero que construye Lufussa para la AMDC en El Picacho|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> With respect to sea turtle preservation, Lufussa has supported this effort since 2011, and in 2016 the company delivered 675 meals to volunteers securing sea turtle eggs at camps in Punta Rat\u00f3n, Boca de Rio Viejo, Cede\u00f1o and Carretales.<ref name=\"Padilla\"/>\n\n===Community development===\nIn support of the Honduran community, Lufussa supports construction efforts in cooperation with the non-governmental organization Honduras Outreach Inc. (HOI),<ref name=\"Hondudiario\">{{cite web|url=http://hondudiario.com/2017/07/27/lufussa-y-honduras-outreach-llevan-ayuda-social-a-comunidades-de-la-zona-sur/|title=Lufussa y Honduras Outreach llevan ayuda social a comunidades de la zona sur|publisher=Hondudiario|date=July 27, 2017}}</ref> and a medical brigade to serve low-income people in northern Honduras, also including the Choluteca region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/09/03/brigada-medica-estadounidense-para-atender-a-personas-de-escasos-recursos-economicos-en-la-zona-norte-de-honduras/|title=Brigada m\u00e9dica estadounidense para atender a personas de escasos recursos econ\u00f3micos en la zona norte de Honduras|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|date=September 3, 2014|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032507/http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/09/03/brigada-medica-estadounidense-para-atender-a-personas-de-escasos-recursos-economicos-en-la-zona-norte-de-honduras/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Brigade\">{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/es/lufussa-lleva-brigadas-medicas-varias-comunidades-choluteca/|title=Lufussa lleva brigadas m\u00e9dicas a varias comunidades de Choluteca|date=29 June 2016|publisher=Lufussa}}</ref> In 2016, Lufussa's volunteer force and HOI brigaders built 2 latrines and 3 bathrooms, installed concrete floors in 7 houses, and installed 2 eco-stoves in the communities of Guanacastillo, El Tambor and Aguacaliente, in the south of the country.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> They also provided more than 50 complete sets of bedding to the Regional Hospital del Sur.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> Since 2011, Lufussa has also carried out \"Healthy Homes\" Program in the communities of El Tambor, Guanacastillo, Pavana Center and Aguacaliente, remodeling 167 homes by changing earth floors to finely finished cement, thereby reducing incidences of disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://criterio.hn/2016/04/12/lufussa-inicia-segunda-etapa-programa-pisos-saludables-la-zona-sur-del-pais/|title=Lufussa inicia segunda etapa de su Programa \u201cPisos Saludables\u201d en la zona sur del pa\u00eds|date=April 12, 2016|publisher=Criterio.hn|access-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032835/http://criterio.hn/2016/04/12/lufussa-inicia-segunda-etapa-programa-pisos-saludables-la-zona-sur-del-pais/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The medical brigade, with the participation of 29 American doctors acting in coordination with Lufussa volunteers, has treated hundreds of people in Pavana Centro and Guanacastillo.<ref name=\"Brigade\"/> Since December 2014, Lufussa has organized an annual city [[marathon]] in [[Choluteca, Choluteca|Choluteca]], Honduras, with the objective of raising funds for charitable causes in the area. In 2014, 150 thousand lempiras were raised for the Hospital del Sur, and in 2015 a donation of 175 thousand lempiras was made to the \"Enrique Elizalde\" School for the Blind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/12/01/exito-marathon-color-2016-lufussa/|title=Un \u00e9xito marath\u00f3n Color 2016 de Lufussa|publisher=[[La Tribuna]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043510/http://www.latribuna.hn/2016/12/01/exito-marathon-color-2016-lufussa/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lufussa.com/es/exito-maraton-color-2016-lufussa/|title=Todo un \u00e9xito Marat\u00f3n Color 2016 de Lufussa|publisher=Lufussa|date=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Energy companies of Honduras]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-La Tribuna", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lufussa"}
