gest unbeaten runs:\n** 33 games from February 1973 to April 1974\n** 23 games from November 2011 to May 2012\n** 21 games from June 1998 to January 1999\n** 21 games from February 2017 to September 2017\n* Best season starter:\n** 4 games won in [[1973\u201374 Honduran Liga Nacional|1973\u201374]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Motagua por igualar el mejor arranque de su historia en Liga Nacional |url=https://www.diez.hn/liganacionaldehonduras/1255233-498/motagua-upn-torneo-clausura-liga-nacional-honduras |website=Diez.hn |publisher=[[La Prensa (Honduras)|Diario Diez]] |accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n* Longest winning streak:\n** 8 games from October to December 2018\n* Longest win-less run:\n** 13 games from April 2001 to July 2001\n\n==Others==\n* Highest home attendance: 37,371 v [[C.D. Olimpia]], 26 August 2000\n* Highest away attendance: 38,256 v [[C.D. Olimpia]], 17 December 2006\n* Lowest home attendance: 0 v [[C.D. Olimpia]], 23 December 2017\n* Lowest away attendance: 0 v [[C.D. Olimpia]], 20 December 2017; 0 v [[C.D.S. Vida]], 3 March 2019; 0 v [[Real C.D. Espa\u00f1a]], 4 August 2019; 0 v [[C.D.S. Vida]], 24 August 2019\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{F.C. Motagua}}\n\n[[Category:F.C. Motagua|Records and statistics]]\n[[Category:Honduran football club statistics|Motagua]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-La Tribuna", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_F.C._Motagua_records_and_statistics"}
{"title_page": "Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name             = Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award\n| subheader        = Named in honor of writer [[Ram\u00f3n Rosa]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| description      = Authors whose work has national and international significance\n| sponsor          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Executive branch of the government of Honduras|Executive branch]]\n* {{ill|Secretariat of Public Education (Honduras)|es|Secretar\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (Honduras)|lt=Secretariat of Public Education}}\n* [[Secretary of State for Culture, Arts and Sports|Secretariat of Culture, Arts, and Sports]]\n}}\n| location         = [[Presidential Palace of Honduras|Presidential Palace]]\n| country          = Honduras\n| presenter        = \n| year             = 1951\n| year2            = \n| website          = \n| holder           = \n}}\nThe '''Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award''' ({{lang-es|'''Premio Nacional de Literatura Ram\u00f3n Rosa'''}}) is an honor presented annually by the [[President of Honduras]].\n\n==History==\nNamed in honor of the liberal writer and government minister [[Ram\u00f3n Rosa]] (1848\u20131993), the award was created by legislative decree in 1949, and first given in 1951, to [[Luis Andr\u00e9s Z\u00faniga]].<ref name=creaci\u00f3n>{{Cite journal |url=https://presencia.unah.edu.hn/noticias/se-cumplieron-67-anos-de-la-creacion-del-premio-nacional-de-literatura-ramon-rosa/ |title=Se cumplieron 67 a\u00f1os de la creaci\u00f3n del Premio Nacional de Literatura Ram\u00f3n Rosa |trans-title=67th Anniversary of the Creation of the Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award |first=Katherine Eunice |last=Ramirez Rivas |journal=Presencia Universitaria |publisher=[[Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de Honduras]] |language=Spanish |date=2016-04-29 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> It was restructured by Legislative Decree no. 100 on 11 October 1967.<ref name=Danl\u00ed>{{Cite news |url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2013/01/13/danli-y-sus-premios-nacionales-de-literatura/ |title=Danl\u00ed y sus Premios Nacionales de Literatura |first=Carlos Ernesto |last=Molina Barahona |work=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2013-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022225051/http://www.latribuna.hn/2013/01/13/danli-y-sus-premios-nacionales-de-literatura/ |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIt is presented annually at the [[Presidential Palace of Honduras|Presidential Palace]] to a writer whose work has national and international significance.<ref name=Fausto>{{Cite web |url=https://www.presidencia.gob.hn/index.php/sala-de-prensa/6590-gobierno-entrega-los-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura |title=Gobierno entrega los Premios Nacionales de Ciencia, Arte y Literatura |trans-title=Government Presents National Awards for Science, Art, and Literature |publisher=[[Executive branch of the government of Honduras]] |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2019-11-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127201727/https://www.presidencia.gob.hn/index.php/sala-de-prensa/6590-gobierno-entrega-los-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura |archive-date=2019-11-27 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn some years, the ceremony has been held at the {{ill|Manuel Bonilla National Theater|es|Teatro Nacional Manuel Bonilla}} in [[Tegucigalpa]].<ref name=entrega2017>{{Cite news |url=https://hondudiario.com/2018/05/17/gobierno-entrega-premios-nacionales-de-arte-ciencia-y-literatura/ |title=Gobierno entrega premios Nacionales de Arte, Ciencia y Literatura |trans-title=Government Presents National Awards for Art, Science, and Literature |work=Hondudiario |language=Spanish |date=2018-05-17 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> It is sponsored by the Civic Projects and Emergency Education Unit of the {{ill|Secretariat of Public Education (Honduras)|es|Secretar\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (Honduras)|lt=Secretariat of Public Education}}, the [[Executive branch of the government of Honduras|executive branch]], and the [[Secretary of State for Culture, Arts and Sports|Secretariat of Culture, Arts, and Sports]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oei.es/historico/cultura2/honduras/cap11.htm |title=Premios y Concursos En Honduras |trans-title=Awards and Contests in Honduras |publisher=[[Organization of Ibero-American States]] |language=Spanish |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Categories==\nThe Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award is given for works in the areas of poetry, novel, short story, oratory and narration, journalism, drama, essay, criticism, and any other genre that contributes to the development of letters and culture in the country.<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n\nThere is only one winner per year; awards are not given in the individual categories.\n\n==Winners==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 1951: [[Luis Andr\u00e9s Z\u00faniga]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1953: [[Guillermo Bustillo]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1954: [[Claudio Barrera]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1955: [[Jacobo C\u00e1rcamo]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.latribuna.hn/2017/02/12/premio-nacional-literatura-ramon-rosa-2016/ |title=Premio Nacional de Literatura 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa' 2016 |first=Juan Fernando |last=\u00c1vila P. |work=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2017-02-12 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1956: [[Daniel La\u00ednez]]\n* 1959: [[Jacobo C\u00e1rcamo]]\n* 1963: [[Guillermo Bustillo]]\n* 1968: [[Argentina D\u00edaz Lozano]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1970: [[Clementina Su\u00e1rez]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1971: [[Medardo Mej\u00eda]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1972: [[Roberto Sosa (poet)|Roberto Sosa]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1975: [[Julio Escoto]]\n* 1976: {{ill|V\u00edctor C\u00e1ceres Lara|es}}\n* 1979: [[\u00d3scar Acosta]]\n* 1980: {{ill|\u00d3scar Armando Flores Midence|es}}\n* 1981: [[Pompeyo del Valle]]\n* 1983: {{ill|Antonio Jos\u00e9 Rivas|es}}\n* 1984: [[Miguel R. Ortega]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.asale.org/noticias/miguel-r-ortega-premio-ramon-amaya-amador |title=Miguel R. Ortega, Premio Ram\u00f3n Amaya Amador |publisher=[[Association of Academies of the Spanish Language]] |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1986: [[Hern\u00e1n de Jes\u00fas C\u00e1rcamo Tercero]]\n* 1987: {{ill|Felipe Elvir Rojas|es}}<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 1989: {{ill|Helen Uma\u00f1a|es}}\n* 1990: {{ill|Santos Juarez Fiallos|es}}\n* 1991: [[Roberto Castillo (philosopher)|Roberto Castillo]]\n* 1992: [[Eduardo B\u00e4hr]]\n* 1996: {{ill|Marcos Car\u00edas Zapata|es}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://tiempo.hn/fallece-escritor-hondureno-marcos-carias/ |title=A sus 80 a\u00f1os fallece el reconocido escritor hondure\u00f1o, Marcos Car\u00edas |trans-title=The Distinguished Honduran Writer Marcos Car\u00edas Passes Away at Age 80 |first=Lorena |last=Martinez |work=[[El Tiempo (Honduras)|El Tiempo]] |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1999: [[Alfredo Le\u00f3n G\u00f3mez]]<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGBXIqWMb-oC&lpg=PA86&pg=PA86 |title=Diccionario de literatos hondure\u00f1os |trans-title=Dictionary of Literary Hondurans |first=Jos\u00e9 |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |publisher=Editorial Guaymuras |isbn=9789992633274 |language=Spanish |year=2004 |access-date=2020-01-16 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2000: [[Livio Ram\u00edrez Lozano]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2002: [[Leticia de Oyuela]]<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVVIbKfqB4IC&lpg=PA73&pg=PA73 |title=Diccionario biogr\u00e1fico de historiadores hondure\u00f1os |trans-title=Biographical Dictionary of Honduran Historians |first=Jos\u00e9 |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |publisher=Editorial Guaymuras |isbn=9789992633458 |pages=72\u201373 |language=Spanish |year=2005 |access-date=2020-01-16 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[Jos\u00e9 Ad\u00e1n Castelar]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2005: [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Quesada]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2006: [[Rigoberto Paredes]]<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://presencia.unah.edu.hn/noticias/fallecio-el-poeta-y-ensayista-rigoberto-paredes/ |title=Falleci\u00f3 el poeta y ensayista Rigoberto Paredes |trans-title=The Poet and Essayist Rigoberto Paredes Passes Away |first=Kelssin Ivan |last=Vasquez Landa |journal=Presencia Universitaria |publisher=[[Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de Honduras]] |language=Spanish |date=2015-03-09 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Juan Antonio Medina Dur\u00f3n]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://proceso.hn/salud/5-salud-y-sociedad/comunidad-de-la-upnfm-lamenta-deceso-del-intelectual-juan-antonio-medina.html |title=Comunidad de la UPNFM lamenta deceso del intelectual Juan Antonio Medina |trans-title=UPNFM Community Mourns Death of Intellectual Juan Antonio Medina |work=Proceso Digital |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2015-11-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2009: {{ill|Nery Alexis Gait\u00e1n|es}}<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 2010: [[Samuel Villeda Arita]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archivo.elheraldo.hn/Vida/listado-nota/Ediciones/2010/11/24/Noticias/Premios-a-la-excelencia |title=Premios a la excelencia |trans-title=Awards for Excellence |first=Gustavo |last=Banegas |work=[[El Heraldo (Tegucigalpa)|El Heraldo]] |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2010-11-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2011: [[A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://old.latribuna.hn/2011/11/27/aida-castaneda-premio-nacional-de-literatura-\u201cramon-rosa\u201d-2011-una-propuesta-en-busca-de-valores-y-solidaridad/ |title=A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda Premio Nacional de Literatura, 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa', 2011: Una propuesta en busca de valores y solidaridad |trans-title=A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa' National Literature Award, 2011: A Proposal in Search of Values and Solidarity |first=Nery Alexis |last=Gait\u00e1n |work=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2011-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103122542/http://old.latribuna.hn/2011/11/27/aida-castaneda-premio-nacional-de-literatura-%E2%80%9Cramon-rosa%E2%80%9D-2011-una-propuesta-en-busca-de-valores-y-solidaridad/ |archive-date=2012-11-03 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2012: [[Luis Alonso G\u00f3mez Oyuela]]<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 2013: [[Luis Roberto Castellanos]]\n* 2014: [[A\u00edda Castellanos Pineda]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.elheraldo.hn/pais/567773-214/gobierno-hondureno-entrega-premios-de-literatura-y-arte |title=Gobierno hondure\u00f1o entrega premios de Literatura y Arte |trans-title=Honduras Government Presents Awards for Literature and Art |work=[[El Heraldo (Tegucigalpa)|El Heraldo]] |language=Spanish |date=2014-04-07 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2015: {{ill|Kalton Harold Bruhl|es}}<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 2016: [[Juan Ramon Martinez (politician)|Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2017: {{ill|Mario Hern\u00e1n Ram\u00edrez|es}}<ref name=entrega2017/>\n* 2018: {{ill|V\u00edctor Manuel Ramos|es|V\u00edctor Manuel Ramos (poeta)}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.proceso.hn/aldia/15-al-d%C3%ADa/educacion-realiza-entrega-de-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura-2018.html |title=Educaci\u00f3n realiza entrega de premios Nacionales de Ciencia, Arte y Literatura 2018 |trans-title=Education Delivers 2018 National Science, Art, and Literature Awards |work=Proceso Digital |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-05 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2019: [[Jorge Fausto Medina Garc\u00eda]]<ref name=Fausto/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramon Rosa National Literature Award}}\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Honduras]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1951]]\n[[Category:Latin American literary awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name             = Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award\n| subheader        = Named in honor of writer [[Ram\u00f3n Rosa]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| description      = Authors whose work has national and international significance\n| sponsor          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Executive branch of the government of Honduras|Executive branch]]\n* {{ill|Secretariat of Public Education (Honduras)|es|Secretar\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (Honduras)|lt=Secretariat of Public Education}}\n* [[Secretary of State for Culture, Arts and Sports|Secretariat of Culture, Arts, and Sports]]\n}}\n| location         = [[Presidential Palace of Honduras|Presidential Palace]]\n| country          = Honduras\n| presenter        = \n| year             = 1951\n| year2            = \n| website          = \n| holder           = \n}}\nThe '''Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award''' ({{lang-es|'''Premio Nacional de Literatura Ram\u00f3n Rosa'''}}) is an honor presented annually by the [[President of Honduras]].\n\n==History==\nNamed in honor of the liberal writer and government minister [[Ram\u00f3n Rosa]] (1848\u20131993), the award was created by legislative decree in 1949, and first given in 1951, to [[Luis Andr\u00e9s Z\u00faniga]].<ref name=creaci\u00f3n>{{Cite journal |url=https://presencia.unah.edu.hn/noticias/se-cumplieron-67-anos-de-la-creacion-del-premio-nacional-de-literatura-ramon-rosa/ |title=Se cumplieron 67 a\u00f1os de la creaci\u00f3n del Premio Nacional de Literatura Ram\u00f3n Rosa |trans-title=67th Anniversary of the Creation of the Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award |first=Katherine Eunice |last=Ramirez Rivas |journal=Presencia Universitaria |publisher=[[Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de Honduras]] |language=Spanish |date=2016-04-29 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> It was restructured by Legislative Decree no. 100 on 11 October 1967.<ref name=Danl\u00ed>{{Cite news |url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2013/01/13/danli-y-sus-premios-nacionales-de-literatura/ |title=Danl\u00ed y sus Premios Nacionales de Literatura |first=Carlos Ernesto |last=Molina Barahona |work=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2013-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022225051/http://www.latribuna.hn/2013/01/13/danli-y-sus-premios-nacionales-de-literatura/ |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIt is presented annually at the [[Presidential Palace of Honduras|Presidential Palace]] to a writer whose work has national and international significance.<ref name=Fausto>{{Cite web |url=https://www.presidencia.gob.hn/index.php/sala-de-prensa/6590-gobierno-entrega-los-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura |title=Gobierno entrega los Premios Nacionales de Ciencia, Arte y Literatura |trans-title=Government Presents National Awards for Science, Art, and Literature |publisher=[[Executive branch of the government of Honduras]] |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2019-11-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127201727/https://www.presidencia.gob.hn/index.php/sala-de-prensa/6590-gobierno-entrega-los-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura |archive-date=2019-11-27 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn some years, the ceremony has been held at the {{ill|Manuel Bonilla National Theater|es|Teatro Nacional Manuel Bonilla}} in [[Tegucigalpa]].<ref name=entrega2017>{{Cite news |url=https://hondudiario.com/2018/05/17/gobierno-entrega-premios-nacionales-de-arte-ciencia-y-literatura/ |title=Gobierno entrega premios Nacionales de Arte, Ciencia y Literatura |trans-title=Government Presents National Awards for Art, Science, and Literature |work=Hondudiario |language=Spanish |date=2018-05-17 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> It is sponsored by the Civic Projects and Emergency Education Unit of the {{ill|Secretariat of Public Education (Honduras)|es|Secretar\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (Honduras)|lt=Secretariat of Public Education}}, the [[Executive branch of the government of Honduras|executive branch]], and the [[Secretary of State for Culture, Arts and Sports|Secretariat of Culture, Arts, and Sports]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oei.es/historico/cultura2/honduras/cap11.htm |title=Premios y Concursos En Honduras |trans-title=Awards and Contests in Honduras |publisher=[[Organization of Ibero-American States]] |language=Spanish |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Categories==\nThe Ram\u00f3n Rosa National Literature Award is given for works in the areas of poetry, novel, short story, oratory and narration, journalism, drama, essay, criticism, and any other genre that contributes to the development of letters and culture in the country.<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n\nThere is only one winner per year; awards are not given in the individual categories.\n\n==Winners==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 1951: [[Luis Andr\u00e9s Z\u00faniga]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1953: [[Guillermo Bustillo]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1954: [[Claudio Barrera]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1955: [[Jacobo C\u00e1rcamo]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.latribuna.hn/2017/02/12/premio-nacional-literatura-ramon-rosa-2016/ |title=Premio Nacional de Literatura 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa' 2016 |first=Juan Fernando |last=\u00c1vila P. |work=[[La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2017-02-12 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1956: [[Daniel La\u00ednez]]\n* 1959: [[Jacobo C\u00e1rcamo]]\n* 1963: [[Guillermo Bustillo]]\n* 1968: [[Argentina D\u00edaz Lozano]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1970: [[Clementina Su\u00e1rez]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1971: [[Medardo Mej\u00eda]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1972: [[Roberto Sosa (poet)|Roberto Sosa]]<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 1975: [[Julio Escoto]]\n* 1976: {{ill|V\u00edctor C\u00e1ceres Lara|es}}\n* 1979: [[\u00d3scar Acosta]]\n* 1980: {{ill|\u00d3scar Armando Flores Midence|es}}\n* 1981: [[Pompeyo del Valle]]\n* 1983: {{ill|Antonio Jos\u00e9 Rivas|es}}\n* 1984: [[Miguel R. Ortega]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.asale.org/noticias/miguel-r-ortega-premio-ramon-amaya-amador |title=Miguel R. Ortega, Premio Ram\u00f3n Amaya Amador |publisher=[[Association of Academies of the Spanish Language]] |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1986: [[Hern\u00e1n de Jes\u00fas C\u00e1rcamo Tercero]]\n* 1987: {{ill|Felipe Elvir Rojas|es}}<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 1989: {{ill|Helen Uma\u00f1a|es}}\n* 1990: {{ill|Santos Juarez Fiallos|es}}\n* 1991: [[Roberto Castillo (philosopher)|Roberto Castillo]]\n* 1992: [[Eduardo B\u00e4hr]]\n* 1996: {{ill|Marcos Car\u00edas Zapata|es}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://tiempo.hn/fallece-escritor-hondureno-marcos-carias/ |title=A sus 80 a\u00f1os fallece el reconocido escritor hondure\u00f1o, Marcos Car\u00edas |trans-title=The Distinguished Honduran Writer Marcos Car\u00edas Passes Away at Age 80 |first=Lorena |last=Martinez |work=[[El Tiempo (Honduras)|El Tiempo]] |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 1999: [[Alfredo Le\u00f3n G\u00f3mez]]<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGBXIqWMb-oC&lpg=PA86&pg=PA86 |title=Diccionario de literatos hondure\u00f1os |trans-title=Dictionary of Literary Hondurans |first=Jos\u00e9 |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |publisher=Editorial Guaymuras |isbn=9789992633274 |language=Spanish |year=2004 |access-date=2020-01-16 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2000: [[Livio Ram\u00edrez Lozano]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2002: [[Leticia de Oyuela]]<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVVIbKfqB4IC&lpg=PA73&pg=PA73 |title=Diccionario biogr\u00e1fico de historiadores hondure\u00f1os |trans-title=Biographical Dictionary of Honduran Historians |first=Jos\u00e9 |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |publisher=Editorial Guaymuras |isbn=9789992633458 |pages=72\u201373 |language=Spanish |year=2005 |access-date=2020-01-16 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[Jos\u00e9 Ad\u00e1n Castelar]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2005: [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Quesada]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2006: [[Rigoberto Paredes]]<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://presencia.unah.edu.hn/noticias/fallecio-el-poeta-y-ensayista-rigoberto-paredes/ |title=Falleci\u00f3 el poeta y ensayista Rigoberto Paredes |trans-title=The Poet and Essayist Rigoberto Paredes Passes Away |first=Kelssin Ivan |last=Vasquez Landa |journal=Presencia Universitaria |publisher=[[Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de Honduras]] |language=Spanish |date=2015-03-09 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Juan Antonio Medina Dur\u00f3n]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://proceso.hn/salud/5-salud-y-sociedad/comunidad-de-la-upnfm-lamenta-deceso-del-intelectual-juan-antonio-medina.html |title=Comunidad de la UPNFM lamenta deceso del intelectual Juan Antonio Medina |trans-title=UPNFM Community Mourns Death of Intellectual Juan Antonio Medina |work=Proceso Digital |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2015-11-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2009: {{ill|Nery Alexis Gait\u00e1n|es}}<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 2010: [[Samuel Villeda Arita]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archivo.elheraldo.hn/Vida/listado-nota/Ediciones/2010/11/24/Noticias/Premios-a-la-excelencia |title=Premios a la excelencia |trans-title=Awards for Excellence |first=Gustavo |last=Banegas |work=[[El Heraldo (Tegucigalpa)|El Heraldo]] |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2010-11-23 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2011: [[A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://old.latribuna.hn/2011/11/27/aida-castaneda-premio-nacional-de-literatura-\u201cramon-rosa\u201d-2011-una-propuesta-en-busca-de-valores-y-solidaridad/ |title=A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda Premio Nacional de Literatura, 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa', 2011: Una propuesta en busca de valores y solidaridad |trans-title=A\u00edda Casta\u00f1eda 'Ram\u00f3n Rosa' National Literature Award, 2011: A Proposal in Search of Values and Solidarity |first=Nery Alexis |last=Gait\u00e1n |work=[[La Tribuna]] |language=Spanish |date=2011-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103122542/http://old.latribuna.hn/2011/11/27/aida-castaneda-premio-nacional-de-literatura-%E2%80%9Cramon-rosa%E2%80%9D-2011-una-propuesta-en-busca-de-valores-y-solidaridad/ |archive-date=2012-11-03 |url-status=dead |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2012: [[Luis Alonso G\u00f3mez Oyuela]]<ref name=Danl\u00ed/>\n* 2013: [[Luis Roberto Castellanos]]\n* 2014: [[A\u00edda Castellanos Pineda]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.elheraldo.hn/pais/567773-214/gobierno-hondureno-entrega-premios-de-literatura-y-arte |title=Gobierno hondure\u00f1o entrega premios de Literatura y Arte |trans-title=Honduras Government Presents Awards for Literature and Art |work=[[El Heraldo (Tegucigalpa)|El Heraldo]] |language=Spanish |date=2014-04-07 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2015: {{ill|Kalton Harold Bruhl|es}}<ref name=creaci\u00f3n/>\n* 2016: [[Juan Ramon Martinez (politician)|Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez]]<ref name=\"Juan Ram\u00f3n Mart\u00ednez\"/>\n* 2017: {{ill|Mario Hern\u00e1n Ram\u00edrez|es}}<ref name=entrega2017/>\n* 2018: {{ill|V\u00edctor Manuel Ramos|es|V\u00edctor Manuel Ramos (poeta)}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.proceso.hn/aldia/15-al-d%C3%ADa/educacion-realiza-entrega-de-premios-nacionales-de-ciencia-arte-y-literatura-2018.html |title=Educaci\u00f3n realiza entrega de premios Nacionales de Ciencia, Arte y Literatura 2018 |trans-title=Education Delivers 2018 National Science, Art, and Literature Awards |work=Proceso Digital |location=Tegucigalpa |language=Spanish |date=2018-12-05 |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n* 2019: [[Jorge Fausto Medina Garc\u00eda]]<ref name=Fausto/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramon Rosa National Literature Award}}\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Honduras]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1951]]\n[[Category:Latin American literary awards]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-La Tribuna", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ram%C3%B3n_Rosa_National_Literature_Award"}
{"title_page": "Health in Cameroon", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe Ministry of Public Health in [[Cameroon]] is responsible for the maintenance of all public health services. Many missionaries maintain health and [[leprosy]] centers. The [[Government of Cameroon|government]] is pursuing a vigorous policy of public health improvement, with considerable success in reducing [[African trypanosomiasis|sleeping sickness]], [[leprosy]], and other endemic diseases.<ref name=\"Rose Futrih N. Njini\">{{cite web |title=The need is so great |author=Rose Futrih N. Njini |publisher=D+C Development and Cooperation/ dandc.eu |date=December 2012 |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/cameroon-too-many-nurses-and-doctors-lack-perspective}}</ref>\n\nThe demand for all types of health services and equipment is high and constant. The need for modern equipment is especially urgent, with many clinics using outdated equipment, some of which is imported illegally from [[Nigeria]]. There is also a shortage in professional medical staff, partially caused by public service hiring quotas. Therefore the staff that works is badly paid and has too much work to do, which makes it difficult to treat patients adequately. Many doctors and nurses which were trained in Cameroon emigrate to Europe \u2013 but also to South Africa and Asia \u2013 for that reason.<ref name=\"Rose Futrih N. Njini\"/>\n\n== Health infrastructure ==\n\nAs of 2016, Cameroon's health map illustrates 10 regions, 189 health districts, 1800 health areas and approximately 5166 public and private health facilities spread throughout the national territory. Access to health services in Cameroon in 2016 was at 2.19 health facilities per 10,000 inhabitants.<ref>MINSANTE, Cameroon Health Map 2016.</ref> The health facilities are organized into seven main categories: general hospitals, central hospitals, regional hospitals, district hospitals, district medical centers, Integrated health centers and ambulatory health centers.<ref name=\":5\">Cameroon: Health Analytical Profile 2016</ref>\n\n== Health status ==\n\n=== Demographics ===\n\n* Population: 24,348,25 estimate for 2019 <ref name=\":2\" />\n* Surface Area: 475,650 Square Km\n* Population density: 51 inhabitants per square Km\n* Young population: 48% of total population below 15 years and 3.5% aged 65 and above<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthdatacollaborative.org/fileadmin/uploads/hdc/Documents/Country_documents/En_Tracking-100-Core-Health__Indicators-For-Cameroon-in-2017.pdf|title=Tracking the 100 core indicators for Cameroon, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.healthdatacollaborative.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* Annual growth rate: 2.6%\n\n===Life expectancy===\nThe 2014 CIA estimated average life expectancy in Cameroon was 57.35 years.<ref name=iuonoa>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2102rank.html |title=CIA - The World Factbook Life Expectancy|publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\nHowever, in 2017, the estimates were 65.5 and 61.0 years for females and males respectively.<ref name=\":3\">Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>\n\n=== Birth rate and Population ===\nIn 2002 the [[birth rate]] was estimated at 35.66 per 1,000 people. As of 1999, an estimated 19 percent of the country\u2019s married women (ages 15 to 49) used any type of contraception.\nThe population is estimated as 24,053,727 in 2017 <ref>World Bank 2018, Cameroon</ref> and Central Bureau of Census and Population Studies gives an official projection of 24,348,251 in 2019.<ref name=\":2\">Central Bureau of Census and Population Studies.http://www.bucrep.cm/index.php/en/</ref>\nThere has been substantial increase from 2.3 million in 1900 through 4.34, 8.66, 11.7, 15.4, 20.1 millions in the years 1950, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 respectively.<ref>Gapminder Tools.https://www.gapminder.org/</ref>\n \n===Health Expenditure Profile===\nThe [[Per capita income]] of [[Cameroon]] in 2017 is $3,640 making her a lower middle income country <ref>World Bank 2018, Cameroon</ref>\nThe current [[Health expenditure]] (CHE) per capita has been on an increase in the last 20 years; US$43, 48, 54 and 64 in the years 2000, 2005, 2010, 2016 respectively though out-of-pocket spending has been the main source of payment for health services for majority of Cameroonians throughout this period.<ref>WHO| Global Health Expenditure Database 2018. http://who.int/nha/database</ref>\nIn 2016, of the health expenditure per capita of $64 spent,  estimated that Out-of-pocket spending accounted for 70% while domestic public spending, voluntary health insurance, aid accounted for 13%, 9% and 6% respectively and other sources just 2%.<ref>WHO| Global Health Expenditure Database 2018. http://who.int/nha/database</ref>\n\n===Major Causes of death===\nFrom 1990 till 2018 communicable, maternal, neonatal diseases as group is the leading causes of death followed by non-communicable diseases and injuries in Cameroon and Sub-Saharan Africa. However, globally this is not the same pattern observed as the group of non-communicable diseases has been the leading cause of death followed by the group of communicable, maternal & neonatal diseases and thirdly the group of injuries in the last three decades.<ref>Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>\nThe top ten causes of [[death]] in 2018:\n* [[Malaria]]\n* [[HIV/AIDS]] \n* [[Lower respiratory infections]]\n* neonatal disorder\n* [[Diarrheal diseases]]\n* [[Ischemic heart disease]] \n* [[Stroke]]\n* [[Tuberculosis]]\n* road injuries and \n* [[Cirrhosis]] <ref name=\":0\">Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref><ref>https://www.cdc.gov/globalhealth/countries/cameroon/pdf/Cameroon_factsheet.pdf</ref>\n\n===Endemic diseases===\n[[Malaria]] is prevalent in the [[B\u00e9nou\u00e9 River]] Valley, the basin of [[Lake Chad]], the coastal region, and the forests of southern Cameroon. A large percentage of the adult population is affected. Other serious water-borne diseases are [[schistosomiasis]] and [[African trypanosomiasis|sleeping sickness]], which is spread by the [[tsetse fly]]. Cameroon lies in the [[yellow fever]] endemic zone.\n\n===HIV/AIDS===\n[[HIV/AIDS]] is the second cause of death in Cameroon in 2018 after [[Malaria]].  \nProgress had been made in AIDS-related death and new infections in Cameroon; reduction in the number of deaths from 22,000 to 18,000 and the number of new infections from 36,000 to 23,000 between the years 2010 and 2018. In 2018, 540,000 people were living with HIV and the prevalence among adults (15-49 years) was 3.6%.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/cameroon|title=UNAIDS Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>Moreover, the incidence among all people of all ages in Cameroon is 1.02% in 2018 <ref name=\":7\" />. In Sub Saharan Africa, the incidence (new infections per 1,000 of population) among adults (15 - 49 years) declined from 3.39 in 2010, 2.49 in 2015 to 2.14 in 2017 and globally for adults it also declined from 0.44 to 0.40 between 2015 and 2017<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdg3|title=Goal 3 .:. Sustainable Development Knowledge Platform|website=sustainabledevelopment.un.org|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref>.   \n \nMany organizations have been partnering with the government of Cameroon via the ministry of public health (MINSANTE) to against this disease. [[File:Incidence of HIV in Cameroon from 1990 - 2018.jpg|thumb|Incidence of HIV in Cameroon from 1990 - 2018]]\n\n===Maternal and child healthcare===\nIn 1999 Cameroon immunized children up to one year old for tuberculosis (52 percent); [[diphtheria]], [[pertussis]], and [[tetanus]] (48 percent); [[polio]] (37 percent); and measles (31 percent). The infant mortality in 2005 was 65 per 1,000 live births. An estimated 29 percent of children under the age of five suffered from malnutrition.\n\nThe under 5 mortality rate, per 1,000 births is 155 and the neonatal mortality as a percentage of under 5's mortality is 24. In Cameroon the number of midwives per 1,000 live births is 0.2 and the lifetime risk of death for pregnant women 1 in 35.<ref name=\"SOWMY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unfpa.org/sowmy/report/home.html|title=The State Of The World's Midwifery|publisher=United Nations Population Fund|accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017:\n\n* Prevalence of child stunting: 30.7%\n* Prevalence of child experiencing wasting: 2.8%\n* Prevalence of child (2-4 years) overweight: 20.9%\n* Coverage of seven vaccine in target population: 72.1%<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Maternal Mortality Ratio ====\nThis is defined it as the number of women who die due to causes related to pregnancy or aggravated by pregnancy and provision of care with such deaths occurring during pregnancy or delivery or within 42 days after the end of pregnancy, whatever the duration or type of pregnancy, expressed per 100,000 live births  for a given period <ref name=\":6\" />.  The [[Maternal Mortality Ratio]] of [[Cameroon]] has shown decline in the last three decades from 728 per 100,000 live births in 1990 and to 596 in the year 2015. These deaths are however preventable with appropriate management and care. However, more efforts are needed so as to meet the global [[Sustainable Development Goals]] target of this indicator which is less than 70 per 100,000 lives births by 2030 <ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" />. \nIn the world at large, it reduced significantly by almost half (44% reduction) from 385 in the year 1990 to 216 in the year 2015; as compared to Sub-Saharan Africa from 987 in 1990 from 546 in 2015.<ref name=\":9\">World Health Organization, UNICEF, United Nations Population Fund and The World Bank, Trends in Maternal Mortality: 1990 to 2015, WHO, Geneva, 2015.https://www.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/pub-pdf/9789241565141_eng.pdf</ref>\n\n'''''Table 1: Maternal Mortality Ratio in Cameroon from 1990 to 2015'''''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Years !! Maternal Mortality Ratio \n|-\n| 2015 || 596\n|-\n| 2010 || 676\n|-\n| 2005 || 729\n|-\n| 2000 || 750\n|-\n| 1995 || 749\n|-\n| 1990 || 728\n|} \n''Source: World Health Organization, UNICEF, United Nations Population Fund and The World Bank, Trends in Maternal Mortality: 1990 to 2015, WHO, Geneva, 2015''\n\n==== Coverage of skill birth attendants ====\nIn Cameroon, there has been a drop from 63.4% in 1990 to 56.8% in 2000 and then an increase to 67.9% in 2017.<ref>Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>However, Globally, the 81% of live births worldwide occurred with the assistance of a skilled health personnel in 2018, up from 62% in 2005 and 69% in 2012 whereas that of Sub-Saharan Africa is just 59%in 2018 <ref name=\":8\" />. \nThis increase in the coverage of live births by skill birth attendants from the year 2000 in Cameroon could be attributed to the increase in the number of training institutions of health owned by the [[government]], [[faith-based organization]] and also by private individuals; and also increase in the number of skilled health personnel employed in health facilities. Moreover, possibly because of the increase in mother and child health campaigns and demand to seek health this services in health facilities though traditional birth attendants are also present <ref name=\":5\" />.[[File:Coverage of skill brith attendants, Cameroon.jpg|thumb|Coverage of skill brith attendants, Cameroon]]\n\n==== Family planning needs met====\nThe proportion women of reproductive age (15 to 49 years) in Cameroon who have their [[family planning]] needs met with modern contraception methods increased about three folds from 14% in 1990, to 43.1% in 2015. As of 2017, still not up to half of women of reproductive age have their family planning needs as met as the percentage stands at 44.7%<ref name=\":1\">https://www.unicef.org/reports/levels-and-trends-child-mortality-report-2018</ref>. However, progress has been globally even though slowly from 74% in 2000 to 76% in 2019<ref name=\":8\" /> .  [[File:Met need for family planning with modern contraception methods, Cameroon.jpg|thumb|Met need for family planning with modern contraception methods, Cameroon]]\n\n==== Under-5 Mortality and Neonatal Mortality ====\nGlobally in the year 2000, the Under-5 mortality rate was 43 per 1,000 and neonatal mortality rate (likelihood of dying in the first 28 days of life) was 31 per 1,000 <ref name=\":8\" />. Also globally, in 2017, the Under-5 morality and neonatal rates stood as 39 and 18<ref name=\":1\" /> . As for Cameroon, the Under-5 and Neonatal mortality rates have shown a decline from 135.6 and 39.3 in 1990 to 73.5 and 23.4 in 2017 respectively. \nMany kids still die before getting celebrating their 5th birthday in Cameroon.\n\n'''''Table 2: Under-5 Mortality and Neonatal Mortality rates 1990 - 2017'''''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Under-5 Mortality Rate !! Neonatal Mortality \n|-\n| 2017 || 73.5 || 23.4\n|-\n| 2016 || 77.5 || 24.3\n|-\n| 2015 || 81.5 || 24.9\n|-\n| 2010 || 103.0 || 28.1\n|-\n| 2005 || 122.5 || 31.2\n|-\n| 2000 || 134.2 || 32.9\n|-\n| 1995 || 139.1 || 37.3\n|-\n| 1990 || 135.6 || 39.3\n|}\n''Source:'' <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Road Injury ===\n\nTransport injury is among the several types of injury. Pedestrian, cyclist, motorcyclist locally called \"benskin\" or \"okada\", motor vehicles, are among the most used road transport in Cameroon. As of 2014, the number of vehicles was estimated at 675,000. Recording more than 16,000 road accidents per year with more than 1000 deaths. In addition to the human loss which is dramatic, the economic loss is estimated at 100 billion FCFA (approximately US Dollars 168 million) per year <ref name=\":4\" />. The estimated number of people killed per 100 million km driven was 73, which is more than 35 times higher than on similar roads in the US and Europe .\n<br>\n'''Road traffic injury''' is a major cause of death in Cameroon and among the top ten causes in 2018. The estimates of the deaths per 100,000 in the year 2017 from all transport injuries was 15.88 while road injury alone was 14.79 in Cameroon. Moreover, the deaths per 100,000 were 17.96 low income countries had as opposed to 10.39 in high income countries. In 2017 in Sub Saharan Africa, the number of deaths per from road traffic injuries were estimated at 161,648.<ref name=\":0\" /> Road traffic accidents are the largest cause of unintended injury in all regions, among low, middle income and high income countries. However, in developing countries, they have to deal with road accident in addition to  some communicable diseases which are not a major issue in the high income countries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Global Health 101. Third Edition|last=Skolnik|first=Richard|publisher=Michel Brown|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=|url-status=live}}</ref> This numbers of deaths from transport injury for Cameroon have increase from 3391 to 4408 in the last two decades with increasing number of  death recorded among he males population <ref name=\":3\" />.    \n[[File:Death_(Percentage)_due_to_Road_Injury_in_Cameroon,_2017_-_Distrbution_by_Sex.jpg|thumb|Percentage distribution by Sex of deaths due to Road Injury in Cameroon, 2017. Data from: https://vizhub.healthdata.org/gbd-compare/]]\nThese deaths could be as a result of several factors grouped into: transport operator (driver, cyclist, motorcyclist) factors, the state of the means of transport, the road or pavement, and also other environmental factors.   \n[[File:Age_Distribution_of_the_Death_due_to_Road_Injury_in_Cameroon,2017.jpg|thumb|Distribution of the Death due to Road Injury in Cameroon, 2017 - Distribution by Age. Data from https://vizhub.healthdata.org/gbd-compare/]]\n<br>\nThe Sustainable Development Goal number 3 (Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all ages) has nine major targets. The target number 6 which involves road injuries states:   \n\n* 3.6 By 2020 halve the number of global deaths and injury from road accident\n\n'''''Table 3: Number of deaths in Cameroon, Sub-Saharan Africa and the Globe from Traffic Injury (Road traffic Injury) 1990 - 2017'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Cameroon - Deaths from \nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury)\n! Sub-Saharan Region - Deaths from \nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury) \n!World - Deaths from\nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury)\n|-\n| 2017 || 4408 (4108) || 172,283 (161,647)\n|1,335,004 (1,243,068)\n|-\n| 2016 || 4441 (4119) || 170,780 (160,446)\n|1,345,442 (1,252,392)\n|-\n| 2015 || 4317 (4074) || 169,377 (159,036)\n|1,347,696 (1,252,514)\n|-\n| 2010 || 4356 (4053) || 167,183 (156,985)\n|1,394,717 (1,299,939)\n|-\n| 2005 || 3484 (3484) || 166,077 (155,417)\n|1,377,836 (1,284,407)\n|-\n| 2000 || 3391 (3158) || 162,369 (151,565)\n|1,376,105 (1,282,553)\n|-\n| 1990 || 2680 (2535) || 131,216 (124,172)\n|1,228,046 (1,150,717)\n|}\n\n''Source:''<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n'''Reports:''' Road Safety: Cameroon must redouble its effort and strengthen coordination<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |title=UNECE Cameroon Report |url=https://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/EPSR_Cameroun.pdf |website=www.unece.org |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Cameroon, ministry of transport in collaboration with other ministries have been enforcing several methods to reduce this deaths in several sensitization campaigns (in schools, sending short messages to subscribers phones, special back to school programs), teams to do unannounced controls, alcohol test for drivers, improving on the high way signs, rehabilitation of road etc. \nHowever, she needs to redouble her effort and improve coordination<ref name=\":4\" />, cooperation  with as well as human behavior in order to greatly reduce not only the number of deaths but also the [[Disability-adjusted life year]] DALYs which stands at 226,673  (157,195 for men)<ref name=\":3\" /> road injury alone for Cameroon.\n\n== United Nations: Sustainable Development Goals, SDGs 2016 - 2030 ==\nCameroon understands that the importance of the [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) cannot be over emphasized as the program takes into consideration the problems of development in the dimensions of security, economy, social, human and the environment <ref name=\":10\">RAPPORT DE LA SITUATION DE REFERENCE\n\nDES INDICATEURS DES OBJECTIFS DE DEVELOPPEMENT DURABLE AU\n\nCAMEROUN \n\n\n_version 26 novembre 2017.pdf</ref>. Cameroon adopted all 17 SDGs but also understands that it will be demanding for her in reporting and also in achieving the objectives. Main challenges identified were:\n* Inadequate mobilization of multiple stakeholders\n* Strengthening of the Statistical System for better monitoring\n* Mobilizing financial resources requested to achieve the SDGs <ref name=\":10\" /> <br>\n\nThe SGDs are implemented in Cameroon against the backdrop of an update of development policies and strategies resulting in the facilitation of their integration. In addition, for the conclusion of an economic and financial program, with the [[International Monetary Fund]] IMF, an interim development strategy has been prepared taking into account the contextualized SDGs. On security fronts, repeated attacks from the Boko Haram terrorist group in the Northern regions since 2014, flow of Central African refugees in the East region, and also the internal crisis in the North-West and South-West regions since 2017. These factors affect the mobilization of domestic funds which has negative impact on the achievement of SDGs <ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/memberstates/cameroon|title=Cameroon .:. Sustainable Development Knowledge Platform|website=sustainabledevelopment.un.org|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>.  Some strides have been made in the implementation of the Agenda 2030 in the areas of '''education, economic growth, policies and institutions''' but the aforementioned factors and host of other factors threaten even the little gains achieved in these areas <ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":12\">https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/24501CAMEROON_VNR_PPTENG_FINAL_VERSION.pdf</ref>.\n\n<br>\nKey factors identified to the success of the implementation of the SDGs will be their '''inclusion in the budget; and the enhancement of the statistical mechanism for the follow-up of the progress'''<ref name=\":11\" /> '''.''' <br>\nCameroon was part of the national voluntary review on the implementation of SDGs and the high level political forum on sustainable development New-York in July 2019. The government has indicated that concrete actions and strategies are needed to:\n* Intensify national ownership of the SDGs (inclusion in schools and university curricular and in extra-curricular activities)\n* Accelerate full integration of SDGs into daily public policies and programs\n* Establish a national multi-stakeholder monitoring body - as a review and accountability platform\n* Strengthen of the national statistical systems\n* Enlarge partnership and mobilize needed financial resources needed for the successful implementation of SDGs<ref name=\":12\" /> .\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unfpa.org/sowmy/resources/docs/country_info/profile/en_Cameroon_SoWMy_Profile.pdf The State of the World's Midwifery - Cameroom Country Profile]\n\n{{Africa in topic|Health in}}\n\n[[Category:Health in Cameroon| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe Ministry of Public Health in [[Cameroon]] is responsible for the maintenance of all public health services. Many missionaries maintain health and [[leprosy]] centers. The [[Government of Cameroon|government]] is pursuing a vigorous policy of public health improvement, with considerable success in reducing [[African trypanosomiasis|sleeping sickness]], [[leprosy]], and other endemic diseases.<ref name=\"Rose Futrih N. Njini\">{{cite web |title=The need is so great |author=Rose Futrih N. Njini |publisher=D+C Development and Cooperation/ dandc.eu |date=December 2012 |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/cameroon-too-many-nurses-and-doctors-lack-perspective}}</ref>\n\nThe demand for all types of health services and equipment is high and constant. The need for modern equipment is especially urgent, with many clinics using outdated equipment, some of which is imported illegally from [[Nigeria]]. There is also a shortage in professional medical staff, partially caused by public service hiring quotas. Therefore the staff that works is badly paid and has too much work to do, which makes it difficult to treat patients adequately. Many doctors and nurses which were trained in Cameroon emigrate to Europe \u2013 but also to South Africa and Asia \u2013 for that reason.<ref name=\"Rose Futrih N. Njini\"/>\n\n== Health infrastructure ==\n\nAs of 2016, Cameroon's health map illustrates 10 regions, 189 health districts, 1800 health areas and approximately 5166 public and private health facilities spread throughout the national territory. Access to health services in Cameroon in 2016 was at 2.19 health facilities per 10,000 inhabitants.<ref>MINSANTE, Cameroon Health Map 2016.</ref> The health facilities are organized into seven main categories: general hospitals, central hospitals, regional hospitals, district hospitals, district medical centers, Integrated health centers and ambulatory health centers.<ref name=\":5\">Cameroon: Health Analytical Profile 2016</ref>\n\n== Health status ==\n\n=== Demographics ===\n\n* Population: 24,348,25 estimate for 2019 <ref name=\":2\" />\n* Surface Area: 475,650 Square Km\n* Population density: 51 inhabitants per square Km\n* Young population: 48% of total population below 15 years and 3.5% aged 65 and above<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthdatacollaborative.org/fileadmin/uploads/hdc/Documents/Country_documents/En_Tracking-100-Core-Health__Indicators-For-Cameroon-in-2017.pdf|title=Tracking the 100 core indicators for Cameroon, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.healthdatacollaborative.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* Annual growth rate: 2.6%\n\n===Life expectancy===\nThe 2014 CIA estimated average life expectancy in Cameroon was 57.35 years.<ref name=iuonoa>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2102rank.html |title=CIA - The World Factbook Life Expectancy|publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\nHowever, in 2017, the estimates were 65.5 and 61.0 years for females and males respectively.<ref name=\":3\">Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>\n\n=== Birth rate and Population ===\nIn 2002 the [[birth rate]] was estimated at 35.66 per 1,000 people. As of 1999, an estimated 19 percent of the country\u2019s married women (ages 15 to 49) used any type of contraception.\nThe population is estimated as 24,053,727 in 2017 <ref>World Bank 2018, Cameroon</ref> and Central Bureau of Census and Population Studies gives an official projection of 24,348,251 in 2019.<ref name=\":2\">Central Bureau of Census and Population Studies.http://www.bucrep.cm/index.php/en/</ref>\nThere has been substantial increase from 2.3 million in 1900 through 4.34, 8.66, 11.7, 15.4, 20.1 millions in the years 1950, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 respectively.<ref>Gapminder Tools.https://www.gapminder.org/</ref>\n \n===Health Expenditure Profile===\nThe [[Per capita income]] of [[Cameroon]] in 2017 is $3,640 making her a lower middle income country <ref>World Bank 2018, Cameroon</ref>\nThe current [[Health expenditure]] (CHE) per capita has been on an increase in the last 20 years; US$43, 48, 54 and 64 in the years 2000, 2005, 2010, 2016 respectively though out-of-pocket spending has been the main source of payment for health services for majority of Cameroonians throughout this period.<ref>WHO| Global Health Expenditure Database 2018. http://who.int/nha/database</ref>\nIn 2016, of the health expenditure per capita of $64 spent,  estimated that Out-of-pocket spending accounted for 70% while domestic public spending, voluntary health insurance, aid accounted for 13%, 9% and 6% respectively and other sources just 2%.<ref>WHO| Global Health Expenditure Database 2018. http://who.int/nha/database</ref>\n\n===Major Causes of death===\nFrom 1990 till 2018 communicable, maternal, neonatal diseases as group is the leading causes of death followed by non-communicable diseases and injuries in Cameroon and Sub-Saharan Africa. However, globally this is not the same pattern observed as the group of non-communicable diseases has been the leading cause of death followed by the group of communicable, maternal & neonatal diseases and thirdly the group of injuries in the last three decades.<ref>Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>\nThe top ten causes of [[death]] in 2018:\n* [[Malaria]]\n* [[HIV/AIDS]] \n* [[Lower respiratory infections]]\n* neonatal disorder\n* [[Diarrheal diseases]]\n* [[Ischemic heart disease]] \n* [[Stroke]]\n* [[Tuberculosis]]\n* road injuries and \n* [[Cirrhosis]] <ref name=\":0\">Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref><ref>https://www.cdc.gov/globalhealth/countries/cameroon/pdf/Cameroon_factsheet.pdf</ref>\n\n===Endemic diseases===\n[[Malaria]] is prevalent in the [[B\u00e9nou\u00e9 River]] Valley, the basin of [[Lake Chad]], the coastal region, and the forests of southern Cameroon. A large percentage of the adult population is affected. Other serious water-borne diseases are [[schistosomiasis]] and [[African trypanosomiasis|sleeping sickness]], which is spread by the [[tsetse fly]]. Cameroon lies in the [[yellow fever]] endemic zone.\n\n===HIV/AIDS===\n[[HIV/AIDS]] is the second cause of death in Cameroon in 2018 after [[Malaria]].  \nProgress had been made in AIDS-related death and new infections in Cameroon; reduction in the number of deaths from 22,000 to 18,000 and the number of new infections from 36,000 to 23,000 between the years 2010 and 2018. In 2018, 540,000 people were living with HIV and the prevalence among adults (15-49 years) was 3.6%.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/cameroon|title=UNAIDS Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>Moreover, the incidence among all people of all ages in Cameroon is 1.02% in 2018 <ref name=\":7\" />. In Sub Saharan Africa, the incidence (new infections per 1,000 of population) among adults (15 - 49 years) declined from 3.39 in 2010, 2.49 in 2015 to 2.14 in 2017 and globally for adults it also declined from 0.44 to 0.40 between 2015 and 2017<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdg3|title=Goal 3 .:. Sustainable Development Knowledge Platform|website=sustainabledevelopment.un.org|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref>.   \n \nMany organizations have been partnering with the government of Cameroon via the ministry of public health (MINSANTE) to against this disease. [[File:Incidence of HIV in Cameroon from 1990 - 2018.jpg|thumb|Incidence of HIV in Cameroon from 1990 - 2018]]\n\n===Maternal and child healthcare===\nIn 1999 Cameroon immunized children up to one year old for tuberculosis (52 percent); [[diphtheria]], [[pertussis]], and [[tetanus]] (48 percent); [[polio]] (37 percent); and measles (31 percent). The infant mortality in 2005 was 65 per 1,000 live births. An estimated 29 percent of children under the age of five suffered from malnutrition.\n\nThe under 5 mortality rate, per 1,000 births is 155 and the neonatal mortality as a percentage of under 5's mortality is 24. In Cameroon the number of midwives per 1,000 live births is 0.2 and the lifetime risk of death for pregnant women 1 in 35.<ref name=\"SOWMY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unfpa.org/sowmy/report/home.html|title=The State Of The World's Midwifery|publisher=United Nations Population Fund|accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017:\n\n* Prevalence of child stunting: 30.7%\n* Prevalence of child experiencing wasting: 2.8%\n* Prevalence of child (2-4 years) overweight: 20.9%\n* Coverage of seven vaccine in target population: 72.1%<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Maternal Mortality Ratio ====\nThis is defined it as the number of women who die due to causes related to pregnancy or aggravated by pregnancy and provision of care with such deaths occurring during pregnancy or delivery or within 42 days after the end of pregnancy, whatever the duration or type of pregnancy, expressed per 100,000 live births  for a given period <ref name=\":6\" />.  The [[Maternal Mortality Ratio]] of [[Cameroon]] has shown decline in the last three decades from 728 per 100,000 live births in 1990 and to 596 in the year 2015. These deaths are however preventable with appropriate management and care. However, more efforts are needed so as to meet the global [[Sustainable Development Goals]] target of this indicator which is less than 70 per 100,000 lives births by 2030 <ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" />. \nIn the world at large, it reduced significantly by almost half (44% reduction) from 385 in the year 1990 to 216 in the year 2015; as compared to Sub-Saharan Africa from 987 in 1990 from 546 in 2015.<ref name=\":9\">World Health Organization, UNICEF, United Nations Population Fund and The World Bank, Trends in Maternal Mortality: 1990 to 2015, WHO, Geneva, 2015.https://www.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/pub-pdf/9789241565141_eng.pdf</ref>\n\n'''''Table 1: Maternal Mortality Ratio in Cameroon from 1990 to 2015'''''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Years !! Maternal Mortality Ratio \n|-\n| 2015 || 596\n|-\n| 2010 || 676\n|-\n| 2005 || 729\n|-\n| 2000 || 750\n|-\n| 1995 || 749\n|-\n| 1990 || 728\n|} \n''Source: World Health Organization, UNICEF, United Nations Population Fund and The World Bank, Trends in Maternal Mortality: 1990 to 2015, WHO, Geneva, 2015''\n\n==== Coverage of skill birth attendants ====\nIn Cameroon, there has been a drop from 63.4% in 1990 to 56.8% in 2000 and then an increase to 67.9% in 2017.<ref>Institute of Health Matrics and Evaluation.http://www.healthdata.org</ref>However, Globally, the 81% of live births worldwide occurred with the assistance of a skilled health personnel in 2018, up from 62% in 2005 and 69% in 2012 whereas that of Sub-Saharan Africa is just 59%in 2018 <ref name=\":8\" />. \nThis increase in the coverage of live births by skill birth attendants from the year 2000 in Cameroon could be attributed to the increase in the number of training institutions of health owned by the [[government]], [[faith-based organization]] and also by private individuals; and also increase in the number of skilled health personnel employed in health facilities. Moreover, possibly because of the increase in mother and child health campaigns and demand to seek health this services in health facilities though traditional birth attendants are also present <ref name=\":5\" />.[[File:Coverage of skill brith attendants, Cameroon.jpg|thumb|Coverage of skill brith attendants, Cameroon]]\n\n==== Family planning needs met====\nThe proportion women of reproductive age (15 to 49 years) in Cameroon who have their [[family planning]] needs met with modern contraception methods increased about three folds from 14% in 1990, to 43.1% in 2015. As of 2017, still not up to half of women of reproductive age have their family planning needs as met as the percentage stands at 44.7%<ref name=\":1\">https://www.unicef.org/reports/levels-and-trends-child-mortality-report-2018</ref>. However, progress has been globally even though slowly from 74% in 2000 to 76% in 2019<ref name=\":8\" /> .  [[File:Met need for family planing with modern contraception methods, Cameroon.jpg|thumb|Met need for family planning with modern contraception methods, Cameroon]]\n\n==== Under-5 Mortality and Neonatal Mortality ====\nGlobally in the year 2000, the Under-5 mortality rate was 43 per 1,000 and neonatal mortality rate (likelihood of dying in the first 28 days of life) was 31 per 1,000 <ref name=\":8\" />. Also globally, in 2017, the Under-5 morality and neonatal rates stood as 39 and 18<ref name=\":1\" /> . As for Cameroon, the Under-5 and Neonatal mortality rates have shown a decline from 135.6 and 39.3 in 1990 to 73.5 and 23.4 in 2017 respectively. \nMany kids still die before getting celebrating their 5th birthday in Cameroon.\n\n'''''Table 2: Under-5 Mortality and Neonatal Mortality rates 1990 - 2017'''''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Under-5 Mortality Rate !! Neonatal Mortality \n|-\n| 2017 || 73.5 || 23.4\n|-\n| 2016 || 77.5 || 24.3\n|-\n| 2015 || 81.5 || 24.9\n|-\n| 2010 || 103.0 || 28.1\n|-\n| 2005 || 122.5 || 31.2\n|-\n| 2000 || 134.2 || 32.9\n|-\n| 1995 || 139.1 || 37.3\n|-\n| 1990 || 135.6 || 39.3\n|}\n''Source:'' <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Road Injury ===\n\nTransport injury is among the several types of injury. Pedestrian, cyclist, motorcyclist locally called \"benskin\" or \"okada\", motor vehicles, are among the most used road transport in Cameroon. As of 2014, the number of vehicles was estimated at 675,000. Recording more than 16,000 road accidents per year with more than 1000 deaths. In addition to the human loss which is dramatic, the economic loss is estimated at 100 billion FCFA (approximately US Dollars 168 million) per year <ref name=\":4\" />. The estimated number of people killed per 100 million km driven was 73, which is more than 35 times higher than on similar roads in the US and Europe .\n<br>\n'''Road traffic injury''' is a major cause of death in Cameroon and among the top ten causes in 2018. The estimates of the deaths per 100,000 in the year 2017 from all transport injuries was 15.88 while road injury alone was 14.79 in Cameroon. Moreover, the deaths per 100,000 were 17.96 low income countries had as opposed to 10.39 in high income countries. In 2017 in Sub Saharan Africa, the number of deaths per from road traffic injuries were estimated at 161,648.<ref name=\":0\" /> Road traffic accidents are the largest cause of unintended injury in all regions, among low, middle income and high income countries. However, in developing countries, they have to deal with road accident in addition to  some communicable diseases which are not a major issue in the high income countries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Global Health 101. Third Edition|last=Skolnik|first=Richard|publisher=Michel Brown|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=|url-status=live}}</ref> This numbers of deaths from transport injury for Cameroon have increase from 3391 to 4408 in the last two decades with increasing number of  death recorded among he males population <ref name=\":3\" />.    \n[[File:Death_(Percentage)_due_to_Road_Injury_in_Cameroon,_2017_-_Distrbution_by_Sex.jpg|thumb|Percentage distribution by Sex of deaths due to Road Injury in Cameroon, 2017. Data from: https://vizhub.healthdata.org/gbd-compare/]]\nThese deaths could be as a result of several factors grouped into: transport operator (driver, cyclist, motorcyclist) factors, the state of the means of transport, the road or pavement, and also other environmental factors.   \n[[File:Age_Distribution_of_the_Death_due_to_Road_Injury_in_Cameroon,2017.jpg|thumb|Distribution of the Death due to Road Injury in Cameroon, 2017 - Distribution by Age. Data from https://vizhub.healthdata.org/gbd-compare/]]\n<br>\nThe Sustainable Development Goal number 3 (Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all ages) has nine major targets. The target number 6 which involves road injuries states:   \n\n* 3.6 By 2020 halve the number of global deaths and injury from road accident\n\n'''''Table 3: Number of deaths in Cameroon, Sub-Saharan Africa and the Globe from Traffic Injury (Road traffic Injury) 1990 - 2017'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Cameroon - Deaths from \nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury)\n! Sub-Saharan Region - Deaths from \nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury) \n!World - Deaths from\nTransport Injury (Road Traffic Injury)\n|-\n| 2017 || 4408 (4108) || 172,283 (161,647)\n|1,335,004 (1,243,068)\n|-\n| 2016 || 4441 (4119) || 170,780 (160,446)\n|1,345,442 (1,252,392)\n|-\n| 2015 || 4317 (4074) || 169,377 (159,036)\n|1,347,696 (1,252,514)\n|-\n| 2010 || 4356 (4053) || 167,183 (156,985)\n|1,394,717 (1,299,939)\n|-\n| 2005 || 3484 (3484) || 166,077 (155,417)\n|1,377,836 (1,284,407)\n|-\n| 2000 || 3391 (3158) || 162,369 (151,565)\n|1,376,105 (1,282,553)\n|-\n| 1990 || 2680 (2535) || 131,216 (124,172)\n|1,228,046 (1,150,717)\n|}\n\n''Source:''<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n'''Reports:''' Road Safety: Cameroon must redouble its effort and strengthen coordination<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |title=UNECE Cameroon Report |url=https://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/EPSR_Cameroun.pdf |website=www.unece.org |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Cameroon, ministry of transport in collaboration with other ministries have been enforcing several methods to reduce this deaths in several sensitization campaigns (in schools, sending short messages to subscribers phones, special back to school programs), teams to do unannounced controls, alcohol test for drivers, improving on the high way signs, rehabilitation of road etc. \nHowever, she needs to redouble her effort and improve coordination<ref name=\":4\" />, cooperation  with as well as human behavior in order to greatly reduce not only the number of deaths but also the [[Disability-adjusted life year]] DALYs which stands at 226,673  (157,195 for men)<ref name=\":3\" /> road injury alone for Cameroon.\n\n== United Nations: Sustainable Development Goals, SDGs 2016 - 2030 ==\nCameroon understands that the importance of the [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) cannot be over emphasized as the program takes into consideration the problems of development in the dimensions of security, economy, social, human and the environment <ref name=\":10\">RAPPORT DE LA SITUATION DE REFERENCE\n\nDES INDICATEURS DES OBJECTIFS DE DEVELOPPEMENT DURABLE AU\n\nCAMEROUN \n\n\n_version 26 novembre 2017.pdf</ref>. Cameroon adopted all 17 SDGs but also understands that it will be demanding for her in reporting and also in achieving the objectives. Main challenges identified were:\n* Inadequate mobilization of multiple stakeholders\n* Strengthening of the Statistical System for better monitoring\n* Mobilizing financial resources requested to achieve the SDGs <ref name=\":10\" /> <br>\n\nThe SGDs are implemented in Cameroon against the backdrop of an update of development policies and strategies resulting in the facilitation of their integration. In addition, for the conclusion of an economic and financial program, with the [[International Monetary Fund]] IMF, an interim development strategy has been prepared taking into account the contextualized SDGs. On security fronts, repeated attacks from the Boko Haram terrorist group in the Northern regions since 2014, flow of Central African refugees in the East region, and also the internal crisis in the North-West and South-West regions since 2017. These factors affect the mobilization of domestic funds which has negative impact on the achievement of SDGs <ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/memberstates/cameroon|title=Cameroon .:. Sustainable Development Knowledge Platform|website=sustainabledevelopment.un.org|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>.  Some strides have been made in the implementation of the Agenda 2030 in the areas of '''education, economic growth, policies and institutions''' but the aforementioned factors and host of other factors threaten even the little gains achieved in these areas <ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":12\">https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/24501CAMEROON_VNR_PPTENG_FINAL_VERSION.pdf</ref>.\n\n<br>\nKey factors identified to the success of the implementation of the SDGs will be their '''inclusion in the budget; and the enhancement of the statistical mechanism for the follow-up of the progress'''<ref name=\":11\" /> '''.''' <br>\nCameroon was part of the national voluntary review on the implementation of SDGs and the high level political forum on sustainable development New-York in July 2019. The government has indicated that concrete actions and strategies are needed to:\n* Intensify national ownership of the SDGs (inclusion in schools and university curricular and in extra-curricular activities)\n* Accelerate full integration of SDGs into daily public policies and programs\n* Establish a national multi-stakeholder monitoring body - as a review and accountability platform\n* Strengthen of the national statistical systems\n* Enlarge partnership and mobilize needed financial resources needed for the successful implementation of SDGs<ref name=\":12\" /> .\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unfpa.org/sowmy/resources/docs/country_info/profile/en_Cameroon_SoWMy_Profile.pdf The State of the World's Midwifery - Cameroom Country Profile]\n\n{{Africa in topic|Health in}}\n\n[[Category:Health in Cameroon| ]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Met need for family planing with modern contraception methods, Cameroon.jpg\u2192File:Met need for family planning with modern contraception methods, Cameroon.jpgtypo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_in_Cameroon"}
{"title_page": "Carbon Disclosure Project", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2007}}\n{{primary sources|date=March 2019}}\n{{advert|date=March 2019}}\n{{POV|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = CDP\n| former_name = Carbon Disclosure Project\n| logo = Carbon Disclosure Project logo.svg\n| logo_size = 220px\n| website = {{URL|https://www.cdp.net}}\n}}\nThe '''CDP''' (formerly the '''Carbon Disclosure Project''') is an organisation based in the United Kingdom which supports companies and cities to disclose the environmental impact of major corporations. It aims to make environmental reporting and [[risk management]] a business norm, and drive disclosure, insight and action towards a sustainable economy.<ref>{{cite web |title=CDP |url=https://www.rolls-royce.com/~/media/Files/R/Rolls-Royce/documents/sustainability/Supplier-docs/CDP.pdf |publisher=[[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> Since 2002 over 8,400 companies have publicly disclosed environmental information through CDP.\n\n== Background ==\nCDP piggybacked on [[Global Reporting Initiative|GRI]]'s concept of environmental disclosure in 2002, focusing on individual companies rather than on nations. At the time CDP had just 35 [[institutional investor|investor]]s signing its request for climate information and 245 companies responding. Today, nearly a fifth of global greenhouse gas emissions are reported through CDP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdp.net/en/investor/ghg-emissions-dataset|title=GHG Emissions Dataset |website=CDP|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nCDP works with investors, companies, cities, states and regions towards a water-secure world.<ref name=\"BASF\">{{cite web |title=BASF recognized as global leader in corporate climate action and water security |url=https://www.basf.com/global/en/media/news-releases/2019/01/p-19-121.html |publisher=[[BASF]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome corporations have higher [[greenhouse gas]] emissions than individual nation states. Some leading companies have moved to become carbon neutral, but for others there is the scope to reduce energy usage and greenhouse gas-emissions through the adoption of energy-efficiency methods and business planning.\n\n== Mechanism ==\nCDP works with over 6000 [[corporations]], as well as over 550 cities and 100 states and regions to help them ensure that an effective [[carbon emissions]] reductions strategy is made integral to their operations. The collection of self-reported data from thousands of companies is supported by over 800 institutional investors with about US$100 trillion in assets.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Carbon Disclosure Project |url=https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/services/sustainability/publications/carbon-disclosure-project.html |publisher=[[PWC]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> CDP operates from [[Berlin]], [[New York City|New York]], [[London]] and has partners in 18 of the world's major economies which help deliver the programme globally.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} It has:{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n* Established the most comprehensive collection of self-reported environmental data in the world, accounting for over 20% of global [[Anthropogenic greenhouse gases|anthropogenic]] emissions.\n* Started to establish a globally used standard for emissions and energy reporting\n* Examined the 250 major electric utilities globally (high GHG emitters)\n* Obtained backing{{clarify|date=March 2019}}{{dubious|date=March 2019|reason=\"Backing\" usually means financial backing. Is this what is meant here?}} from investors such as [[HSBC]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[Bank of America]], [[Merrill Lynch]], [[Goldman Sachs]], [[American International Group]], and State Street Corp.\n* Active staff or partner organisations in the United States, China, Japan, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Canada, India, Brazil, [[Nordic region]], South Africa, Netherlands, Australia, and New Zealand, among others.\n* Works with corporations including [[Walmart]], [[Tesco]], [[Cadbury Schweppes]], [[Procter and Gamble]], and many others to measure emissions through the supply chain.\n\nMuch of the data [[wikt:elicited|elicited]] has never been collected before. This information is helpful to investors,<ref>http://www.sri-connect.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=475:faq-do-investors-use-cdp-data&catid=132:take-control-of-sri-communications&Itemid=1112</ref> corporations, and regulators in making informed decisions on taking action towards a sustainable economy by measuring and understanding their environmental impact and taking meaningful steps to address and limit their risk to climate change, deforestation and water security.<ref name=BASF/>\n\n== CDP's programs ==\nCDP operates in most major economies worldwide and channels information and progress through individual programs. These are:\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150627221416/https://www.cdp.net/en-us/programmes/pages/climate-change-programs.aspx Climate Change]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150403101026/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/cdp-water-disclosure.aspx Water], [https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Supply-Chain.aspx Supply Chain]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150403100930/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx Forests]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150703021720/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Cities.aspx Cities]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nIts [https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200327/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx Carbon Action]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} initiative encourages investors to accelerate carbon reduction in high emitting industries and to implement emissions reducing projects that generate positive return on investment.\n\n=== Climate change ===\nCDP's climate change program aims to reduce companies' greenhouse gas emissions and mitigate climate change risk. CDP requests information on climate risks and low carbon opportunities from the world\u2019s largest companies on behalf of over 800 institutional investor signatories with a combined US$100 trillion in assets.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Investors.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526212355/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Investors.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-26}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== Water ===\nIn 2014, 573 investors used the CDP Water program, collectively representing US$60 trillion in assets.<ref>https://www.cdp.net/CDPResults/CDP-Global-Water-Report-2014.pdf</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} The program motivates companies to disclose and reduce their environmental impacts by using the power of investors and companies.\n\n=== Supply chain ===\nIn 2016, some 90 organizations, representing over US$2.5 trillion of purchasing power, requested that their suppliers disclose information on how they are approaching climate and water risks and opportunities. Data was gathered from over 4,000 suppliers worldwide,<ref>https://www.cdp.net/CDPResults/CDP-Supply-Chain-Report-2015.pdf</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} who reported over US$12 billion worth of savings from emission reduction activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3blmedia.com/News/Forging-Missing-Link-What-2017-CDP-Supply-Chain-Report-Says-About-Supplier-Engagement|title=Forging the Missing Link: What the 2017 CDP Supply Chain Report Says About Supplier Engagement|last=BSR|website=3blmedia.com|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Forests ===\nCDP's forests program has over 290 signatory investors in its network, which collectively represent about US$19 trillion in combined assets. CDP collects information from companies through the lens of the four agricultural commodities responsible for most deforestation: timber, palm oil, cattle and soy. CDP's forests program was first set up by the UK Government's Department for International Development via the Global Canopy Programme and the JMG Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403100930/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx |archivedate=2015-04-03}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== Cities ===\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20110728181527/https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Cities.aspx CDP Cities] provides the global platform for cities to measure, manage and disclose their environmental data. More than 500 cities are now measuring and disclosing environmental data on an annual basis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Half of European companies have no carbon reduction plan despite admitting climate change risks, report finds |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/19/half-of-european-companies-have-no-carbon-reduction-plan-report-finds.html |work=[[CNBC]] |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> The potential and need for this program is enormous since soon over half of the world\u2019s population will live in cities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Joel, E|title=The Human Population: the next half century|journal=Science|year=2003|volume=302|pages=1172\u20131175|doi=10.1126/science.1088665|pmid=14615528|issue=5648}}<!--|accessdate=4 March 2011--></ref> CDP Cities provides an easy to use global platform based upon a simple questionnaire that allows city governments to publicly disclose their greenhouse gas emission data. One of the greatest values of the annual report, first released in June 2011, is to city leaders who can identify peers who are addressing similar risks and issues with new and innovative strategies for reducing carbon emissions and for mitigating risk from climate change.\n\n=== Carbon Action initiative ===\nCarbon Action is an investor-led initiative which shows how companies in investment portfolios are managing carbon emissions and energy efficiency.\n\nOver 300 investors with US$25 trillion in assets under management ask the world's highest emitting companies to take three specific actions in response to climate change:\n* Make emissions reductions (year-on-year)\n* Publicly disclose emission reduction targets\n* Make ROI-positive investments in projects\n\nIn 2016, the Carbon Action request went to over 1300 of the highest emitters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200327/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-26}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nCDP launched a new research series at the beginning of 2015, taking a sector by sector approach.<ref>https://www.responsible-investor.com/home/article/cdp_auto_investor_research/</ref>\n\n== Leadership indices ==\nCDP recognizes companies with high-quality disclosure in its annual scoring process, with top companies making it onto CDP's A-list.{{Clarify|date=March 2019}}\n\nScores are calculated according to a standardized methodology which measures whether and how well, a company responds to each question. A company goes through four main steps, starting with disclosure of their current position, moving to awareness which looks at whether a company is conscious of it environmental impact, to management, and finally leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdp.net/en/guidance/guidance-for-companies|title=Guidance for companies |website=CDP|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nA high CDP score is usually indicative of a company's high environmental awareness, advanced sustainability governance and leadership to address climate change.\n\n== Relevance of CDP ==\n=== Studies on the CDP ===\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1080/09638180802489121|title=Corporate Responses in an Emerging Climate Regime: The Institutionalization and Commensuration of Carbon Disclosure|journal=European Accounting Review|volume=17|issue=4|pages=719\u2013745|year=2008|last1=Kolk|first1=Ans|last2=Levy|first2=David|last3=Pinkse|first3=Jonatan|url=http://dare.uva.nl/personal/pure/en/publications/corporate-responses-in-an-emerging-climate-regime-the-institutionalization-and-commensuration-of-carbon-disclosure(385b0cd4-0123-4ff4-90cf-7b3a2d15c506).html}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/smj.796|title=Responding to public and private politics: Corporate disclosure of climate change strategies|journal=Strategic Management Journal|volume=30|issue=11|pages=1157\u20131178|year=2009|last1=Reid|first1=Erin M.|last2=Toffel|first2=Michael W.|url=http://www.hbs.edu/research/pdf/09-019.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1162/GLEP_a_00057|title=The Limits of Carbon Disclosure: Theorizing the Business Case for Investor Environmentalism|journal=Global Environmental Politics|volume=11|issue=2|pages=98\u2013119|year=2011|last1=Harmes|first1=Adam}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2139/ssrn.1943690|title=Engaging Supply Chains in Climate Change|year=2012|last1=Jira|first1=Chonnikarn Fern|last2=Toffel|first2=Michael W.|url=http://www.hbs.edu/faculty/pages/download.aspx?name=12-026.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/bse.1741|title=Convergence in Environmental Reporting: Assessing the Carbon Disclosure Project|journal=Business Strategy and the Environment|volume=22|issue=5|pages=285\u2013305|year=2013|last1=Matisoff|first1=Daniel C.|last2=Noonan|first2=Douglas S.|last3=O'Brien|first3=John J.|hdl=1805/3573}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2202/1935-1682.2676|title=When Does Institutional Investor Activism Increase Shareholder Value?: The Carbon Disclosure Project|journal=The B.e. Journal of Economic Analysis & Policy|volume=11|year=2011|last1=Kim|first1=Eun-Hee|last2=Lyon|first2=Thomas}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/smj.2127|title=Difference in degrees: CEO characteristics and firm environmental disclosure|journal=Strategic Management Journal|volume=35|issue=5|pages=712\u2013722|year=2014|last1=Lewis|first1=Ben W.|last2=Walls|first2=Judith L.|last3=Dowell|first3=Glen W. S.|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2331&context=facpub}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2308/accr-50629|title=Firm-Value Effects of Carbon Emissions and Carbon Disclosures|journal=The Accounting Review|volume=89|issue=2|pages=695\u2013724|year=2014|last1=Matsumura|first1=Ella Mae|last2=Prakash|first2=Rachna|last3=Vera-Mu\u00f1oz|first3=Sandra C.}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1108/SAMPJ-09-2012-0030|title=Disclosure effects, carbon emissions and corporate value|journal=Sustainability Accounting, Management and Policy Journal|volume=5|pages=22\u201345|year=2014|last1=Saka|first1=Chika|last2=Oshika|first2=Tomoki}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/bse.1857|title=Adaptation Measures of Energy and Utility Companies to Cope with Water Scarcity Induced by Climate Change|journal=Business Strategy and the Environment|volume=25|pages=54\u201372|year=2016|last1=Gasbarro|first1=Federica|last2=Rizzi|first2=Francesco|last3=Frey|first3=Marco}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/csr.1369|title=Are Corporate Carbon Management Practices Reducing Corporate Carbon Emissions?|journal=Corporate Social Responsibility and Environmental Management|volume=23|issue=5|pages=257\u2013270|year=2016|last1=Doda|first1=Baran|last2=Gennaioli|first2=Caterina|last3=Gouldson|first3=Andy|last4=Grover|first4=David|last5=Sullivan|first5=Rory|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/90725/8/Doda_et_al-2015-Corporate_Social_Responsibility_and_Environmental_Management.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.ecolecon.2014.11.010|title=Unraveling the effects of environmental outcomes and processes on financial performance: A non-linear approach|journal=Ecological Economics|volume=109|pages=150\u2013160|year=2015|last1=Misani|first1=Nicola|last2=Pogutz|first2=Stefano|url=https://mpra.ub.uni-muenchen.de/60359/1/MPRA_paper_60359.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.5890/JEAM.2018.09.001|title=Impact of Climate Change Disclosure on Financial Performance: An Analysis of Indian Firms|journal=Journal of Environmental Accounting and Management|volume=6|issue=3|pages=185\u2013197|year=2018|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1108/MF-03-2018-0108|title=Impact of carbon emissions on cost of debt-evidence from India|journal=Managerial Finance|volume=44|issue=12|pages=1401\u20131417|year=2018|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.5890/JEAM.2019.03.004|title=What Drives the Voluntary Environmental Reporting (VER): An Examination of CDP India Firms|journal=Journal of Environmental Accounting and Management|volume=7|pages=47\u201359|year=2019|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.14453/aabfj.v13i2.2|title=Do Women on Boards Influence Climate Change Disclosures to CDP? \u2013 Evidence from Large Indian Companies|journal=Australasian Accounting, Business and Finance Journal|volume=13|issue=2|pages=5\u201331|year=2019|last1=Charumathi|first1=B.|last2=Rahman|first2=Habeebu}}\n\n=== Corporate recognition of the CDP ===\nThe CDP has 525 institutional investors in its network, holding US$96 trillion in assets.<ref name=about-us>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en/info/about-us |title=About us |publisher=CDP |accessdate=2019-03-21}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} In 2010, CDP was called \"The most powerful green NGO you've never heard of\" by the Harvard Business Review.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://blogs.hbr.org/winston/2010/10/the-most-powerful-green-ngo.html|author=Andrew Winston  |date=October 5, 2010|title=The Most Powerful Green NGO You've Never Heard Of|accessdate=Oct 26, 2012}}\n</ref> In 2012 it won the Zayed Future Energy Prize.<ref>ZaYed Future Energy Prize, 2012 Winners {{cite web |url=https://www.zayedfutureenergyprize.com/en/winners-and-runners_up |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615223004/http://www.zayedfutureenergyprize.com/en/winners-and-runners_up |archivedate=2012-06-15 }}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate participants ===\nSome of the corporate participants:{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}{{clarify|date=March 2019|reason=Is this the list of the \"investors\" in the CDP's network, or the \"companies\"?}}\n* [[Apple Inc.]]\n* [[CenturyLink]] (which acquired [[Level 3 Communications]])\n* [[Siemens]]\n* [[T\u00fcrkiye Sanayi Kalk\u0131nma Bankas\u0131]]\n* [[Dell]]\n* [[Hewlett Packard]]\n* [[L'Or\u00e9al]]\n* [[KLA-Tencor|KLA]]\n* [[PepsiCo]]\n* [[Cadbury Schweppes]]\n* [[Nestl\u00e9]]\n* [[Procter & Gamble]]\n* [[Tesco]]\n* [[Unilever]]\n* [[Lloyds TSB]]\n* [[Amcor]]\n* [[Johnson Controls]]\n* [[Metro-Richelieu]]\n* [[Schneider Electric]]\n* [[NH Hoteles]]\n* [[Ventas, Inc.]]\n* [[Ipsos Group SA]]\n* [[Xylem Inc.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sustainability.xylem.com/sustainability/strategy.html |title=2017 Sustainability Report |publisher=Xylem |accessdate=2019-03-21}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Carbon accounting]]\n*[[Carbon footprint]]\n*[[Global warming]]\n*[[Greenhouse debt]]\n*[[Science Based Targets]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://www.cdp.net}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120124122914/https://www.cdproject.net/Documents/CDP-Cities-2011-Report.pdf 2011 (first) annual report from the CDP Cities program]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070821002227/http://www.cdproject.net/ About the Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Environmental science]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gases]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas inventories]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2007}}\n{{primary sources|date=March 2019}}\n{{advert|date=March 2019}}\n{{POV|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = CDP\n| former_name = Carbon Disclosure Project\n| logo = Carbon Disclosure Project logo.svg\n| logo_size = 220px\n| website = {{URL|https://www.cdp.net}}\n}}\nThe '''CDP''' (formerly the '''Carbon Disclosure Project''') is an organisation based in the United Kingdom which supports companies and cities to disclose the environmental impact of major corporations. It aims to make environmental reporting and [[risk management]] a business norm, and drive disclosure, insight and action towards a sustainable economy.<ref>{{cite web |title=CDP |url=https://www.rolls-royce.com/~/media/Files/R/Rolls-Royce/documents/sustainability/Supplier-docs/CDP.pdf |publisher=[[Rolls-Royce]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> Since 2002 over 8,400 companies have publicly disclosed environmental information through CDP.\n\n== Background ==\nCDP piggybacked on [[Global Reporting Initiative|GRI]]'s concept of environmental disclosure in 2002, focusing on individual companies rather than on nations. At the time CDP had just 35 [[institutional investor|investor]]s signing its request for climate information and 245 companies responding. Today, nearly a fifth of global greenhouse gas emissions are reported through CDP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdp.net/en/investor/ghg-emissions-dataset|title=GHG Emissions Dataset |website=CDP|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nCDP works with investors, companies, cities, states and regions towards a water-secure world.<ref name=\"BASF\">{{cite web |title=BASF recognized as global leader in corporate climate action and water security |url=https://www.basf.com/global/en/media/news-releases/2019/01/p-19-121.html |publisher=[[BASF]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome corporations have higher [[greenhouse gas]] emissions than individual nation states. Some leading companies have moved to become carbon neutral, but for others there is the scope to reduce energy usage and greenhouse gas-emissions through the adoption of energy-efficiency methods and business planning.\n\n== Mechanism ==\nCDP works with over 6000 [[corporations]], as well as over 550 cities and 100 states and regions to help them ensure that an effective [[carbon emissions]] reductions strategy is made integral to their operations. The collection of self-reported data from thousands of companies is supported by over 800 institutional investors with about US$100 trillion in assets.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Carbon Disclosure Project |url=https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/services/sustainability/publications/carbon-disclosure-project.html |publisher=[[PWC]] |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> CDP operates from [[Berlin]], [[New York City|New York]], [[London]] and has partners in 18 of the world's major economies which help deliver the programme globally.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} It has:{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n* Established the most comprehensive collection of self-reported environmental data in the world, accounting for over 20% of global [[Anthropogenic greenhouse gases|anthropogenic]] emissions.\n* Started to establish a globally used standard for emissions and energy reporting\n* Examined the 250 major electric utilities globally (high GHG emitters)\n* Obtained backing{{clarify|date=March 2019}}{{dubious|date=March 2019|reason=\"Backing\" usually means financial backing. Is this what is meant here?}} from investors such as [[HSBC]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[Bank of America]], [[Merrill Lynch]], [[Goldman Sachs]], [[American International Group]], and State Street Corp.\n* Active staff or partner organisations in the United States, China, Japan, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Canada, India, Brazil, [[Nordic region]], South Africa, Netherlands, Australia, and New Zealand, among others.\n* Works with corporations including [[Walmart]], [[Tesco]], [[Cadbury Schweppes]], [[Procter and Gamble]], and many others to measure emissions through the supply chain.\n\nMuch of the data [[wikt:elicited|elicited]] has never been collected before. This information is helpful to investors,<ref>http://www.sri-connect.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=475:faq-do-investors-use-cdp-data&catid=132:take-control-of-sri-communications&Itemid=1112</ref> corporations, and regulators in making informed decisions on taking action towards a sustainable economy by measuring and understanding their environmental impact and taking meaningful steps to address and limit their risk to climate change, deforestation and water security.<ref name=BASF/>\n\n== CDP's programs ==\nCDP operates in most major economies worldwide and channels information and progress through individual programs. These are:\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150627221416/https://www.cdp.net/en-us/programmes/pages/climate-change-programs.aspx Climate Change]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150403101026/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/cdp-water-disclosure.aspx Water], [https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Supply-Chain.aspx Supply Chain]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150403100930/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx Forests]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150703021720/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Cities.aspx Cities]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nIts [https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200327/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx Carbon Action]{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} initiative encourages investors to accelerate carbon reduction in high emitting industries and to implement emissions reducing projects that generate positive return on investment.\n\n=== Climate change ===\nCDP's climate change program aims to reduce companies' greenhouse gas emissions and mitigate climate change risk. CDP requests information on climate risks and low carbon opportunities from the world\u2019s largest companies on behalf of over 800 institutional investor signatories with a combined US$100 trillion in assets.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Investors.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526212355/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Investors.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-26}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== Water ===\nIn 2014, 573 investors used the CDP Water program, collectively representing US$60 trillion in assets.<ref>https://www.cdp.net/CDPResults/CDP-Global-Water-Report-2014.pdf</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} The program motivates companies to disclose and reduce their environmental impacts by using the power of investors and companies.\n\n=== Supply chain ===\nIn 2016, some 90 organizations, representing over US$2.5 trillion of purchasing power, requested that their suppliers disclose information on how they are approaching climate and water risks and opportunities. Data was gathered from over 4,000 suppliers worldwide,<ref>https://www.cdp.net/CDPResults/CDP-Supply-Chain-Report-2015.pdf</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} who reported over US$12 billion worth of savings from emission reduction activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3blmedia.com/News/Forging-Missing-Link-What-2017-CDP-Supply-Chain-Report-Says-About-Supplier-Engagement|title=Forging the Missing Link: What the 2017 CDP Supply Chain Report Says About Supplier Engagement|last=BSR|website=3blmedia.com|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Forests ===\nCDP's forests program has over 290 signatory investors in its network, which collectively represent about US$19 trillion in combined assets. CDP collects information from companies through the lens of the four agricultural commodities responsible for most deforestation: timber, palm oil, cattle and soy. CDP's forests program was first set up by the UK Government's Department for International Development via the Global Canopy Programme and the JMG Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403100930/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/forests.aspx |archivedate=2015-04-03}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== Cities ===\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20110728181527/https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Cities.aspx CDP Cities] provides the global platform for cities to measure, manage and disclose their environmental data. More than 500 cities are now measuring and disclosing environmental data on an annual basis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Half of European companies have no carbon reduction plan despite admitting climate change risks, report finds |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/19/half-of-european-companies-have-no-carbon-reduction-plan-report-finds.html |work=[[CNBC]] |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> The potential and need for this program is enormous since soon over half of the world\u2019s population will live in cities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Joel, E|title=The Human Population: the next half century|journal=Science|year=2003|volume=302|pages=1172\u20131175|doi=10.1126/science.1088665|pmid=14615528|issue=5648}}<!--|accessdate=4 March 2011--></ref> CDP Cities provides an easy to use global platform based upon a simple questionnaire that allows city governments to publicly disclose their greenhouse gas emission data. One of the greatest values of the annual report, first released in June 2011, is to city leaders who can identify peers who are addressing similar risks and issues with new and innovative strategies for reducing carbon emissions and for mitigating risk from climate change.\n\n=== Carbon Action initiative ===\nCarbon Action is an investor-led initiative which shows how companies in investment portfolios are managing carbon emissions and energy efficiency.\n\nOver 300 investors with US$25 trillion in assets under management ask the world's highest emitting companies to take three specific actions in response to climate change:\n* Make emissions reductions (year-on-year)\n* Publicly disclose emission reduction targets\n* Make ROI-positive investments in projects\n\nIn 2016, the Carbon Action request went to over 1300 of the highest emitters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200327/https://www.cdp.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/Initiatives-CDP-Carbon-Action.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-26}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nCDP launched a new research series at the beginning of 2015, taking a sector by sector approach.<ref>https://www.responsible-investor.com/home/article/cdp_auto_investor_research/</ref>\n\n== Leadership indices ==\nCDP recognizes companies with high-quality disclosure in its annual scoring process, with top companies making it onto CDP's A-list.{{Clarify|date=March 2019}}\n\nScores are calculated according to a standardized methodology which measures whether and how well, a company responds to each question. A company goes through four main steps, starting with disclosure of their current position, moving to awareness which looks at whether a company is conscious of it environmental impact, to management, and finally leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdp.net/en/guidance/guidance-for-companies|title=Guidance for companies |website=CDP|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nA high CDP score is usually indicative of a company's high environmental awareness, advanced sustainability governance and leadership to address climate change.\n\n== Relevance of CDP ==\n=== Studies on the CDP ===\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1080/09638180802489121|title=Corporate Responses in an Emerging Climate Regime: The Institutionalization and Commensuration of Carbon Disclosure|journal=European Accounting Review|volume=17|issue=4|pages=719\u2013745|year=2008|last1=Kolk|first1=Ans|last2=Levy|first2=David|last3=Pinkse|first3=Jonatan|url=http://dare.uva.nl/personal/pure/en/publications/corporate-responses-in-an-emerging-climate-regime-the-institutionalization-and-commensuration-of-carbon-disclosure(385b0cd4-0123-4ff4-90cf-7b3a2d15c506).html}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/smj.796|title=Responding to public and private politics: Corporate disclosure of climate change strategies|journal=Strategic Management Journal|volume=30|issue=11|pages=1157\u20131178|year=2009|last1=Reid|first1=Erin M.|last2=Toffel|first2=Michael W.|url=http://www.hbs.edu/research/pdf/09-019.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1162/GLEP_a_00057|title=The Limits of Carbon Disclosure: Theorizing the Business Case for Investor Environmentalism|journal=Global Environmental Politics|volume=11|issue=2|pages=98\u2013119|year=2011|last1=Harmes|first1=Adam}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2139/ssrn.1943690|title=Engaging Supply Chains in Climate Change|year=2012|last1=Jira|first1=Chonnikarn Fern|last2=Toffel|first2=Michael W.|url=http://www.hbs.edu/faculty/pages/download.aspx?name=12-026.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/bse.1741|title=Convergence in Environmental Reporting: Assessing the Carbon Disclosure Project|journal=Business Strategy and the Environment|volume=22|issue=5|pages=285\u2013305|year=2013|last1=Matisoff|first1=Daniel C.|last2=Noonan|first2=Douglas S.|last3=O'Brien|first3=John J.|hdl=1805/3573}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2202/1935-1682.2676|title=When Does Institutional Investor Activism Increase Shareholder Value?: The Carbon Disclosure Project|journal=The B.e. Journal of Economic Analysis & Policy|volume=11|year=2011|last1=Kim|first1=Eun-Hee|last2=Lyon|first2=Thomas}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/smj.2127|title=Difference in degrees: CEO characteristics and firm environmental disclosure|journal=Strategic Management Journal|volume=35|issue=5|pages=712\u2013722|year=2014|last1=Lewis|first1=Ben W.|last2=Walls|first2=Judith L.|last3=Dowell|first3=Glen W. S.|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2331&context=facpub}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2308/accr-50629|title=Firm-Value Effects of Carbon Emissions and Carbon Disclosures|journal=The Accounting Review|volume=89|issue=2|pages=695\u2013724|year=2014|last1=Matsumura|first1=Ella Mae|last2=Prakash|first2=Rachna|last3=Vera-Mu\u00f1oz|first3=Sandra C.}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1108/SAMPJ-09-2012-0030|title=Disclosure effects, carbon emissions and corporate value|journal=Sustainability Accounting, Management and Policy Journal|volume=5|pages=22\u201345|year=2014|last1=Saka|first1=Chika|last2=Oshika|first2=Tomoki}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/bse.1857|title=Adaptation Measures of Energy and Utility Companies to Cope with Water Scarcity Induced by Climate Change|journal=Business Strategy and the Environment|volume=25|pages=54\u201372|year=2016|last1=Gasbarro|first1=Federica|last2=Rizzi|first2=Francesco|last3=Frey|first3=Marco}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1002/csr.1369|title=Are Corporate Carbon Management Practices Reducing Corporate Carbon Emissions?|journal=Corporate Social Responsibility and Environmental Management|volume=23|issue=5|pages=257\u2013270|year=2016|last1=Doda|first1=Baran|last2=Gennaioli|first2=Caterina|last3=Gouldson|first3=Andy|last4=Grover|first4=David|last5=Sullivan|first5=Rory|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/90725/8/Doda_et_al-2015-Corporate_Social_Responsibility_and_Environmental_Management.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.ecolecon.2014.11.010|title=Unraveling the effects of environmental outcomes and processes on financial performance: A non-linear approach|journal=Ecological Economics|volume=109|pages=150\u2013160|year=2015|last1=Misani|first1=Nicola|last2=Pogutz|first2=Stefano|url=https://mpra.ub.uni-muenchen.de/60359/1/MPRA_paper_60359.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.5890/JEAM.2018.09.001|title=Impact of Climate Change Disclosure on Financial Performance: An Analysis of Indian Firms|journal=Journal of Environmental Accounting and Management|volume=6|issue=3|pages=185\u2013197|year=2018|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1108/MF-03-2018-0108|title=Impact of carbon emissions on cost of debt-evidence from India|journal=Managerial Finance|volume=44|issue=12|pages=1401\u20131417|year=2018|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.5890/JEAM.2019.03.004|title=What Drives the Voluntary Environmental Reporting (VER): An Examination of CDP India Firms|journal=Journal of Environmental Accounting and Management|volume=7|pages=47\u201359|year=2019|last1=Kumar|first1=Praveen|last2=Firoz|first2=Mohammad}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.14453/aabfj.v13i2.2|title=Do Women on Boards Influence Climate Change Disclosures to CDP? \u2013 Evidence from Large Indian Companies|journal=Australasian Accounting, Business and Finance Journal|volume=13|issue=2|pages=5\u201331|year=2019|last1=Charumathi|first1=B.|last2=Rahman|first2=Habeebu}}\n\n=== Corporate recognition of the CDP ===\nThe CDP has 525 institutional investors in its network, holding US$96 trillion in assets.<ref name=about-us>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdp.net/en/info/about-us |title=About us |publisher=CDP |accessdate=2019-03-21}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}} In 2010, CDP was called \"The most powerful green NGO you've never heard of\" by the Harvard Business Review.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://blogs.hbr.org/winston/2010/10/the-most-powerful-green-ngo.html|author=Andrew Winston  |date=October 5, 2010|title=The Most Powerful Green NGO You've Never Heard Of|accessdate=Oct 26, 2012}}\n</ref> In 2012 it won the Zayed Future Energy Prize.<ref>ZaYed Future Energy Prize, 2012 Winners {{cite web |url=https://www.zayedfutureenergyprize.com/en/winners-and-runners_up |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615223004/http://www.zayedfutureenergyprize.com/en/winners-and-runners_up |archivedate=2012-06-15 }}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate participants ===\nSome of the corporate participants:{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}{{clarify|date=March 2019|reason=Is this the list of the \"investors\" in the CDP's network, or the \"companies\"?}}\n* [[Apple Inc.]]\n* [[CenturyLink]] (which acquired [[Level 3 Communications]])\n* [[Siemens]]\n* [[T\u00fcrkiye Sanayi Kalk\u0131nma Bankas\u0131]]\n* [[Dell]]\n* [[Hewlett Packard]]\n* [[L'Or\u00e9al]]\n* [[KLA-Tencor|KLA]]\n* [[PepsiCo]]\n* [[Cadbury Schweppes]]\n* [[Nestl\u00e9]]\n* [[Procter & Gamble]]\n* [[Tesco]]\n* [[Unilever]]\n* [[Lloyds TSB]]\n* [[Amcor]]\n* [[Johnson Controls]]\n* [[Metro-Richelieu]]\n* [[Schneider Electric]]\n* [[NH Hoteles]]\n* [[Ventas, Inc.]]\n* [[Ipsos Group SA]]\n* [[Xylem Inc.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sustainability.xylem.com/sustainability/strategy.html |title=2017 Sustainability Report |publisher=Xylem |accessdate=2019-03-21}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Carbon accounting]]\n*[[Carbon footprint]]\n*[[Global warming]]\n*[[Greenhouse debt]]\n*[[Science Based Targets]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://www.cdp.net}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120124122914/https://www.cdproject.net/Documents/CDP-Cities-2011-Report.pdf 2011 (first) annual report from the CDP Cities program]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070821002227/http://www.cdproject.net/ About the Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Environmental science]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gases]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions]]\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas inventories]]\n", "name_user": "LittleWink", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repairing links toRolls-Royce(link changed toRolls-Royce Holdings)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_Disclosure_Project"}
{"title_page": "Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum\n| image       =Miguel Facusse.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Miguel Facuss\u00e9, former Executive President, Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |1924|08|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Tegucigalpa]], [[Honduras]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2015|6|23|1924|8|14}}\n| alma mater  = [[University of Notre Dame]]\n| occupation  = President of ''Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant''\n\n}}\n\n'''Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum''' (August 14, 1924 \u2013 June 23, 2015) was a [[Honduras|Honduran]] businessman and landowner.<ref name=death>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.elheraldo.hn/pais/852053-214/muere-el-empresario-miguel-facusse\n|title=Muere el empresario hondure\u00f1o Miguel Facuss\u00e9\n|date=June 23, 2015\n|newspaper=El Heraldo\n|accessdate=June 23, 2015\n|language=Spanish\n}} \n</ref> He was Executive President of Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant, a consumer products manufacturing company he founded in Honduras in 1960. Dinant sells its products throughout [[Central America]] and the [[Dominican Republic]], and also exports to global markets.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Our History\n|url=http://www.dinant.com/index.php/en/quienes-somos|publisher=Corporacion Dinant\n|accessdate=January 31, 2015\n}}\n</ref> A 2006 study by the [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]] named Facuss\u00e9 one of the three \"most powerful men in Honduras\".<ref>Thelma Mej\u00eda, [[Inter Press Service]], 15 December 2006, [http://www.ipsnews.net/2006/12/honduras-governed-by-vested-interests/ HONDURAS: Governed by Vested Interests]</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was the chief economic advisor to President [[Roberto Suazo C\u00f3rdova]]<ref name=Rockwell/> during his term in office from 1982 to 1986 and vice-president of APROH, a \"right-wing grouping of business interests and members of the armed forces\"<ref name=Routledge2001/> from the early 1980s<ref name=Maolain/> to at least 2001. Facuss\u00e9 was married and had nine children.<ref name=LaTribuna/><ref name=RSF>[[Reporters without Borders]], 2 May 2012, [http://en.rsf.org/honduras-miguel-facusse-barjum-02-05-2012,42452.html Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum , Businessman and landowner, Honduras], accessed 11 October 2012</ref> His nephew, [[Carlos Roberto Flores]], was President of Honduras from 1998 to 2002. His son-in-law, [[Fredy Nasser]], is a prominent Honduran businessman. In May 2009, Facuss\u00e9 was awarded the ''Orden M\u00e9rito a la Democracia en el Grado de Gran Caballero'' by the [[Senate of Colombia]].<ref name=LaTribuna/> In August 2014, he was awarded the CEAL Founders' Award for his pioneering role in promoting business between Latin American nations.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=CEAL premia al empresario Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barj\u00fam\n|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/08/06/ceal-premia-al\u00e9\u00e9-empresario-miguel-facusse-barjum/\n|newspaper=La Tribuna\n|date=6 August 2014\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=MIGUEL FACUSSE BARJUM HONORED FOR LIFETIME CONTRIBUTION TO LATIN AMERICA\n|url=http://www.dinant.com/index.php/en/sala-de-prensa/comunicados/302-miguel-facusse-barjum-honored-for-lifetime-contribution-to-latin-america/\n|publisher=Corporacion Dinant\n|date=20 October 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMiguel Facuss\u00e9 was born in [[Tegucigalpa]], Honduras in 1924,<ref name=LaTribuna>{{in lang|es}} ''[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]'', 24 May 2009, [http://old.latribuna.hn/2009/05/24/post10064872/ Senado de Colombia condecora al empresario Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202110131/http://old.latribuna.hn/2009/05/24/post10064872/ |date=2014-02-02 }}</ref> the seventh of nine children of Nichol\u00e1s and Mar\u00eda Barjum de Facuss\u00e9 and his family is of [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] descent.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103>{{in lang|es}} {{cite news|title=Cohep reconoce trayectoria empresarial de Miguel Facuss\u00e9|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/11/03/cohep-reconoce-trayectoria-empresarial-de-miguel-facusse/|accessdate=25 January 2013|newspaper=[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]] (Honduras)|date=3 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112235946/http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/11/03/cohep-reconoce-trayectoria-empresarial-de-miguel-facusse/|archive-date=12 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFacuss\u00e9 earned a degree in [[aeronautical engineering]] in 1944 at the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilberto Nuila Coto, Msc.|first=Ram\u00f3n|title=Zacate Grande: Una gran visita|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/04/15/zacate-grande-una-gran-visita/|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=La Tribuna|date=12 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123184414/http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/04/15/zacate-grande-una-gran-visita/|archive-date=23 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Malloy 2004\">{{cite book|last=Malloy|first=Edward A.|title=Monk's travels : People, Places, and Events|year=2004|publisher=Andrews McMeel Pub.|location=Kansas City|isbn=0-7407-4706-1|url=https://archive.org/details/monkstravels00edwa|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/monkstravels00edwa/page/94 94]}}</ref> Facuss\u00e9 hosted [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] University President [[Theodore Hesburgh|Rev. Theodore M. Hesburgh, CSC]] during a visit to Honduras in 1960 <ref>{{cite news|title=Our Family To The South|url=http://www.archives.nd.edu/Alumnus/VOL_0038/VOL_0038_ISSUE_0004.pdf|accessdate=25 January 2013|newspaper=Notre Dame Alumnus Magazine|date=November 1960}}</ref> and [[Edward Malloy|Rev. Edward \"Monk\" Malloy, CSC]] in 2003.<ref name=\"Malloy 2004\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Costa Rica===\nIn 1944, Facuss\u00e9 moved to Costa Rica, where he converted warplanes into commercial cargo airliners. He quickly became general manager of a multinational corporation that reconstructed and maintained wartime aircraft from all over the world.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103/>\n\n===1960s===\nAfter returning to Tegucigalpa, Facuss\u00e9 worked in his brother's textile company.  Facuss\u00e9 set up ''Qu\u00edmicas Dinant de Centroam\u00e9rica SA'' in July 1960. In the late 1960s, Facuss\u00e9 won contracts with [[Procter & Gamble]] to produce and distribute its products in Honduras, El Salvador, and Guatemala.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103/>\n\nIn 1969, Facuss\u00e9 was president of both the Honduras Industrial Association and the Central American Industrial Association.  At the time, Facuss\u00e9 owned Qu\u00edmicas Dinant, a company that made soaps and detergents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class Notes for Class of 1944|url=http://www.archives.nd.edu/Alumnus/VOL_0047/VOL_0047_ISSUE_0006.pdf|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=Notre Dame Alumnus Magazine|date=September 1969}}</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nIn the 1970s, Facuss\u00e9 created a small factory making detergents and soaps for Qu\u00edmicas Dinant. He did so with support from the private international banking sector and credit from the Corporaci\u00f3n Nacional de Inversiones ([[CONADI]]), created by the state in 1974 as part of the strategy to consolidate the new Industrial Model for Substituting Imports (ISI).<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum\n|url=http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html\n|work=Historical Survey|publisher=Bolpress \n|via=Derechos.org)\n|accessdate=28 January 2013\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nIn the early 1980s, Facuss\u00e9 was the chief economic advisor to President [[Roberto Suazo C\u00f3rdova]]<ref name=Rockwell/> (in office 1982 to 1986). During this time Facuss\u00e9 helped his nephew, [[Carlos Roberto Flores]], (who later went on to become president of Honduras) become a political advisor to Suazo.<ref name=Rockwell>Rick Rockwell, Noreene Janus (2003), ''Media Power in Central America'', [[University of Illinois Press]], p21</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, Facuss\u00e9 was also vice-president of the ''Asociaci\u00f3n para el Progreso de Honduras'' (APROH), an organization officially founded in January 1983<ref>Henry W. Degenhardt (1988), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=DVmGAAAAMAAJ Revolutionary and dissident movements: an international guide]'', Longman p149</ref> linking business leaders and military personnel (head of the armed forces [[Gustavo \u00c1lvarez Mart\u00ednez]] was elected its first president).<ref name=Maolain>Listed as \"vice-president\" alongside \"Gen. (retd) Gustavo Alvarez Martinez\" as \"leader\" in Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Maol\u00e1in (ed, 1985), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=GxUPAAAAYAAJ Latin American Political Movements]'', Longman, p159</ref><ref>James D. Rudolph (1983),[https://books.google.com/books?id=9tJqAAAAMAAJ Honduras, a country study: Volume 550, Issues 151\u2013152], American University (Washington, D.C.). Foreign Area Studies, United States. Dept. of the Army, p172</ref><ref>{{in lang|es}} [[Bolpress]], 4 June 2012, [http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum]</ref><ref>Described as \"APROH co-ordinator\" in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=E6IpAQAAIAAJ Business Week, Issues 2788\u20132796]'', [[McGraw-Hill]], 1983, p75</ref><ref>Listed as \"vice-president\" in Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Maol\u00e1in (1987), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=d9wPAQAAMAAJ The radical right: a world directory]'', Longman, p152</ref> A \"widely publicised memorandum\" by Facuss\u00e9 \"argued that the only way out of the national crisis was to 'sell Honduras to the foreign investor'\".<ref>Richard Lapper, James Painter (1985), Latin America Bureau, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=2doXAAAAYAAJ Honduras, state for sale]\", Latin America Bureau special brief, p100</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was still listed as Vice-President of APROH in 2001.<ref name=Routledge2001>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=o9ODxqsr-dIC South America, Central America and the Caribbean]\", ''Regional Surveys of the World Series'', 10th Edition 2002, [[Routledge]] 2001, p496</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nFacuss\u00e9 was president of the Cressida Corporation, which in the 1990s received a $55m investment loan from the World Bank.<ref>''Revista Envio'', [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/3010 Maquila*: The Swallow That Lays Golden Eggs], Number 194, September 1997.</ref> In 2000 Facuss\u00e9 sold Cressida, which had subsidiaries throughout Central America and was at the time described as \"the biggest food and cleaning products manufacturer in Honduras\" to [[Unilever]] for $322m for an estimated net profit to Facuss\u00e9 of $120m.<ref name=EIU>\n{{cite web\n|work=[[Economist Intelligence Unit]]\n|date=11 May 2000\n|url= http://www.eiu.com/index.asp?layout=VWArticleVW3&article_id=904744890\n|title=Article Country Briefing: Honduras finance: Regional links attract foreign direct investments\n}}\n</ref> Facuss\u00e9 had previously sold the brand ''Magia Blanca'' and others to [[Procter & Gamble]] for over $25m.<ref name=EIU/>\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2011, Facuss\u00e9 remained the owner of Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant, which owned over 22,000 acres of palm plantations in [[Bajo Agu\u00e1n]].<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', September 15, 2011 [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/16/world/americas/honduras-land-conflicts-highlight-polarization.html?pagewanted=all In Honduras, Land Struggles Highlight Post-Coup Polarization]</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was described in 2012 by [[Reporters without Borders]] as having, \"a private militia that can count on support from the police and army to impose his will\".<ref name=RSF/> Reporters without Borders previously had called upon Facuss\u00e9 to respond publicly after the president of La Voz de [[Zacate Grande]], a radio station involved in a land struggle against Facuss\u00e9, was shot in 2011.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.rsf-es.org/news/honduras-herido-de-bala-en-un-atentado-el-director-de-la-voz-de-zacate-grande/\n|title=Herido de bala en un atentado el director de La Voz de Zacate Grande\n|date=17 March 2011\n|publisher=[[Reporters without Borders]]\n|accessdate=2013-11-20\n}} (Spanish)\n</ref> Accusations that Facuss\u00e9's militia had killed agricultural workers who had occupied his land led to the withdrawal in 2011 of a $20m investment loan from the German,<ref name=TheNation>\n{{cite news\n|author=Dana Frank\n|work=[[The Nation]]\n|date=21 October 2011\n|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/164120/wikileaks-honduras-us-linked-brutal-businessman \n|title=WikiLeaks Honduras: US Linked to Brutal Businessman\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|author1=Mathew Carr\n|author2=Catherine Airlie\n|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]\n|date=21 April 2011\n|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-21/-misleading-claims-harm-honduras-emissions-project-owner-executive-says.html\n|title=\u2018Misleading\u2019 Claims Harm Honduras Emissions-Project Owner, Executive Says\n}}\n</ref> and to [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]] cancelling the purchase of [[carbon credit]]s from Dinant.<ref name=Ramsey>\n{{cite web\n|author=Geoffrey Ramsey\n|work=[[InSight Crime]]\n|date=18 May 2012\n|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/honduran-tycoon-accused-of-drug-ties-named-press-predator\n|title=Honduran Tycoon Accused of Drug Ties Named 'Press Predator'\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHowever the [[United Nations]] continued to back two Dinant palm-oil-waste-to-[[biogas]] projects through its [[Clean Development Mechanism]].<ref name=Kryt/> Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant denied committing [[human rights]] violations or forcibly evicting intruders from its land. It claimed that \"externally funded armed groups, with no interest in farming, are using the conflicts in Honduras for wider political ends by encouraging the illegal seizure of private lands.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title=Dinant has never committed human rights violations against protesters\n|url=http://timeli.info/item/1613541/The_Guardian_World_News/Dinant_has_never_committed_human_rights_violations_against_protesters____guardianletters___World_...\n|newspaper=The Guardian\n|date=7 May 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\nMedia reports and leaked US Embassy cables published by [[WikiLeaks]] suggest that an airstrip on Facuss\u00e9's property has been used for to transit cocaine.<ref name=TheNation/><ref name=Ramsey/><ref name=Kryt>\n{{cite news\n|author=Jeremy Kryt\n|work=[[In These Times]]\n|date=30 November 2011\n|url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/12285/carbon_credits_in_the_valley_of_death/ \n|title=Carbon Credits in the \u2018Valley of Death\u2019\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|author=hondurasnews\n|url=http://www.hondurasnews.com/wikileaks-cable-re-honduras-031904/ \n|title=WikiLeaks Cable Re: Honduras 03/19/04}}\n</ref> Facuss\u00e9 denied ever having been involved in any activities related to drug trafficking, claiming instead to help drug enforcement authorities by reporting illegal activities on Dinant\u2019s property.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Re: Counter Punch article on \"Obama Deports Honduran Migrants\"\n|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/07/18/obama-deports-honduran-migrants/|publisher=Counter Punch|date=23 July 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2014, an internal [[World Bank]] investigation said that the [[International Finance Corporation]] violated its own social and environmental rules in approving a $30m loan to Facuss\u00e9.<ref name='Woodsome01'>\n{{cite news \n| first = Kate \n| last = Woodsome \n| title = Audit slams World Bank agency: Investigation says loan to Honduran palm oil magnate, alleged to be linked to activist deaths, violated bank's rules. \n| date = January 12, 2014 \n| url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/audit-slams-world-bank-agency-201411274722345113.html \n| work = [[Al Jazeera English]] \n| accessdate = January 12, 2014 \n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140112230828/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/audit-slams-world-bank-agency-201411274722345113.html \n| archivedate = January 12, 2014\n}}\n</ref>  However, in its 2015 report on Honduras, the [[International Criminal Court]] stated that \"criminal organisations and international drug cartels are deeply involved in local businesses and criminal activities in the region and seem to be involved in most of the alleged crimes in the Bajo Agu\u00e1n, including unlawful occupations of land and robbery of African palm fruits, in order to retain control of the region and to continue to operate in total impunity.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=International Criminal Court|title=Situation in Honduras\n|date=October 2015|url=https://www.icc-cpi.int/iccdocs/otp/SAS-HON-Article_5_Report-Oct2015-ENG.PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Dinant became a provisional membership of the [[Voluntary Principles on Security and Human Rights]], an internationally recognized benchmark that strictly governs how organizations vet, recruit and train their security men and women, and how they engage with local communities.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dinant|title=Dinant Joins Voluntary Principles on Security and Human Rights|date=3 February 2020|url=https://www.dinant.com/noticias/dinant-joins-voluntary-principles-on-security-and-human-rights/?lang=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Voluntary Principles Initiative|title=VPI Welcomes New Members in 2019|accessdate=7 February 2020|url=https://mailchi.mp/7b9244a8353a/voluntary-principles-initiative-newsletter-january-2020?e=67de7c5e7a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[[Bolpress]], 4 June 2012, [http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum] {{in lang|es}}\n*[[Food First Information and Action Network]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120608041924/http://www.fian.org/resources/documents/others/honduras-human-rights-violations-in-bajo-aguan/pdf Human Rights Violations in Bajo Agu\u00e1n], July 2011\n*Ismael Moreno, ''Revista Envio'', [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/2933 Miguel Facuss\u00e9: Fencing off Paradise], Number 286, May 2005\n*[https://www.forbes.com.mx/miguel-facusse-el-genio-de-las-marcas-en-centroamerica// Interview by Forbes Mexico, 3 November 2014]\n*[http://www.dinant.com/ Corporacion Dinant website] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facusse Barjum, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Honduran businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Honduran people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Honduran expatriates in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum\n| image       =Miguel Facusse.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Miguel Facuss\u00e9, former Executive President, Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |1924|08|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Tegucigalpa]], [[Honduras]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2015|6|23|1924|8|14}}\n| alma mater  = [[University of Notre Dame]]\n| occupation  = President of ''Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant''\n\n}}\n\n'''Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum''' (August 14, 1924 \u2013 June 23, 2015) was a [[Honduras|Honduran]] businessman and landowner.<ref name=death>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.elheraldo.hn/pais/852053-214/muere-el-empresario-miguel-facusse\n|title=Muere el empresario hondure\u00f1o Miguel Facuss\u00e9\n|date=June 23, 2015\n|newspaper=El Heraldo\n|accessdate=June 23, 2015\n|language=Spanish\n}} \n</ref> He was Executive President of Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant, a consumer products manufacturing company he founded in Honduras in 1960. Dinant sells its products throughout [[Central America]] and the [[Dominican Republic]], and also exports to global markets.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Our History\n|url=http://www.dinant.com/index.php/en/quienes-somos|publisher=Corporacion Dinant\n|accessdate=January 31, 2015\n}}\n</ref> A 2006 study by the [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]] named Facuss\u00e9 one of the three \"most powerful men in Honduras\".<ref>Thelma Mej\u00eda, [[Inter Press Service]], 15 December 2006, [http://www.ipsnews.net/2006/12/honduras-governed-by-vested-interests/ HONDURAS: Governed by Vested Interests]</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was the chief economic advisor to President [[Roberto Suazo C\u00f3rdova]]<ref name=Rockwell/> during his term in office from 1982 to 1986 and vice-president of APROH, a \"right-wing grouping of business interests and members of the armed forces\"<ref name=Routledge2001/> from the early 1980s<ref name=Maolain/> to at least 2001. Facuss\u00e9 was married and had nine children.<ref name=LaTribuna/><ref name=RSF>[[Reporters without Borders]], 2 May 2012, [http://en.rsf.org/honduras-miguel-facusse-barjum-02-05-2012,42452.html Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum , Businessman and landowner, Honduras], accessed 11 October 2012</ref> His nephew, [[Carlos Roberto Flores]], was President of Honduras from 1998 to 2002. His son-in-law, [[Fredy Nasser]], is a prominent Honduran businessman. In May 2009, Facuss\u00e9 was awarded the ''Orden M\u00e9rito a la Democracia en el Grado de Gran Caballero'' by the [[Senate of Colombia]].<ref name=LaTribuna/> In August 2014, he was awarded the CEAL Founders' Award for his pioneering role in promoting business between Latin American nations.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=CEAL premia al empresario Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barj\u00fam\n|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2014/08/06/ceal-premia-al\u00e9\u00e9-empresario-miguel-facusse-barjum/\n|newspaper=La Tribuna\n|date=6 August 2014\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=MIGUEL FACUSSE BARJUM HONORED FOR LIFETIME CONTRIBUTION TO LATIN AMERICA\n|url=http://www.dinant.com/index.php/en/sala-de-prensa/comunicados/302-miguel-facusse-barjum-honored-for-lifetime-contribution-to-latin-america/\n|publisher=Corporacion Dinant\n|date=20 October 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMiguel Facuss\u00e9 was born in [[Tegucigalpa]], Honduras in 1924,<ref name=LaTribuna>{{in lang|es}} ''[[La Tribuna (Honduras)|La Tribuna]]'', 24 May 2009, [http://old.latribuna.hn/2009/05/24/post10064872/ Senado de Colombia condecora al empresario Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202110131/http://old.latribuna.hn/2009/05/24/post10064872/ |date=2014-02-02 }}</ref> the seventh of nine children of Nichol\u00e1s and Mar\u00eda Barjum de Facuss\u00e9 and his family is of [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] descent.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103>{{in lang|es}} {{cite news|title=Cohep reconoce trayectoria empresarial de Miguel Facuss\u00e9|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/11/03/cohep-reconoce-trayectoria-empresarial-de-miguel-facusse/|accessdate=25 January 2013|newspaper=[[La Tribuna]] (Honduras)|date=3 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112235946/http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/11/03/cohep-reconoce-trayectoria-empresarial-de-miguel-facusse/|archive-date=12 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFacuss\u00e9 earned a degree in [[aeronautical engineering]] in 1944 at the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilberto Nuila Coto, Msc.|first=Ram\u00f3n|title=Zacate Grande: Una gran visita|url=http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/04/15/zacate-grande-una-gran-visita/|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=La Tribuna|date=12 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123184414/http://www.latribuna.hn/2012/04/15/zacate-grande-una-gran-visita/|archive-date=23 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Malloy 2004\">{{cite book|last=Malloy|first=Edward A.|title=Monk's travels : People, Places, and Events|year=2004|publisher=Andrews McMeel Pub.|location=Kansas City|isbn=0-7407-4706-1|url=https://archive.org/details/monkstravels00edwa|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/monkstravels00edwa/page/94 94]}}</ref> Facuss\u00e9 hosted [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] University President [[Theodore Hesburgh|Rev. Theodore M. Hesburgh, CSC]] during a visit to Honduras in 1960 <ref>{{cite news|title=Our Family To The South|url=http://www.archives.nd.edu/Alumnus/VOL_0038/VOL_0038_ISSUE_0004.pdf|accessdate=25 January 2013|newspaper=Notre Dame Alumnus Magazine|date=November 1960}}</ref> and [[Edward Malloy|Rev. Edward \"Monk\" Malloy, CSC]] in 2003.<ref name=\"Malloy 2004\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Costa Rica===\nIn 1944, Facuss\u00e9 moved to Costa Rica, where he converted warplanes into commercial cargo airliners. He quickly became general manager of a multinational corporation that reconstructed and maintained wartime aircraft from all over the world.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103/>\n\n===1960s===\nAfter returning to Tegucigalpa, Facuss\u00e9 worked in his brother's textile company.  Facuss\u00e9 set up ''Qu\u00edmicas Dinant de Centroam\u00e9rica SA'' in July 1960. In the late 1960s, Facuss\u00e9 won contracts with [[Procter & Gamble]] to produce and distribute its products in Honduras, El Salvador, and Guatemala.<ref name=LaTribuna20121103/>\n\nIn 1969, Facuss\u00e9 was president of both the Honduras Industrial Association and the Central American Industrial Association.  At the time, Facuss\u00e9 owned Qu\u00edmicas Dinant, a company that made soaps and detergents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class Notes for Class of 1944|url=http://www.archives.nd.edu/Alumnus/VOL_0047/VOL_0047_ISSUE_0006.pdf|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=Notre Dame Alumnus Magazine|date=September 1969}}</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nIn the 1970s, Facuss\u00e9 created a small factory making detergents and soaps for Qu\u00edmicas Dinant. He did so with support from the private international banking sector and credit from the Corporaci\u00f3n Nacional de Inversiones ([[CONADI]]), created by the state in 1974 as part of the strategy to consolidate the new Industrial Model for Substituting Imports (ISI).<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum\n|url=http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html\n|work=Historical Survey|publisher=Bolpress \n|via=Derechos.org)\n|accessdate=28 January 2013\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nIn the early 1980s, Facuss\u00e9 was the chief economic advisor to President [[Roberto Suazo C\u00f3rdova]]<ref name=Rockwell/> (in office 1982 to 1986). During this time Facuss\u00e9 helped his nephew, [[Carlos Roberto Flores]], (who later went on to become president of Honduras) become a political advisor to Suazo.<ref name=Rockwell>Rick Rockwell, Noreene Janus (2003), ''Media Power in Central America'', [[University of Illinois Press]], p21</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, Facuss\u00e9 was also vice-president of the ''Asociaci\u00f3n para el Progreso de Honduras'' (APROH), an organization officially founded in January 1983<ref>Henry W. Degenhardt (1988), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=DVmGAAAAMAAJ Revolutionary and dissident movements: an international guide]'', Longman p149</ref> linking business leaders and military personnel (head of the armed forces [[Gustavo \u00c1lvarez Mart\u00ednez]] was elected its first president).<ref name=Maolain>Listed as \"vice-president\" alongside \"Gen. (retd) Gustavo Alvarez Martinez\" as \"leader\" in Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Maol\u00e1in (ed, 1985), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=GxUPAAAAYAAJ Latin American Political Movements]'', Longman, p159</ref><ref>James D. Rudolph (1983),[https://books.google.com/books?id=9tJqAAAAMAAJ Honduras, a country study: Volume 550, Issues 151\u2013152], American University (Washington, D.C.). Foreign Area Studies, United States. Dept. of the Army, p172</ref><ref>{{in lang|es}} [[Bolpress]], 4 June 2012, [http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum]</ref><ref>Described as \"APROH co-ordinator\" in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=E6IpAQAAIAAJ Business Week, Issues 2788\u20132796]'', [[McGraw-Hill]], 1983, p75</ref><ref>Listed as \"vice-president\" in Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Maol\u00e1in (1987), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=d9wPAQAAMAAJ The radical right: a world directory]'', Longman, p152</ref> A \"widely publicised memorandum\" by Facuss\u00e9 \"argued that the only way out of the national crisis was to 'sell Honduras to the foreign investor'\".<ref>Richard Lapper, James Painter (1985), Latin America Bureau, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=2doXAAAAYAAJ Honduras, state for sale]\", Latin America Bureau special brief, p100</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was still listed as Vice-President of APROH in 2001.<ref name=Routledge2001>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=o9ODxqsr-dIC South America, Central America and the Caribbean]\", ''Regional Surveys of the World Series'', 10th Edition 2002, [[Routledge]] 2001, p496</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nFacuss\u00e9 was president of the Cressida Corporation, which in the 1990s received a $55m investment loan from the World Bank.<ref>''Revista Envio'', [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/3010 Maquila*: The Swallow That Lays Golden Eggs], Number 194, September 1997.</ref> In 2000 Facuss\u00e9 sold Cressida, which had subsidiaries throughout Central America and was at the time described as \"the biggest food and cleaning products manufacturer in Honduras\" to [[Unilever]] for $322m for an estimated net profit to Facuss\u00e9 of $120m.<ref name=EIU>\n{{cite web\n|work=[[Economist Intelligence Unit]]\n|date=11 May 2000\n|url= http://www.eiu.com/index.asp?layout=VWArticleVW3&article_id=904744890\n|title=Article Country Briefing: Honduras finance: Regional links attract foreign direct investments\n}}\n</ref> Facuss\u00e9 had previously sold the brand ''Magia Blanca'' and others to [[Procter & Gamble]] for over $25m.<ref name=EIU/>\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2011, Facuss\u00e9 remained the owner of Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant, which owned over 22,000 acres of palm plantations in [[Bajo Agu\u00e1n]].<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', September 15, 2011 [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/16/world/americas/honduras-land-conflicts-highlight-polarization.html?pagewanted=all In Honduras, Land Struggles Highlight Post-Coup Polarization]</ref> Facuss\u00e9 was described in 2012 by [[Reporters without Borders]] as having, \"a private militia that can count on support from the police and army to impose his will\".<ref name=RSF/> Reporters without Borders previously had called upon Facuss\u00e9 to respond publicly after the president of La Voz de [[Zacate Grande]], a radio station involved in a land struggle against Facuss\u00e9, was shot in 2011.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.rsf-es.org/news/honduras-herido-de-bala-en-un-atentado-el-director-de-la-voz-de-zacate-grande/\n|title=Herido de bala en un atentado el director de La Voz de Zacate Grande\n|date=17 March 2011\n|publisher=[[Reporters without Borders]]\n|accessdate=2013-11-20\n}} (Spanish)\n</ref> Accusations that Facuss\u00e9's militia had killed agricultural workers who had occupied his land led to the withdrawal in 2011 of a $20m investment loan from the German,<ref name=TheNation>\n{{cite news\n|author=Dana Frank\n|work=[[The Nation]]\n|date=21 October 2011\n|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/164120/wikileaks-honduras-us-linked-brutal-businessman \n|title=WikiLeaks Honduras: US Linked to Brutal Businessman\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|author1=Mathew Carr\n|author2=Catherine Airlie\n|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]\n|date=21 April 2011\n|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-21/-misleading-claims-harm-honduras-emissions-project-owner-executive-says.html\n|title=\u2018Misleading\u2019 Claims Harm Honduras Emissions-Project Owner, Executive Says\n}}\n</ref> and to [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]] cancelling the purchase of [[carbon credit]]s from Dinant.<ref name=Ramsey>\n{{cite web\n|author=Geoffrey Ramsey\n|work=[[InSight Crime]]\n|date=18 May 2012\n|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/honduran-tycoon-accused-of-drug-ties-named-press-predator\n|title=Honduran Tycoon Accused of Drug Ties Named 'Press Predator'\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHowever the [[United Nations]] continued to back two Dinant palm-oil-waste-to-[[biogas]] projects through its [[Clean Development Mechanism]].<ref name=Kryt/> Corporaci\u00f3n Dinant denied committing [[human rights]] violations or forcibly evicting intruders from its land. It claimed that \"externally funded armed groups, with no interest in farming, are using the conflicts in Honduras for wider political ends by encouraging the illegal seizure of private lands.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title=Dinant has never committed human rights violations against protesters\n|url=http://timeli.info/item/1613541/The_Guardian_World_News/Dinant_has_never_committed_human_rights_violations_against_protesters____guardianletters___World_...\n|newspaper=The Guardian\n|date=7 May 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\nMedia reports and leaked US Embassy cables published by [[WikiLeaks]] suggest that an airstrip on Facuss\u00e9's property has been used for to transit cocaine.<ref name=TheNation/><ref name=Ramsey/><ref name=Kryt>\n{{cite news\n|author=Jeremy Kryt\n|work=[[In These Times]]\n|date=30 November 2011\n|url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/12285/carbon_credits_in_the_valley_of_death/ \n|title=Carbon Credits in the \u2018Valley of Death\u2019\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|author=hondurasnews\n|url=http://www.hondurasnews.com/wikileaks-cable-re-honduras-031904/ \n|title=WikiLeaks Cable Re: Honduras 03/19/04}}\n</ref> Facuss\u00e9 denied ever having been involved in any activities related to drug trafficking, claiming instead to help drug enforcement authorities by reporting illegal activities on Dinant\u2019s property.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Re: Counter Punch article on \"Obama Deports Honduran Migrants\"\n|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/07/18/obama-deports-honduran-migrants/|publisher=Counter Punch|date=23 July 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2014, an internal [[World Bank]] investigation said that the [[International Finance Corporation]] violated its own social and environmental rules in approving a $30m loan to Facuss\u00e9.<ref name='Woodsome01'>\n{{cite news \n| first = Kate \n| last = Woodsome \n| title = Audit slams World Bank agency: Investigation says loan to Honduran palm oil magnate, alleged to be linked to activist deaths, violated bank's rules. \n| date = January 12, 2014 \n| url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/audit-slams-world-bank-agency-201411274722345113.html \n| work = [[Al Jazeera English]] \n| accessdate = January 12, 2014 \n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140112230828/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/audit-slams-world-bank-agency-201411274722345113.html \n| archivedate = January 12, 2014\n}}\n</ref>  However, in its 2015 report on Honduras, the [[International Criminal Court]] stated that \"criminal organisations and international drug cartels are deeply involved in local businesses and criminal activities in the region and seem to be involved in most of the alleged crimes in the Bajo Agu\u00e1n, including unlawful occupations of land and robbery of African palm fruits, in order to retain control of the region and to continue to operate in total impunity.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=International Criminal Court|title=Situation in Honduras\n|date=October 2015|url=https://www.icc-cpi.int/iccdocs/otp/SAS-HON-Article_5_Report-Oct2015-ENG.PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Dinant became a provisional membership of the [[Voluntary Principles on Security and Human Rights]], an internationally recognized benchmark that strictly governs how organizations vet, recruit and train their security men and women, and how they engage with local communities.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dinant|title=Dinant Joins Voluntary Principles on Security and Human Rights|date=3 February 2020|url=https://www.dinant.com/noticias/dinant-joins-voluntary-principles-on-security-and-human-rights/?lang=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Voluntary Principles Initiative|title=VPI Welcomes New Members in 2019|accessdate=7 February 2020|url=https://mailchi.mp/7b9244a8353a/voluntary-principles-initiative-newsletter-january-2020?e=67de7c5e7a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[[Bolpress]], 4 June 2012, [http://www.derechos.org/nizkor/honduras/doc/facusse.html Ra\u00edces hist\u00f3ricas de la fortuna de Miguel Facuss\u00e9 Barjum] {{in lang|es}}\n*[[Food First Information and Action Network]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120608041924/http://www.fian.org/resources/documents/others/honduras-human-rights-violations-in-bajo-aguan/pdf Human Rights Violations in Bajo Agu\u00e1n], July 2011\n*Ismael Moreno, ''Revista Envio'', [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/2933 Miguel Facuss\u00e9: Fencing off Paradise], Number 286, May 2005\n*[https://www.forbes.com.mx/miguel-facusse-el-genio-de-las-marcas-en-centroamerica// Interview by Forbes Mexico, 3 November 2014]\n*[http://www.dinant.com/ Corporacion Dinant website] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facusse Barjum, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Honduran businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Honduran people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Honduran expatriates in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-La Tribuna", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_Facuss%C3%A9_Barjum"}
{"title_page": "Geo Super", "text_new": "{{Infobox TV channel\n| name = Geo Super\n| logofile = Geo Super logo.png\n| launch = September 2007;13 years ago\n| owner = [[Geo TV]]\n| slogan = Jeet Kay Geo<br>Geo Tou Aesay\n| picture format = [[4:3]] ([[576i]], [[SDTV]])<br>[[MPEG-3]]/HD\n| headquarters = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]\n| sister names =\n\n| web = [http://www.geosuper.tv geosuper.tv]\n| sat serv 1 = [[PAKSAT]] (Pakistan)|\n| sat chan 1 = 3797 MHz 3/4|\n| sat serv 2 = [[Intelsat|Intelsat 10]] (Aisa)|\n| sat chan 2 = 3333-2/3| \n| sat serv 3 = [[Dish Network]] <small>([[United States|USA]])</small>\n| sat chan 3 = Channel 747 \n| sat serv 4 = [[TrueVisions]] <small>([[Thailand]])</small>\n| sat chan 4 = Channel 873 \n| adsl serv 1 = [[PTCL Smart TV]] (Pakistan)|\n| adsl chan 1 = Channel 76|\n| online serv 1 = Live streaming\n| online chan 1 = [http://geosuper.tv/live/ Geo Super live]\n|language=[[Urdu]]<br>[[English language|English]]}}\n\n'''Geo Super''' is the first 24-hour [[Karachi]] based Pakistani channel dedicated to the world of sports. It is owned by the [[Jang Group of Newspapers]]. Geo Super was launched September 2007. It retains exclusive broadcasting for many sporting events such as cricket, football, hockey, wrestling and others.\n\nIn May 2018, the channel shut down its live coverage and fired its employees including sports journalists Naseem Rajput and Waheed Khan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/05/09/geo-super-shuts-down-live-transmission/|title=Geo Super shuts down live transmission - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n==Launch==\nIn late September 2007, [[Geo Television Network]] launched Geo Super. Geo Super broadcasts sports events, focusing mainly on [[cricket]], with secondary focuses on [[association football|football]] and [[field hockey]]. Shortly after its launch, Geo Super managed to secure the television rights of the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] tournaments for the next five years covering all major cricketing events like [[ICC Cricket World Cup]], [[ICC Champions Trophy]], [[Twenty20 World Cup]], [[Faysal Bank T20 Cup]] and [[ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup]].\n\n==Subscription==\nGeo Super is an encrypted channel and is only available in [[Pakistan]] (legally) free for cable operators. The whole Geo Network uses Conax encryption with KAON set-top boxes.\n\n==Coverage==\nGeo Super covered all major events in the recent years cricketing world, boxing, hockey, football and tennis. Events like [[The Ashes]], [[ICC Cricket World Cup]], [[ICC World Twenty20]], [[ICC Champions Trophy]], [[Faysal Bank T20 Cup|Pakistan's domestic T20 Cup]], [[Pakistan Super League|PSL]], [[Bangladesh Premier League]] and Pakistan Boxing League to name a few. \n\nRecently, in collaboration with [[Pakistan Football Federation]], Geo Super launched the [[Geo Super Football League|Super Football League]] competition involving the 5 big cities of [[Pakistan]] having their own football clubs in a league format competition for the betterment of football in Pakistan. [[Geo Super Football League|Super Football League]] and many others and will air more of the domestic sports in the future. It bought rights to show Brazilian League 2011/12 live on the channel. \n\nSince Geo Super is a Pakistan-based sports channel, it has focused on the domestic sports in the country and has aired events like 2007-08 RBS Twenty20 Cup and 2008-09 RBS Twenty20 Cup, 2008-09 RBS Pentangular Cup One Day, [[2009\u201310 RBS Twenty-20 Cup]], [[2010\u201311 Faysal Bank Twenty-20 Cup]], [[Faysal Bank Super 8 T20 Cup 2011]].\n\nThe 52nd National Badminton Championship, 34th National Snooker Championship, 2nd Ranking Snooker Championship, Pentangular 6 Red Snooker Team Series, Shandur Polo Cup 2008, MAC Kyokushin, Spring Blossom Polo Festival, 16th National Skiing Championship.\n\nAfter having a deal with [[Pro Wrestling Federation|Pro Wrestling Federation of Pakistan]], [[Geo Super]] aired PWFP's first ever pay-per-view \"[[PWFP Rumble in Pakistan|Rumble in Pakistan]]\" which involved international superstars and local superstars. The event had their main event the first ever \"Rumble Battle Match\" in [[Pakistan]]. which was for the inaugural [[PWFP Hardcore Championship]]. International superstar Sammy Guevara won the [[PWFP Ultimate Championship]] after defeating former champion Raja Naveed. The event was aired on Geo Super at 2019 Eid-ul-Fitr.\n\n=== Cricket ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!League\n!Country\n!Latest season\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Super League|PSL]]\n|[[Pakistan]]\n|[[2020 Pakistan Super League|2020]]\n|-\n|[[Qatar T10 League|QT10]]\n|[[Qatar]]\n|[[2019 Qatar T10 League|2019]]\n|-\n|[[Mzansi Super League|MSL]]\n|[[South Africa]]\n|[[2019 Mzansi Super League|2019]]\n|-\n|[[Bangladesh Premier League|BPL]]\n|[[Bangladesh]]\n|[[2019-20 Bangladesh Premier League|2019-20]]\n|}\n\n=== Wrestling ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Promotion\n!Country\n!Latest event\n|-\n|[[Pro Wrestling Federation of Pakistan|PWFP]]\n|[[Pakistan]]\n|[[Rumble in Pakistan]]\n|}\n\n== Featured programmes ==\n\n=== Score ===\nScore is the most populest show of Geo Super which is hosted by Yahya Hussaini. Sometimes, [[Sikandar Bakht]] and [[Shoaib Akhtar]] accompany him in the show. The show also got famous become the Yahya Hussaini curse. The curse was that which ever cricketer Yahya Hussaini took a photo with, he or his team played really bad in the upcoming matches. The show mainly covers cricket news but sometimes also covers other sports.\n\n==Controversies==\n\n=== ICC World Cup 2011 dispute ===\nThe 2011 World Cup was the second to be broadcast by Geo Super. However [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA) terminated its contract for hosting the world cup. After taking the case to the Supreme Court, Geo was re-awarded the sole and exclusive rights to host the tournament.<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=9978 Geo Super rights for WC matches restored]. Thenews.com.pk. Retrieved on 2013-12-23.</ref> Geo also announced that they had hired former Pakistan captain [[Imran Khan]] as a commentator.<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=3200&Cat=13&dt=1/9/2011 Imran Khan signs with Geo Super for World Cup 2011]. Thenews.com.pk. Retrieved on 2013-12-23.</ref>\n\n===Geo Super taken off-air===\nOn 7 April 2011, Geo Super was banned from broadcasting in Pakistan by PEMRA due to the disputes relating to broadcast from another country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Govt has Geo Super turned off |url=http://www.geo.tv/4-6-2011/80089.htm |publisher=[[GEO TV]] |accessdate=2011-05-05 |date=6 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410003123/http://www.geo.tv/4-6-2011/80089.htm |archivedate=2011-04-10 }}</ref> But after two months broadcasting ban was uplifted.\n\n=== Reaction after 14 May 2014 ===\nOn 14 May 2014 after an alleged attempt of blasphemy by [[Geo TV]] several internet websites decided to boycott Geo Super and decided to take the network off their streaming platforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cric-live.co/live/geo-super-live-streaming-21414/|title=cric-live.co|website=cric-live.co}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Geo Television Network]]\n* [[Jang Group of Newspapers]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.geosuper.tv}}\n* {{facebook|geosuper|''Geo Super''}}\n* {{Twitter |name=''Geo Super''}}\n* [https://epicsat.com/geo-super-biss-key/ Geo Super Frequency]\n {{Television in Pakistan |state=autocollapse}} \n{{GEO TV}}\n{{Boxing on television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geo Super}}\n[[Category:Geo TV]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sports television in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Lahore]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox TV channel\n| name = Geo Super\n| logofile = Geo Super logo.png\n| launch = September 2007;13 years ago\n| owner = [[Geo TV]]\n| slogan = Jeet Kay Geo<br>Geo Tou Aesay\n| picture format = [[4:3]] ([[576i]], [[SDTV]])<br>[[MPEG-3]]/HD\n| headquarters = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]\n| sister names =\n\n| web = [http://www.geosuper.tv geosuper.tv]\n| sat serv 1 = [[PAKSAT]] (Pakistan)|\n| sat chan 1 = 3797 MHz 3/4|\n| sat serv 2 = [[Intelsat|Intelsat 10]] (Aisa)|\n| sat chan 2 = 3333-2/3| \n| sat serv 3 = [[Dish Network]] <small>([[United States|USA]])</small>\n| sat chan 3 = Channel 747 \n| sat serv 4 = [[TrueVisions]] <small>([[Thailand]])</small>\n| sat chan 4 = Channel 873 \n| adsl serv 1 = [[PTCL Smart TV]] (Pakistan)|\n| adsl chan 1 = Channel 76|\n| online serv 1 = Live streaming\n| online chan 1 = [http://geosuper.tv/live/ Geo Super live]\n|language=[[Urdu]]<br>[[English language|English]]}}\n\n'''Geo Super''' is the first 24-hour [[Karachi]] based Pakistani channel dedicated to the world of sports. It is owned by the [[Jang Group of Newspapers]]. Geo Super was launched September 2007. It retains exclusive broadcasting for many sporting events such as cricket, football, hockey, wrestling and others.\n\nIn May 2018, the channel shut down its live coverage and fired its employees including sports journalists Naseem Rajput and Waheed Khan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/05/09/geo-super-shuts-down-live-transmission/|title=Geo Super shuts down live transmission - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n==Launch==\nIn late September 2007, [[Geo Television Network]] launched Geo Super. Geo Super broadcasts sports events, focusing mainly on [[cricket]], with secondary focuses on [[association football|football]] and [[field hockey]]. Shortly after its launch, Geo Super managed to secure the television rights of the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] tournaments for the next five years covering all major cricketing events like [[ICC Cricket World Cup]], [[ICC Champions Trophy]], [[Twenty20 World Cup]], [[Faysal Bank T20 Cup]] and [[ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup]].\n\n==Subscription==\nGeo Super is an encrypted channel and is only available in [[Pakistan]] (legally) free for cable operators. The whole Geo Network uses Conax encryption with KAON set-top boxes.\n\n==Coverage==\nGeo Super covered all major events in the recent years cricketing world, boxing, hockey, football and tennis. Events like [[The Ashes]], [[ICC Cricket World Cup]], [[ICC World Twenty20]], [[ICC Champions Trophy]], [[Faysal Bank T20 Cup|Pakistan's domestic T20 Cup]], [[Pakistan Super League|PSL]], [[Bangladesh Premier League]] and Pakistan Boxing League to name a few. \n\nRecently, in collaboration with [[Pakistan Football Federation]], Geo Super launched the [[Geo Super Football League|Super Football League]] competition involving the 5 big cities of [[Pakistan]] having their own football clubs in a league format competition for the betterment of football in Pakistan. [[Geo Super Football League|Super Football League]] and many others and will air more of the domestic sports in the future. It bought rights to show Brazilian League 2011/12 live on the channel. \n\nSince Geo Super is a Pakistan-based sports channel, it has focused on the domestic sports in the country and has aired events like 2007-08 RBS Twenty20 Cup and 2008-09 RBS Twenty20 Cup, 2008-09 RBS Pentangular Cup One Day, [[2009\u201310 RBS Twenty-20 Cup]], [[2010\u201311 Faysal Bank Twenty-20 Cup]], [[Faysal Bank Super 8 T20 Cup 2011]].\n\nThe 52nd National Badminton Championship, 34th National Snooker Championship, 2nd Ranking Snooker Championship, Pentangular 6 Red Snooker Team Series, Shandur Polo Cup 2008, MAC Kyokushin, Spring Blossom Polo Festival, 16th National Skiing Championship.\n\nAfter having a deal with [[Pro Wrestling Federation|Pro Wrestling Federation of Pakistan]], [[Geo Super]] aired PWFP's first ever pay-per-view \"[[PWFP Rumble in Pakistan|Rumble in Pakistan]]\" which involved international superstars and local superstars. The event had their main event the first ever \"Rumble Battle Match\" in [[Pakistan]]. which was for the inaugural [[PWFP Hardcore Championship]]. International superstar Sammy Guevara won the [[PWFP Ultimate Championship]] after defeating former champion Raja Naveed. The event was aired on Geo Super at 2019 Eid-ul-Fitr.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n|}\n\n=== Cricket ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!League\n!Country\n!Latest season\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Super League|PSL]]\n|[[Pakistan]]\n|[[2020 Pakistan Super League|2020]]\n|-\n|[[Qatar T10 League|QT10]]\n|[[Qatar]]\n|[[2019 Qatar T10 League|2019]]\n|-\n|[[Mzansi Super League|MSL]]\n|[[South Africa]]\n|[[2019 Mzansi Super League|2019]]\n|-\n|[[Bangladesh Premier League|BPL]]\n|[[Bangladesh]]\n|[[2019-20 Bangladesh Premier League|2019-20]]\n|}\n\n=== Wrestling ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Promotion\n!Country\n!Latest event\n|-\n|[[Pro Wrestling Federation|PWFP]]\n|[[Pakistan]]\n|[[Rumble in Pakistan]]\n|}\n\n== Featured programmes ==\n\n=== Score ===\nScore is the most populest show of Geo Super which is hosted by Yahya Hussaini. Sometimes, [[Sikandar Bakht]] and [[Shoaib Akhtar]] accompany him in the show. The show also got famous become the Yahya Hussaini curse. The curse was that which ever cricketer Yahya Hussaini took a photo with, he or his team played really bad in the upcoming matches. The show mainly covers cricket news but sometimes also covers other sports.\n\n==Controversies==\n\n=== ICC World Cup 2011 dispute ===\nThe 2011 World Cup was the second to be broadcast by Geo Super. However [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA) terminated its contract for hosting the world cup. After taking the case to the Supreme Court, Geo was re-awarded the sole and exclusive rights to host the tournament.<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=9978 Geo Super rights for WC matches restored]. Thenews.com.pk. Retrieved on 2013-12-23.</ref> Geo also announced that they had hired former Pakistan captain [[Imran Khan]] as a commentator.<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=3200&Cat=13&dt=1/9/2011 Imran Khan signs with Geo Super for World Cup 2011]. Thenews.com.pk. Retrieved on 2013-12-23.</ref>\n\n===Geo Super taken off-air===\nOn 7 April 2011, Geo Super was banned from broadcasting in Pakistan by PEMRA due to the disputes relating to broadcast from another country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Govt has Geo Super turned off |url=http://www.geo.tv/4-6-2011/80089.htm |publisher=[[GEO TV]] |accessdate=2011-05-05 |date=6 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410003123/http://www.geo.tv/4-6-2011/80089.htm |archivedate=2011-04-10 }}</ref> But after two months broadcasting ban was uplifted.\n\n=== Reaction after 14 May 2014 ===\nOn 14 May 2014 after an alleged attempt of blasphemy by [[Geo TV]] several internet websites decided to boycott Geo Super and decided to take the network off their streaming platforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cric-live.co/live/geo-super-live-streaming-21414/|title=cric-live.co|website=cric-live.co}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Geo Television Network]]\n* [[Jang Group of Newspapers]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.geosuper.tv}}\n* {{facebook|geosuper|''Geo Super''}}\n* {{Twitter |name=''Geo Super''}}\n* [https://epicsat.com/geo-super-biss-key/ Geo Super Frequency]\n {{Television in Pakistan |state=autocollapse}} \n{{GEO TV}}\n{{Boxing on television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geo Super}}\n[[Category:Geo TV]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sports television in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Lahore]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2006]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "PWFP", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geo_Super"}
{"title_page": "SJ Y3", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Train\n| background =\n| name = Y3\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| interiorimage =\n| interiorcaption =\n| service =  1966\u20131990\n\n| manufacturer = [[ASEA]], [[Linke-Hofmann]]\n| factory =\n| family =\n| refurbishment =\n| replaced =\n\n| formation =\n| fleetnumbers = 1261\u20131266\n| operator = [[Statens J\u00e4rnv\u00e4gar]]\n| depots =\n| lines =\n\n| yearconstruction = 1966\u201367\n| yearservice =\n| yearscrapped =\n| numberconstruction =\n| numberbuilt =  6\n| numberservice =\n| numberscrapped =\n\n| carbody =\n| carlength = {{convert|19,620|mm|ftin|1|abbr=on}} ([[Rail motor|motor units]])<br>{{convert|21,000|mm|ftin|1|abbr=on}} (trailer)\n| width =\n| height =\n| floorheight =\n| platformheight =\n| entrylevelorstep =\n| art-sections =\n| doors =\n\n| maxspeed = {{convert|140|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|61.9|t|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| capacity =\n| acceleration =\n| deceleration =\n| traction =\n| engine = [[Deutz AG]]\n| poweroutput = {{convert|910|kW|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| transmission =\n| aux =\n| powersupply =\n| gauge = {{track gauge|sg}}\n| electricsystem =\n| brakes =\n| safety =\n}}\n\n'''Y3''' was a series of [[diesel multiple unit|diesel]] [[railcar]]s operated by [[Statens J\u00e4rnv\u00e4gar]] (SJ) of Sweden. Six units were delivered by [[Linke-Hofmann]] of Germany in 1966\u201367, with electrical equipment supplied by [[ASEA]]. They remained in service until 1990, serving first on the unelectrified services [[Stockholm]] \u2013 [[Mora (locality)|Mora]] and [[Malm\u00f6]] \u2013 [[Karlskrona]], later on [[Ystadbanan]].\n\nThe Y3 served the same purpose as the electric [[SJ X9|X9]]-series. A variation of configurations was used, with the production consisting of six [[Rail motor|motor cars]], two [[Control car (rail)|cab cars]] and eleven trailers. With motor cars on each end the Y3 could have six trailers between. Although considered to be the first [[Bilevel rail car|double-decker]] train used in Sweden, only the first and last cars of a Y3 train were built to a design somewhat resembling a [[dome car]], whereas the middle coaches were all single-decker (unlike in the [[SJ X40|X40]] and [[Stadler KISS|Stadler DOSTO]]). The series was prone to fires, since the cooling system didn't work sufficiently for the extremely powerful [[Deutz AG|Deutz]] diesel engines introduced in place of the slower and less powerful [[Rolls-Royce Limited|Rolls-Royce]] engines. This was solved through rebuilding the cooling system in the 1970s. Some of the bilevel rail cars were taken out of service in 1982 when the Y3 series was relegated to local traffic on the Malm\u00f6 \u2013 Ystad \u2013 Tomelilla route, with the last Y3 coaches retired in 1990.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jarnvag.net/vagnguide/y3 J\u00e4rnv\u00e4g.net on Y3] {{in lang|sv}}\n\n{{Swedish railway stock}}\n\n[[Category:SJ multiple units|Y03]]\n[[Category:Multiple units of Sweden|Y03]]\n[[Category:Double-decker rail vehicles]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1966]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Train\n| background =\n| name = Y3\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| interiorimage =\n| interiorcaption =\n| service =  1966\u20131990\n\n| manufacturer = [[ASEA]], [[Linke-Hofmann]]\n| factory =\n| family =\n| refurbishment =\n| replaced =\n\n| formation =\n| fleetnumbers = 1261\u20131266\n| operator = [[Statens J\u00e4rnv\u00e4gar]]\n| depots =\n| lines =\n\n| yearconstruction = 1966\u201367\n| yearservice =\n| yearscrapped =\n| numberconstruction =\n| numberbuilt =  6\n| numberservice =\n| numberscrapped =\n\n| carbody =\n| carlength = {{convert|19,620|mm|ftin|1|abbr=on}} ([[Rail motor|motor units]])<br>{{convert|21,000|mm|ftin|1|abbr=on}} (trailer)\n| width =\n| height =\n| floorheight =\n| platformheight =\n| entrylevelorstep =\n| art-sections =\n| doors =\n\n| maxspeed = {{convert|140|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|61.9|t|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| capacity =\n| acceleration =\n| deceleration =\n| traction =\n| engine = [[Deutz AG]]\n| poweroutput = {{convert|910|kW|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| transmission =\n| aux =\n| powersupply =\n| gauge = {{track gauge|sg}}\n| electricsystem =\n| brakes =\n| safety =\n}}\n\n'''Y3''' was a series of [[diesel multiple unit|diesel]] [[railcar]]s operated by [[Statens J\u00e4rnv\u00e4gar]] (SJ) of Sweden. Six units were delivered by [[Linke-Hofmann]] of Germany in 1966\u201367, with electrical equipment supplied by [[ASEA]]. They remained in service until 1990, serving first on the unelectrified services [[Stockholm]] \u2013 [[Mora (locality)|Mora]] and [[Malm\u00f6]] \u2013 [[Karlskrona]], later on [[Ystadbanan]].\n\nThe Y3 served the same purpose as the electric [[SJ X9|X9]]-series. A variation of configurations was used, with the production consisting of six [[Rail motor|motor cars]], two [[Control car (rail)|cab cars]] and eleven trailers. With motor cars on each end the Y3 could have six trailers between. Although considered to be the first [[Bilevel rail car|double-decker]] train used in Sweden, only the first and last cars of a Y3 train were built to a design somewhat resembling a [[dome car]], whereas the middle coaches were all single-decker (unlike in the [[SJ X40|X40]] and [[Stadler KISS|Stadler DOSTO]]). The series was prone to fires, since the cooling system didn't work sufficiently for the extremely powerful [[Deutz AG|Deutz]] diesel engines introduced in place of the slower and less powerful [[Rolls-Royce]] engines. This was solved through rebuilding the cooling system in the 1970s. Some of the bilevel rail cars were taken out of service in 1982 when the Y3 series was relegated to local traffic on the Malm\u00f6 \u2013 Ystad \u2013 Tomelilla route, with the last Y3 coaches retired in 1990.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jarnvag.net/vagnguide/y3 J\u00e4rnv\u00e4g.net on Y3] {{in lang|sv}}\n\n{{Swedish railway stock}}\n\n[[Category:SJ multiple units|Y03]]\n[[Category:Multiple units of Sweden|Y03]]\n[[Category:Double-decker rail vehicles]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1966]]\n", "name_user": "LittleWink", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repairing links toRolls-Royce(link changed toRolls-Royce Limited)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SJ_Y3"}
